WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
[Amit Varma]: Ever since our independence 73 years ago, the neighbor we've been obsessed with is Pakistan.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:17.120
[Amit Varma]: This is not surprising as until recently we lived in the same damn house and we were the

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:18.120
[Amit Varma]: same damn people.

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:23.280
[Amit Varma]: With the history we have had and the violence of our separation, it is natural that India

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:26.240
[Amit Varma]: and Pakistan should think so much about each other.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:30.920
[Amit Varma]: But in all this time, we haven't thought much about another neighbor, a country bigger than

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:37.160
[Amit Varma]: us, an economy more prosperous, a civilization just as old, a neighbor separated by just

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:38.220
[Amit Varma]: the Himalayas.

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:43.960
[Amit Varma]: In the geopolitics of our popular culture, the enemy is always Pakistan, never China.

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:46.520
[Amit Varma]: But China is the big brother of our neighborhood.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And hey, they did actually meet us in a war and we are embroiled in multiple disputes

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:52.920
[Amit Varma]: with them.

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:57.440
[Amit Varma]: Should we be worried?

00:00:57.440 --> 00:01:02.880
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:03.880
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:09.400
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bhadwa.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.040
[Amit Varma]: We can't understand the present without understanding the past.

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:20.040
[Amit Varma]: And given the recent bust-ups between China and India in the Galwan Valley, we do need

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:22.640
[Amit Varma]: to understand what is going on.

00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Today's episode looks back at the history of the interactions between China and India.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:33.640
[Amit Varma]: First, a bird's eye view that spans centuries and looks at the difference between our civilizational

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:34.840
[Amit Varma]: approaches.

00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:39.320
[Amit Varma]: Then we zoom into British times, in which many of our current border disputes were born,

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:43.380
[Amit Varma]: as the British Empire grappled with China and the questions of how far they could go

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:45.400
[Amit Varma]: and how far they wanted to go.

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:50.800
[Amit Varma]: Then we zoom in further to our independence and the changed dynamics of the Cold War.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:56.120
[Amit Varma]: We see why the 1962 war happened and how the aftermath unfolded.

00:01:56.120 --> 00:02:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And then, through the decades, we come to these present times, when China asserts its

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:05.240
[Amit Varma]: strength as India struggles to define its place in the world.

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:09.520
[Amit Varma]: My guests today are Hamsini Hariharan and Shibani Mehta.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Hamsini is the host of The States of Anarchy, a podcast on global affairs and foreign policy.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:17.840
[Amit Varma]: She is a Yenching Scholar at Peking University.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:21.000
[Amit Varma]: She researches on Chinese politics and policy.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.640
[Amit Varma]: She used to be a research associate at the Takshashila Institution and the assistant

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: editor at Pragati at the time when I was the editor there, and our entire editorial team

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:33.600
[Amit Varma]: was basically the two of us.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:39.920
[Amit Varma]: UNESCO recently certified us as the greatest two-person editorial team in world history.

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:43.700
[Amit Varma]: Shibani is a foreign affairs researcher and writer based in Bangalore.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:49.160
[Amit Varma]: She contributes to Eye on China, a weekly bulletin offering news and analysis related

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:50.420
[Amit Varma]: to the Middle Kingdom.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:54.760
[Amit Varma]: She is writing about China's engagement in the Indian subcontinent for a forthcoming

00:02:54.760 --> 00:03:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Routledge publication, along with Manoj Kevalramani, who has been on the show a few times to talk

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:01.760
[Amit Varma]: about China.

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Those episodes will be linked from the show notes.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Before I begin my conversation with Hamsini and Shibani though, let's take a quick commercial

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:12.320
[Amit Varma]: break.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:15.860
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Seen and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:17.160
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.200
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and the Unseen has been a labour of love for me.

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:25.800
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:26.800
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:32.120
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Although The Seen and the Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:40.780
[Amit Varma]: up to the insane engagement level of podcasts, and I do many many hours of deep research

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:46.880
[Amit Varma]: for each episode, besides all the logistics of producing the show myself, scheduling guests,

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:50.720
[Amit Varma]: booking studios, paying technicians, the travel and so on.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.640
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this, for every episode of The Seen and the Unseen that you

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:04.880
[Amit Varma]: enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth.

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:10.800
[Amit Varma]: You can do this by heading over to seenunseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:11.800
[Amit Varma]: your choice.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:13.760
[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:20.800
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at seenunseen.in.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:23.400
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation.

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:31.240
[Amit Varma]: Help keep this thing going, seenunseen.in slash support.

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:35.680
[Guest 2]: Hamsini and Shibani, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:37.200
[Guest 2]: Thanks for having us, Amit.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:41.760
[Amit Varma]: So you know, Hamsini, long time since we've actually spoken, we were colleagues for the

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.160
[Amit Varma]: longest time, you've come on at least a couple of episodes of The Seen and the Unseen in

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:46.280
[Amit Varma]: the past.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:49.040
[Amit Varma]: So how has life been treating you?

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:50.040
[Guest 2]: It's been good, Amit.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:54.080
[Guest 2]: I was thinking about, you know, I don't know if you know this, Shibani, but when we first

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:59.600
[Guest 2]: started doing editorial meets, Amit and I had this tradition of going to Blossoms, and

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:05.280
[Guest 2]: then we'd go over to the Starbucks across the street and sit there, compare purchases,

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:09.880
[Guest 2]: and then sit down and talk about like, what was going to go on with Pragati.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:15.440
[Guest 2]: And when we first started this, I think Church Street was at that point in time, going through

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:16.440
[Guest 2]: renovations.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:20.440
[Guest 2]: So it was literally like you had to dodge and walk on some of these wooden planks that

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:21.960
[Guest 2]: were on the street.

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:25.280
[Guest 2]: And at one point, I remember Amit turning and saying to me, you know, we should really

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:30.080
[Guest 2]: go in a single file, because if the both of us die, then that's it for Pragati, we're

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:31.080
[Guest 2]: completely done.

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:37.520
[Guest 2]: And yeah, so it's been a long time since we've been holding the soul of Pragati in our feet

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:41.040
[Guest 2]: on Church Street, Amit, but life has been good.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:45.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I don't remember this wooden plank thing, but it sounds like just the kind of morbid

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:47.440
[Amit Varma]: thing that I would say.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:50.520
[Amit Varma]: And I must here tell my listeners something that they've probably heard before from me

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:55.400
[Amit Varma]: that Church Street is basically the best street in the world, partly because you know, there's

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:59.920
[Amit Varma]: Takshashila with that captive studio and all the wonderful people who work there, including

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:04.600
[Amit Varma]: you guys at one point in time, and plus Blossoms in the Starbucks.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I was recording with Ram Guha once in the Takshashila studio, when we were

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:10.560
[Amit Varma]: doing our Gandhi episodes.

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:14.280
[Amit Varma]: And at the end of that, I said that, you know, he said, Okay, where are you going?

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:15.280
[Amit Varma]: What are you up to?

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:21.120
[Amit Varma]: I said that I'm now going to go to the best bookshop in the world, which is Blossoms.

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:25.200
[Amit Varma]: And he said, best bookshop in the world, you fool, it's not even the best bookshop on Church

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:31.600
[Amit Varma]: Street, by which there's another store called Bookworm, which is very nice, where I went

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:33.760
[Amit Varma]: and found a secondhand copy of my own book.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:36.440
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, how good can this shop be?

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:43.600
[Guest 2]: Clearly, it's great, Amit, I mean, if it has secondhand versions of your book.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:48.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so our listeners are now like, this is supposed to be an episode about India and

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:49.160
[Amit Varma]: China.

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:50.520
[Amit Varma]: Let's start talking about that.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:55.680
[Amit Varma]: But you know, before that, I want to get a sense of, Hamsini, starting with you, how

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:00.400
[Amit Varma]: you got drawn to China, in the sense your master's degree also has to do with China.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And after that, you went to China, and you were actually a student there.

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:06.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you're studying in Beijing.

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:13.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, of course, you're back in Chennai, and, you know, waiting for all of this to end,

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.160
[Amit Varma]: and bemoaning the loss of WeChat.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:20.320
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how the journey has been, what got you interested in, say,

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:23.040
[Amit Varma]: international relations to begin with, and then China?

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:26.360
[Amit Varma]: And what was sort of your experience in China, like, while you were there?

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:28.920
[Guest 2]: Okay, so there are different versions to this story.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:32.640
[Guest 2]: One is, you know, the one that my parents are most proud of is, you know, when I was

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:37.120
[Guest 2]: eight, I said I wanted to be like Kofi Annan, and they were like, yes, this girl is going

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:39.400
[Guest 2]: to go into the civil services.

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:45.280
[Guest 2]: And then I rebelled, like every other person in this country, and I really didn't want

00:07:45.280 --> 00:07:47.160
[Guest 2]: to go into the civil services.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:49.600
[Guest 2]: I actually did my bachelor's in journalism.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:55.680
[Guest 2]: And when I was doing my bachelor's, I did one of my internships at a Tibetan newspaper

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:57.280
[Guest 2]: based in Dharamsala.

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:00.880
[Guest 2]: And my whole point was that I wanted to spend a summer in Dharamsala more than anything

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:02.240
[Guest 2]: else.

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:05.960
[Guest 2]: And that experience really changed me, I think.

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:11.040
[Guest 2]: So you know, while I now go to Beijing, and everyone calls me sort of a China apologist

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:16.600
[Guest 2]: to various degrees, I think my journey really started out with knowing nothing about China

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:25.400
[Guest 2]: or Tibet, but staying there for a month or two, and just really realizing sort of the

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:27.660
[Guest 2]: boundaries of my knowledge about the world.

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:32.840
[Guest 2]: And that's when I realized that I wanted to study more about international relations.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:39.060
[Guest 2]: And I did a master's in India, before I worked at the Takshashila Institution and Pragati.

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:43.400
[Guest 2]: And even during my master's, China was sort of the thing that was always lurking at the

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:49.080
[Guest 2]: back of my mind, I didn't have a specific region or a focus like a lot of other people

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:50.080
[Guest 2]: did.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:55.320
[Guest 2]: But I realized that I enjoyed reading about China, and very few people knew about it.

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:58.640
[Guest 2]: So I wanted to dive more into it.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:02.640
[Guest 2]: I think when I was in Takshashila, even when I was working with you, I was doing these

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.680
[Guest 2]: Mandarin classes on the side and learning more about the language.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:12.480
[Guest 2]: And none of that was useful when I finally went to China, because you know, while I could

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:17.560
[Guest 2]: read and write quite decently, I think my speaking was just horrible, because I'd had

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:18.560
[Guest 2]: no practice whatsoever.

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:24.600
[Guest 2]: So I'm doing my second master's in China at Peking University, which is a very good university

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:30.320
[Guest 2]: and I was having a wonderful time until the pandemic hit and I was sort of forced to come

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:31.360
[Guest 2]: back home.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:37.160
[Guest 2]: So I am waiting out the pandemic until the international borders reopen and I can go

00:09:37.160 --> 00:09:39.360
[Guest 2]: back and finish my research.

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:43.160
[Amit Varma]: And Shibani to turn to you, you've also been into international relations for the longest

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:44.160
[Amit Varma]: time.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:48.380
[Amit Varma]: And then you also got into China, not that you've specialized in only that, but that's

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:52.320
[Amit Varma]: been one of the key areas on which you've been working and you were at Takshashila till

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:53.320
[Amit Varma]: recently as well.

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.160
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about your journey, why international relations, because that's not the kind of

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:59.560
[Amit Varma]: thing young people get drawn to, right?

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:00.560
[Guest 1]: So what happened?

00:10:00.560 --> 00:10:08.400
[Guest 1]: For me, I also had aspirations like Hamsini to join the foreign services and which is

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:14.480
[Guest 1]: why I was studying history, economics and political science as an undergraduate.

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:21.080
[Guest 1]: And international relations was this discipline that combined all of those interests for me.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:27.160
[Guest 1]: So immediately after I finished college, I went to do my master's and I went to Singapore.

00:10:27.160 --> 00:10:31.880
[Guest 1]: I would say my scholarly sort of journey with China is fairly recent.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:37.940
[Guest 1]: I've only started working on China and related issues in the last year, but my introduction

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:44.080
[Guest 1]: happened when I was doing my master's because Singapore has a lot of Chinese students.

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:50.160
[Guest 1]: So I was introduced to it in the classroom where you have classmates from China talking

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:55.680
[Guest 1]: about the Chinese take on issues that were being discussed.

00:10:55.680 --> 00:11:00.760
[Guest 1]: But at the time, I was completely obsessed with international terrorism.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:06.360
[Guest 1]: That's what I wanted to study for the rest of my life and wanted to become a war correspondent

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:08.080
[Guest 1]: and things like that.

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:10.160
[Guest 1]: So that's what I was doing.

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:15.080
[Guest 1]: But on the side also, hanging out with people from China, listening to what they had to

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:19.320
[Guest 1]: say about issues of international politics.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:22.600
[Guest 1]: And yeah, so I kind of wandered.

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:28.000
[Guest 1]: And at Takshashila, I used to hang out with Hamsini and Manoj and just like chat with

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.000
[Guest 1]: them to know more.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.480
[Guest 1]: It was nothing more than that.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:33.960
[Guest 1]: But yeah, in the last year, it's become a little more formal.

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:39.360
[Guest 1]: I'm studying China's engagement in the Indian subcontinent, trying to look at the Indian

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:43.680
[Guest 1]: point of view, what is the Indian perception of China and stuff.

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:47.600
[Amit Varma]: And I have a couple of broad questions I'd like, you know, both of you to sort of take

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:53.200
[Amit Varma]: on which is, you know, before we get to the subject at hand, which is, one is that, you

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:58.280
[Amit Varma]: know, when we start learning about a subject, and this is a process I've seen that happens

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:03.000
[Amit Varma]: to all of us, and is especially interesting when one is young and getting into a subject,

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:08.480
[Amit Varma]: is that you shall, for example, leave China and IR out of it for a while, let's say, how

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:11.640
[Amit Varma]: do you frame the way that you look at the world.

00:12:11.640 --> 00:12:16.920
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of young people when they find a theory that sort of contains a worldview and

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:21.560
[Amit Varma]: contains a frame through which they can decipher the world, they get enamored by it.

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And all they can see for a while is, you know, that framework.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.240
[Amit Varma]: So they're using that hammer to break every nail.

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:31.440
[Amit Varma]: For example, there's a joke about how if you're not a communist at 18, you don't have a heart.

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:34.960
[Amit Varma]: And if you're not a capitalist at 32, you don't have a brain, something to that effect.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:37.520
[Amit Varma]: There are many sort of versions of that.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:42.560
[Amit Varma]: And it sort of strikes me that when you guys get into international relations, for example,

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:45.640
[Amit Varma]: there are all these different frames to which you look at the world.

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:50.520
[Amit Varma]: Or when you talk about China and China's engagement with the world, there are all these different

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:51.520
[Amit Varma]: frames.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the moment you come across one theory that seems so good, and your eyes just

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:59.320
[Amit Varma]: open and you're like, wow, this explains everything, then how seductive is that?

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And how easy is it then to sort of, you know, keep your mind open and just keep taking in

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.400
[Amit Varma]: influences from all sides?

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:13.680
[Amit Varma]: And at what point like, so have you guys sort of, you know, been through this sort of journey

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:17.200
[Amit Varma]: in, you know, learning about IR and learning about China?

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:18.200
[Amit Varma]: Hamsini?

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:22.400
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, I think for myself, I've definitely gone through that.

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:28.040
[Guest 2]: I think even my podcast, the concept of, you know, states of anarchy comes from the first

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:32.040
[Guest 2]: time I heard about the concept of anarchy sitting in international relations.

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:35.720
[Guest 2]: It really sort of blew my mind.

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:37.840
[Guest 2]: And it hasn't stopped blowing my mind.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:45.840
[Guest 2]: But what I also learned very early on, is I came across opposing viewpoints, particularly

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:53.920
[Guest 2]: from people who thought that concepts of realism really discounted domestic processes, really

00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:59.960
[Guest 2]: discounted behaviours of certain states, really discounted histories, which were not Western

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:01.600
[Guest 2]: histories.

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:06.880
[Guest 2]: And so it was sort of good to go up against those and see how other people felt about

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:08.520
[Guest 2]: these theories.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:13.280
[Guest 2]: But something that I say for myself, at least, is that learning about international relations

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:18.120
[Guest 2]: helps me understand and make more sense of the world around me.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:24.160
[Guest 2]: And I think that's something that's definitely true of international relations theory as

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:25.160
[Guest 2]: well.

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:26.280
[Amit Varma]: Can you briefly elaborate on that?

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:29.160
[Amit Varma]: What do you mean learning about international relations makes you help sense of the world

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:30.160
[Amit Varma]: about that?

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:31.160
[Amit Varma]: Because that's what I say about economics.

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:35.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, if you start saying that about international relations, it just gets very confusing for

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:36.920
[Amit Varma]: the listener.

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:38.640
[Guest 2]: What am I supposed to study to make sense of the world?

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:44.920
[Guest 2]: You know, economics, sure, Amit, we've always had this thing where I've seen you talk about

00:14:44.920 --> 00:14:47.960
[Guest 2]: like things like household economics, at least when we were at Prakriti.

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:53.720
[Guest 2]: But for me, foreign policy theories really help you make sense of the world, in the sense

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:57.400
[Guest 2]: of they also consider that players are rational actors.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:00.480
[Guest 2]: They also consider decision making.

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:04.760
[Guest 2]: What's very interesting for me is that they consider the international system, for the

00:15:04.760 --> 00:15:07.280
[Guest 2]: large part, is amoral.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:12.280
[Guest 2]: And that has really helped me figure out debates in my own life.

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:18.960
[Guest 2]: And I think sort of the existing conditions for international relations is something that

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:25.520
[Guest 2]: I've sort of applied to my own world view, whether it's the way power works, or the way

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:33.000
[Guest 2]: networks work, or just the lack of a hierarchical system in the world at large.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.480
[Guest 2]: I think those are just concepts that make me understand how everything ticks.

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:39.480
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating.

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:41.120
[Amit Varma]: Shabani, what about you?

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:43.960
[Amit Varma]: What's your sort of learning through IR been like?

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:47.960
[Amit Varma]: Like, was there sort of a particular school of thought which was attractive to you to

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:48.960
[Amit Varma]: begin with?

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And also, how do you sort of, you know, a question I guess you could ask a scholar in

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:56.120
[Amit Varma]: any field, how do you increase your knowledge?

00:15:56.120 --> 00:15:57.600
[Amit Varma]: How do you figure out what to read?

00:15:57.600 --> 00:15:59.680
[Guest 1]: How do you organize whatever you're learning?

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:06.440
[Guest 1]: I was definitely influenced by one school of thought when I first started studying international

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:07.720
[Guest 1]: relations.

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:12.720
[Guest 1]: And that was because the professor that was teaching us IR theory belonged to a particular

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:13.720
[Guest 1]: school of thought.

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:19.080
[Guest 1]: So for me to question a teacher was a very new concept.

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:23.680
[Guest 1]: It was not something that we had been introduced to in the Indian education system, unfortunately.

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:30.400
[Guest 1]: So I was like, whatever he's saying is like final, right, it can't be anything else.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:36.320
[Guest 1]: And then in my second term, I encountered another professor who came from the completely

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:43.120
[Guest 1]: like different school of thought and I was as enamored by him.

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:48.520
[Guest 1]: And that's when I realized that I have to, you know, you have to figure it out for yourself.

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:53.800
[Guest 1]: Initially there was this urgency to be like, who am I, where do I fit in?

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:56.320
[Guest 1]: What is the label that I would put on myself?

00:16:56.320 --> 00:17:03.760
[Guest 1]: But right now I'm allowing myself to learn about everything that there is, evolve my

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:11.360
[Guest 1]: own thinking process, which is I think essential for anyone, even when it comes to economics.

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:14.560
[Guest 1]: Same for IR, you have to give yourself some time.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:16.920
[Guest 1]: It's too soon for me to put myself in a box.

00:17:16.920 --> 00:17:19.520
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so right now I don't give myself any labels.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:26.440
[Guest 1]: And it also allows you to read a little more, you're more open to the other arguments and

00:17:26.440 --> 00:17:31.680
[Guest 1]: you can be more objective, which is, I think, what we're all trying to do.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:17:32.680 --> 00:17:38.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, all these theoretical lenses are obviously sort of useful tools and useful

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:43.400
[Amit Varma]: guides to being able to think about the world and understands people's actions in different

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:44.400
[Amit Varma]: ways.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But what's wrong, do you find they actually correspond with reality?

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.880
[Amit Varma]: For example, we can have all kinds of frames of about how, you know, foreign policy proceeds

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.880
[Amit Varma]: and how China relates to India and blah, blah, blah.

00:17:55.880 --> 00:17:57.960
[Amit Varma]: And then things happen, which don't fit into these frames.

00:17:57.960 --> 00:17:59.640
[Amit Varma]: And you're like, Hey, what's going on?

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:00.640
[Amit Varma]: What's happening?

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:04.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and Hamsini, you've actually sort of been in China and I heard you in the

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:08.880
[Amit Varma]: All Things Policy podcast the other day with Manoj, where you made the very interesting

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.760
[Amit Varma]: observation that while China is a part of our lives here in India, right down to the

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:18.800
[Amit Varma]: phones we use and all of that, India was not at all a part of your life in China, which

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:23.680
[Amit Varma]: I found fascinating, and which also kind of indicates that, you know, in all these frameworks,

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:28.160
[Amit Varma]: we'll talk about Indochina with a hyphen, as if, you know, these are two characters

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:31.160
[Amit Varma]: equally interested in each other.

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:36.480
[Amit Varma]: But for a lot of Chinese, India is very far away, which is not quite the case for us here.

00:18:36.480 --> 00:18:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Can you kind of expand on these two sort of angles?

00:18:39.720 --> 00:18:46.800
[Guest 2]: Yeah, also, as an IR scholar, Amit, I will object to you saying Indochina, because Indochina

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:51.560
[Guest 2]: typically refers to Cambodia, Vietnam, Laos.

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:57.960
[Guest 2]: So Sino-Indian is what they generally say, but I agree with your point, in the sense

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:07.240
[Guest 2]: that it's very difficult to fathom how the world around us fits into these theories that

00:19:07.240 --> 00:19:10.800
[Guest 2]: were formed since the 1920s, right?

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:17.960
[Guest 2]: And what I try to do, at least with my own understanding of the world, is to, I think

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:23.680
[Guest 2]: in the back of my head, I will understand how, say, liberals look at something or constructivists

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:31.000
[Guest 2]: look at something, and then see if it plays out without prescribing that lens to it, you

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.120
[Guest 2]: know, and say, this is what happened.

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:38.240
[Guest 2]: It doesn't particularly matter what a school of thought thinks about it.

00:19:38.240 --> 00:19:44.400
[Guest 2]: But what matters is sort of the element that's at play, you know?

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:49.800
[Guest 2]: If this is power, then what does that school of thought tell us about that element, rather

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:55.540
[Guest 2]: than about, you know, large scale sweeping statements about the world?

00:19:55.540 --> 00:20:03.200
[Guest 2]: So when I was living in China, for example, there was a lot that we kept talking about.

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:07.160
[Guest 2]: For example, in US and India, you talk a lot about sort of the China threat theory, which

00:20:07.160 --> 00:20:15.160
[Guest 2]: is that China's rise is threatening, and it will destabilize the world order, and so on.

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:21.240
[Guest 2]: And in China, they talk about China's peaceful rise, which is the idea that China will peacefully

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:23.360
[Guest 2]: become a superpower.

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:28.640
[Guest 2]: And you have criticisms of both theories on either end.

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:34.400
[Guest 2]: And it's very interesting to see how that plays out and sort of live that reality.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:38.560
[Guest 2]: There is always a little bit of dissonance, however.

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:46.120
[Guest 2]: What I think for me helps is to use these labels to understand and put a name to what

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:52.600
[Guest 2]: is happening around me, but not fully ascribe to that label alone as my own worldview, if

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:54.000
[Amit Varma]: that makes sense.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.160
[Amit Varma]: That makes a lot of sense.

00:20:55.160 --> 00:21:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's about time before our listeners rebel and go away to actually talk about India and

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:01.760
[Amit Varma]: China.

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:02.760
[Amit Varma]: I was about to say Indochina.

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:04.800
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, you've corrected me there.

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:08.600
[Amit Varma]: So to talk about sort of India and China, and obviously, you know, before we come to

00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:14.160
[Amit Varma]: the current time, which is deeply complicated, and it's almost become a trend of, I mean,

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:17.960
[Amit Varma]: there's actually two simultaneous trends going on nowadays in our discourse.

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And one is to disregard history completely and just talk of the current moment and the

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:27.560
[Amit Varma]: other trend is to make up a history and, you know, fit it to whatever ideology you happen

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:28.560
[Amit Varma]: to have.

00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:32.560
[Amit Varma]: But we will not fall into any of these traps before we can talk about what is now happening,

00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:35.360
[Amit Varma]: we have to get complete historical context.

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:39.200
[Amit Varma]: And we will do it at different kinds of levels.

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:45.040
[Amit Varma]: Level one, which I'd like you guys to talk about, is sort of a centuries old view, which

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:49.320
[Amit Varma]: is how has China traditionally looked at itself?

00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:53.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, India as a political entity, of course, is recent, but in general, in the

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:56.760
[Amit Varma]: subcontinent, how have we looked at ourselves?

00:21:56.760 --> 00:22:00.800
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of different worldviews towards the rest of the world?

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:06.040
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, how has that impacted our relations over the centuries?

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:11.320
[Guest 2]: You know, particularly when we talk about China and India, we come across two different

00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:12.880
[Guest 2]: schools of thought, right?

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:18.280
[Guest 2]: And the first in China is tianxia, or, you know, all under the heavens.

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:22.320
[Guest 2]: And, you know, I know it's extremely cliche to now sort of begin talking with tianxia,

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:25.160
[Guest 2]: but you can't escape from it either.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:29.840
[Guest 2]: And the concept of tianxia essentially is that you have, you know, heaven and underneath

00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:34.920
[Guest 2]: heaven, the Middle Kingdom, which is China, and you know, and then you have sort of layers

00:22:34.920 --> 00:22:36.000
[Guest 2]: outside it.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.840
[Guest 2]: And first you have the Middle Kingdom itself, then you have countries that have pledged

00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:45.040
[Guest 2]: their allegiance, in a sense, to the Middle Kingdom, and outside that you have barbarians.

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:49.880
[Guest 2]: And this sort of worldview is supposed to have informed the way the Chinese approached

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:52.280
[Guest 2]: the world and themselves for a very long time.

00:22:52.280 --> 00:22:59.400
[Guest 2]: So there's even a very funny anecdote that the first time that a British envoy goes into

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:05.120
[Guest 2]: the court of the Qianlong Emperor and says, oh, my king sends his regards, the Emperor

00:23:05.120 --> 00:23:06.600
[Guest 2]: says, who is your king?

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:08.680
[Guest 2]: There is only one king.

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:14.680
[Guest 2]: So they didn't really recognize the sovereignty of anybody else.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:20.040
[Guest 2]: And that's very interesting when you consider the Westphalian system, where we traditionally

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:22.680
[Guest 2]: put ourselves where all states are equal.

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:25.760
[Guest 2]: Yeah, that is something that I wanted to point out.

00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:29.920
[Amit Varma]: And in the Indian subcontinent, rather, as you know, there wasn't per se in India, then

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:31.080
[Amit Varma]: the approach was very different, right?

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:36.160
[Amit Varma]: It was a very pluralistic kind of approach where you recognize that there are many different

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:39.760
[Amit Varma]: sort of sovereigns, and there are different ways of dealing with this.

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:44.000
[Amit Varma]: But you certainly don't have this arrogance that you'll recognize no other king but yourself.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, that's kind of dictated also by size, you are a lot of chutku-chutkulati

00:23:48.320 --> 00:23:49.320
[Amit Varma]: kingdoms.

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:56.920
[Guest 2]: Yeah, that's a brilliant way to talk about India's sort of checkered history, right?

00:23:56.920 --> 00:24:01.440
[Guest 2]: Like all these chutku-chutku systems that exist, often making alliances with each other

00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:08.520
[Guest 2]: ganging up on bigger kingdoms, each of these kingdoms have their own civil services base,

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:10.960
[Guest 2]: they have their own tax structures.

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:15.120
[Guest 2]: Of course, when you look at like small kingdoms in Rajasthan, for example, they could have

00:24:15.120 --> 00:24:17.400
[Guest 2]: all shared similar features.

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:21.320
[Guest 2]: But when you look at it on a macro scale, these were very disparate kingdoms.

00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:27.520
[Guest 2]: When India finally got independence, we were 540 odd kingdoms, that princely states that

00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:30.380
[Guest 2]: eventually acceded to form the Indian Union.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:36.080
[Guest 2]: And before the British came, this could have easily been twice, thrice that number.

00:24:36.080 --> 00:24:42.280
[Guest 2]: And there's sort of a tradition in Indian strategic thought, to go back to the Arthashastra

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:50.160
[Guest 2]: and Cortellian schools of thought, that look at how alliances were formed, and how they

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:55.200
[Guest 2]: were often directed at enemies, you know, the concept of my enemy's enemy is my friend

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:56.320
[Guest 2]: and so on.

00:24:56.320 --> 00:25:01.760
[Guest 2]: But I would not say that you could prescribe this sort of strategic thought to all the

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:03.920
[Amit Varma]: countries in the subcontinent.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:07.640
[Amit Varma]: To all the countries in the subcontinent is an interesting way of putting it.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:11.640
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that, you know, China, despite this sort of sense of superiority,

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:16.320
[Amit Varma]: were also in a sense, a little bit insular in the sense that they didn't really have

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:19.280
[Amit Varma]: imperial ambitions of taking over the world.

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:24.640
[Amit Varma]: Certainly not when it came to India, for example, where of course, the Himalayas are a natural

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:26.080
[Amit Varma]: barrier.

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:31.120
[Amit Varma]: And I believe before modern times, there was only one conflict sometime in, you know, 600

00:25:31.120 --> 00:25:35.640
[Amit Varma]: AD or something, a minor conflict, but otherwise, there was really nothing much.

00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:41.240
[Guest 2]: No, Amit, the Chinese history is filled with war.

00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:44.560
[Guest 2]: If you look at like, whether it's the Song or the Ming or the Qin.

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:51.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, towards India, towards India, which is Sino-Indian, Sino-Indian would be slightly

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:52.160
[Guest 2]: different.

00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:54.520
[Guest 2]: I think we have to raise a couple of points here.

00:25:54.520 --> 00:26:00.480
[Guest 2]: There's this really excellent book that I refer to later as well, called From Frontier

00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:05.000
[Guest 2]: Policy to Foreign Policy.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:12.520
[Guest 2]: And the author, Matthew Mosca, points out that for the most part, the Qing Empire, which

00:26:12.520 --> 00:26:20.120
[Guest 2]: was ruling during the 17th and 18th and the 19th centuries, didn't really look at India

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:21.640
[Guest 2]: as a whole.

00:26:21.640 --> 00:26:28.480
[Guest 2]: In the sense you had Indian traders at Guangdong, Guangzhou, the ports on the eastern seaboard,

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:30.480
[Guest 2]: and those people were seen as different.

00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:33.720
[Guest 2]: You had merchants from Calcutta who were being seen as different.

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:37.640
[Guest 2]: You had people who were in Tibet who were being seen as different.

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:44.880
[Guest 2]: And so for a very long time, the Chinese court had to contend with the fact that these were

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:51.680
[Guest 2]: not localized tribes, but rather one large kingdom, which eventually came under British

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:52.900
[Guest 2]: India and so on.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:59.200
[Guest 2]: So that was something that was a real feature of Chinese foreign policy at that point in

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:00.200
[Guest 2]: time.

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:04.800
[Guest 2]: And it was difficult because of intelligence gathering, because of the way that courts

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:07.600
[Guest 2]: were structured, the way information was relayed and so on.

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:13.080
[Guest 2]: But they didn't largely have any conflicts towards India.

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:19.560
[Guest 2]: There were always skirmishes along the border that could have been traced, for example,

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:25.320
[Guest 2]: with the emperor and the kingdom in Ladakh or across Tibet and things like that.

00:27:25.320 --> 00:27:30.680
[Guest 2]: So those were regular features of the border, but they aren't really considered in Chinese

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:31.680
[Amit Varma]: history.

00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And is it sort of fair to say that the one time where China begins to loom large in India's

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:44.280
[Amit Varma]: sort of geopolitical considerations is really when the British Empire is underway.

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:48.480
[Amit Varma]: So in the 19th century, you have the great game happening where you have sort of two

00:27:48.480 --> 00:27:54.520
[Amit Varma]: imperialistic forces in the British and the Russians vying for influence in territory.

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, you know, the question that the British face is where do we draw

00:27:58.560 --> 00:27:59.560
[Amit Varma]: the line?

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:02.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we're obviously not going beyond the Himalayas, but where do we draw the line?

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Do we keep Afghanistan as a buffer state between Russia and us?

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:10.720
[Amit Varma]: What role, most pertinently, does China play in this?

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:15.240
[Amit Varma]: And China is almost, you know, this insular force whose approach till then to the rest

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:18.000
[Amit Varma]: of the world is, you know, who the hell are you guys?

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:22.080
[Amit Varma]: You are either barbarians or kindly come here to pay tribute.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:26.040
[Amit Varma]: But at this point, you know, they are not up against, you know, India as it will be

00:28:26.040 --> 00:28:32.360
[Amit Varma]: later or against a whole bunch of disparate nation states, but against the British Empire.

00:28:32.360 --> 00:28:39.520
[Amit Varma]: And this is when the first sort of disagreements about borders start to take shape.

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:41.560
[Guest 2]: So tell me a little bit about that period.

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:46.320
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I think you raised a very important point, Amit, in that the British wanted a

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:47.320
[Guest 2]: buffer zone.

00:28:47.320 --> 00:28:52.440
[Guest 2]: And a lot of this does go back to sort of this great game of the 1800s.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:58.960
[Guest 2]: And the British were particularly concerned when Russia conquered Tashkent and Samarkand,

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:01.640
[Guest 2]: which are currently sort of Uzbekistan.

00:29:01.640 --> 00:29:07.480
[Guest 2]: And the British were really afraid that Russia would come all the way to the borders of India.

00:29:07.480 --> 00:29:13.880
[Guest 2]: And so they wanted not only a frontier, which at that point in time was Afghanistan and

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:20.240
[Guest 2]: the Himalayas, but they wanted a border, which was a line in that sense.

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:25.600
[Guest 2]: There's often, whenever we talk about the border with China, a lot of scholars do point

00:29:25.600 --> 00:29:33.560
[Guest 2]: out that it's very difficult to parse through the Chinese sources on the Indian border,

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:38.960
[Guest 2]: because there's A, very little that's been written about, and B, it's very, very disparate,

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:41.120
[Guest 2]: as I'd mentioned a couple of minutes ago.

00:29:41.120 --> 00:29:46.400
[Guest 2]: So I think, you know, when it comes to this, you have to go back to Ladakh at that point

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:47.400
[Guest 2]: in time.

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:51.240
[Guest 2]: And I'm sure you've spoken about this with other guests on your show whenever you're

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:52.800
[Guest 2]: talking to Kashmir.

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:57.160
[Guest 2]: But all of this history of even Jammu and Kashmir, right, at the end of the first Anglo-Sikh

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:00.200
[Guest 2]: war, you have the Treaty of Amritsar that's signed.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:05.680
[Guest 2]: And then Gulab Singh took over as sort of the Dogra Maharaja of Jammu and Kashmir.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:13.440
[Guest 2]: And so the Dogras, the people who start pushing the frontiers of Jammu and Kashmir, they are

00:30:13.440 --> 00:30:20.300
[Guest 2]: the ones who subsumed Ladakh, which was an independent kingdom for the most part of history.

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:24.960
[Guest 2]: And it was independent the way Tibet was, the way Bhutan was, the way Nepal and Sikkim

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:25.960
[Guest 2]: were.

00:30:25.960 --> 00:30:33.200
[Guest 2]: And so Gulab Singh and the Sikhs eventually also capture Gilgit-Baltistan, which is now

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:37.760
[Guest 2]: a part of POK, and the Hunza region, and so on and so forth.

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:42.840
[Guest 2]: But what happens here is that you have all of these British geographers and explorers

00:30:42.840 --> 00:30:49.000
[Guest 2]: and diplomats who go in during the 19th century, and they start exploring the Himalayas, right,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:55.880
[Guest 2]: the Royal Geographic Society is an organization that's now looking at how explorers will see

00:30:55.880 --> 00:30:59.480
[Guest 2]: the world and look at unknown places and things like that.

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:05.320
[Guest 2]: So I think this is the period when maps are finally starting to be drawn.

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:10.800
[Guest 2]: And the first map that comes up is something called the Ada-Johnson line.

00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:16.600
[Guest 2]: And what essentially happens is William Johnson, who was a British surveyor, becomes Gulab

00:31:16.600 --> 00:31:18.820
[Guest 2]: Singh's governor for Ladakh.

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:25.280
[Guest 2]: And he proposed a line that would go through Aksai Chin, which we know now as very infamous.

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:29.000
[Guest 2]: And it goes all the way to the Kunlun range, which is a little further back.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:33.340
[Guest 2]: And the Johnson line was presented in London by a man called Sir John Ada.

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:36.160
[Guest 2]: And that's why it's called the Ada-Johnson line.

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:42.000
[Guest 2]: This was proposed in 1865, but the Chinese never really recognized it.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:47.440
[Guest 2]: So the next line that comes up about 20 years later, is that the British again, are in talks

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:50.160
[Guest 2]: with the Chinese and they propose another line.

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:53.240
[Guest 2]: And this is called the McCartney-McDonnell line.

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:58.880
[Guest 2]: And it's very famous because McDonnell is also the person who secured the 99-year lease

00:31:58.880 --> 00:32:00.280
[Guest 2]: for Hong Kong.

00:32:00.280 --> 00:32:07.380
[Guest 2]: And so he proposes a line that will put Aksai Chin directly under the Chinese rule.

00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:14.120
[Guest 2]: So these are two lines that are proposed much before the 1912 similar agreement, which we

00:32:14.120 --> 00:32:15.120
[Guest 2]: can talk about.

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:18.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so they proposed, but how did the Chinese react to that?

00:32:18.600 --> 00:32:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Like, is this a unilateral thing that the British are proposing that these are the lines

00:32:22.120 --> 00:32:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that they're declaring it?

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:25.320
[Amit Varma]: Is there pushback from the Chinese?

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:27.680
[Amit Varma]: What do the Chinese feel about all this?

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:29.720
[Guest 2]: What's the sort of politics happening there?

00:32:29.720 --> 00:32:32.200
[Guest 2]: So the British present these lines.

00:32:32.200 --> 00:32:34.300
[Guest 2]: So they get these surveyors to draw up these lines.

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:39.560
[Guest 2]: They present it to the Chinese court, they present it to the Tibetans as well.

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:45.320
[Guest 2]: And you have various interpretations of how this was perceived.

00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:51.000
[Guest 2]: The Chinese, to date, staunchly argue that they have never accepted any of these lines.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.080
[Guest 2]: And there is a certain amount of truth in that, in that even if there were conversations

00:32:55.080 --> 00:33:00.640
[Guest 2]: or discussions, you see Chinese diplomats at that point in time, or the Qing court just

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:05.320
[Guest 2]: rejecting these maps and the talks finally falling through.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:11.600
[Amit Varma]: Right, and then in 1914, there's another sort of interesting border discussion that, you

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:17.120
[Amit Varma]: know, has resonance up to the current day, which is supposedly a three-way agreement

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:20.800
[Amit Varma]: between India, China, and Tibet, which leads to what we call the Mek-Mohan line.

00:33:20.800 --> 00:33:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that, because that's also interesting in the court dispute there

00:33:25.120 --> 00:33:29.440
[Amit Varma]: was even a little funny to me for reasons I'll get into, but yeah.

00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:35.580
[Guest 2]: Okay, so I know that, you know, we come up with the Mek-Mohan line in 1914, but what's

00:33:35.580 --> 00:33:41.280
[Guest 2]: important to remember is that we come up with the Mek-Mohan line after nine months of deliberations.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:42.280
[Amit Varma]: So the-

00:33:42.280 --> 00:33:44.360
[Amit Varma]: By we, you mean the British, you're referring to we as a British.

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:47.680
[Guest 2]: By we, I mean the British, the Chinese, and the Tibetans, right?

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:52.840
[Guest 2]: So all three of us hold deliberations for about nine months about where a border should

00:33:52.840 --> 00:33:53.960
[Guest 2]: be.

00:33:53.960 --> 00:34:01.240
[Guest 2]: And what's interesting is that they finally agreed on sort of an inner Tibet, which would

00:34:01.240 --> 00:34:06.840
[Guest 2]: be made up of regions of Amdo and Kham, and outer Tibet, which is sort of made up of adjoining

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:12.520
[Guest 2]: areas within China, which would typically be in areas of Sichuan and Yunnan right now.

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:17.440
[Guest 2]: And the British finally agreed that Tibet was sort of under the sovereignty of the Chinese,

00:34:17.440 --> 00:34:21.840
[Guest 2]: but they also put down stipulations that the Chinese would not interfere with the running

00:34:21.840 --> 00:34:25.360
[Guest 2]: of Tibet or they would agree never to annex it and so on.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:31.760
[Guest 2]: So with the Chinese, the main deliberations were on what would be the boundary between

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:34.120
[Guest 2]: inner Tibet and outer Tibet.

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:37.680
[Guest 2]: And with the Tibetans, the British drew up the borders of Tibet.

00:34:37.680 --> 00:34:43.160
[Guest 2]: And this is what Indians now call the Mek-Mohan line, which is now disputed.

00:34:43.160 --> 00:34:45.200
[Guest 2]: So that is one part of it.

00:34:45.200 --> 00:34:51.800
[Guest 2]: Now I think what is important to mention here is that the Chinese argument is that the Chinese

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:55.040
[Guest 2]: representatives at this meeting were kept in the dark.

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:59.120
[Guest 2]: They said that, you know, these British imperialists pressured the Tibetans into accepting a new

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:01.960
[Guest 2]: border and that all of this was a conspiracy.

00:35:01.960 --> 00:35:09.960
[Guest 2]: And their biggest rejection of the line comes in because their negotiator, this man called

00:35:09.960 --> 00:35:15.080
[Guest 2]: Chen Yifan, just initiated some pages of the agreement.

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:17.160
[Guest 2]: He never really ratified it.

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:22.160
[Guest 2]: And so that's why the Chinese argue that the Mek-Mohan line is not valid.

00:35:22.160 --> 00:35:27.280
[Amit Varma]: And for all future diplomats, kindly note the difference between initialing and ratifying.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:28.280
[Amit Varma]: Do not make this mistake.

00:35:28.280 --> 00:35:32.840
[Amit Varma]: No, it's a very interesting argument because it's like the Chinese weren't too interested

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:36.160
[Amit Varma]: at that time in the border between Tibet and British India.

00:35:36.160 --> 00:35:39.080
[Amit Varma]: And so, you know, the Tibet and British India agree on a border.

00:35:39.080 --> 00:35:43.540
[Amit Varma]: And later China takes over Tibet and suddenly the border between China and British India.

00:35:43.540 --> 00:35:48.840
[Amit Varma]: And then, of course, there are all these disputes over, you know, I mean, Tawang is famously

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:50.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of part of that dispute.

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Let me turn to you, Shabani, now as we approach independence and we even reach independence.

00:35:55.960 --> 00:36:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And but before we sort of talk about the post-independence imperatives, one sort of broader question

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:09.400
[Amit Varma]: I have is that, you know, when one thinks about all these kinds of border disputes and

00:36:09.400 --> 00:36:14.960
[Amit Varma]: many of these disputes are over areas which are uninhabited, like Saichen is the area

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:18.800
[Amit Varma]: of Switzerland, but it's not quite the most bustling place.

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:22.800
[Amit Varma]: And these disputes are things that we are stuck with, even though, you know, if you

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:27.800
[Amit Varma]: were to approach it with a tabula rasa, it's quite possible that, you know, neither country

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.920
[Amit Varma]: would really dispute in the first place.

00:36:29.920 --> 00:36:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's a historical artifact, it's been something that's fought over.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, that kind of comes down over time and it almost becomes therefore

00:36:37.760 --> 00:36:42.080
[Amit Varma]: a matter of sticking to the previous stance you've made, not just personal ego, but even

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:43.080
[Amit Varma]: national pride.

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:46.840
[Amit Varma]: Like there's a wonderful quote by Jawaharlal Nehru, which I'll take this opportunity to

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:51.320
[Amit Varma]: read out, which he said on September 4th, 1959, I don't quote him much, but here we

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:52.320
[Amit Varma]: go.

00:36:52.320 --> 00:36:53.320
[Amit Varma]: This seem pertinent quote.

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:57.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, it is a question of fact, whether this village or that village or this little strip

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:00.680
[Amit Varma]: of territory is on their side or on our side.

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:05.080
[Amit Varma]: Normally, wherever there are relatively petty disputes, well, it does seem rather absurd

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:09.720
[Amit Varma]: for two great countries immediately to rush at each other's throats to decide whether

00:37:09.720 --> 00:37:13.840
[Amit Varma]: two miles of territory are on this side or on that side, and especially two miles of

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:18.240
[Amit Varma]: territory in the high mountains where nobody lives, but where national prestige and dignity

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:19.240
[Amit Varma]: is involved.

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:21.200
[Amit Varma]: It is not the two miles of territory.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:24.960
[Amit Varma]: It is a nation's dignity and self-respect that becomes involved.

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:27.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore this happens, stop quote.

00:37:27.480 --> 00:37:30.640
[Amit Varma]: And of course, we could argue that he could have been much crisper there, but it's a speech

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:33.680
[Amit Varma]: and not a piece of writing.

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:38.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know, in all this talk of this and that, but it seems to me that, you know, in

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:42.440
[Amit Varma]: these areas that we are fighting about, it's almost ironic that these countries and the

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:46.640
[Amit Varma]: leaders of these countries don't seem to care too much per se for these areas, but these

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:48.080
[Amit Varma]: are historical disputes.

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And because you disagree, you kind of keep disagreeing like, you know, Srinath Raghavan

00:37:53.320 --> 00:37:58.480
[Amit Varma]: in his book, War and Peace in Modern India, in fact, writes about how, you know, Nehru

00:37:58.480 --> 00:38:02.760
[Amit Varma]: at first didn't really think that India had a legit claim to Aksai Chin.

00:38:02.760 --> 00:38:06.760
[Amit Varma]: His whole game was that, let's use it as a bargaining chip and all of that.

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:12.480
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, by the time we get to Chu Enlai's famous sort of offer to India in 1960, which

00:38:12.480 --> 00:38:17.600
[Amit Varma]: Shibani will enlighten us about soon, you know, Nehru has been convinced that, no, we

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:20.400
[Amit Varma]: should claim Aksai Chin and not let it go.

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And some could say that, you know, all our future conflicts could have been avoided had

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:27.520
[Amit Varma]: we just been pragmatic about that.

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:29.800
[Guest 1]: So Shibani, what do you feel about all of this?

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:36.240
[Guest 1]: I think the quote that you read from Nehru says a lot about his personality.

00:38:36.240 --> 00:38:42.320
[Guest 1]: And the reason I bring in personality is because the way I understand international relations,

00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:47.320
[Guest 1]: if you look at it as a board game, while the moves that the players make are important,

00:38:47.320 --> 00:38:51.520
[Guest 1]: it's also important to understand who's making the move.

00:38:51.520 --> 00:38:57.000
[Guest 1]: And that's why the study of personalities, the context in which certain decisions were

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:03.360
[Guest 1]: taken, and what were the constraints that the leadership had, are equally important.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:09.920
[Guest 1]: While your scholarly sort of debate and discussion should be about the policy decision itself,

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:14.080
[Guest 1]: you can't overlook the circumstances in which they were made.

00:39:14.080 --> 00:39:22.440
[Guest 1]: And so while we're talking about Nehru, Nehru comes to power much like when Mao Zedong is

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:30.600
[Guest 1]: also gaining prominence, and we have People's Republic of China established when the Cold

00:39:30.600 --> 00:39:32.280
[Guest 1]: War is going on.

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:40.800
[Guest 1]: So both of these people inherit an international system that's based on great power politics

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:43.920
[Guest 1]: between the US and the Soviet Union.

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:51.240
[Guest 1]: And it's very easy to think that leaders would just adapt to the international system that

00:39:51.240 --> 00:39:54.920
[Guest 1]: they inherit, and because they are restricted by it.

00:39:54.920 --> 00:40:00.480
[Guest 1]: But both of these people are similar in the way that they sort of assert themselves and

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:03.680
[Guest 1]: challenge the system that they inherit.

00:40:03.680 --> 00:40:09.960
[Guest 1]: With Nehru, he knew that non-alignment was, you know, one of the key policy decisions

00:40:09.960 --> 00:40:12.000
[Guest 1]: that he made.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:15.280
[Guest 1]: He was assertive, but in a more diplomatic way.

00:40:15.280 --> 00:40:22.480
[Guest 1]: When you compare it to Mao, Mao viewed it as, you know, the need to be military, like

00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:26.800
[Guest 1]: have more military power and be assertive in that sense.

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:33.680
[Guest 1]: And that's why he also sort of inflamed the conflicts in Korea, in Vietnam, and what Hamsini

00:40:33.680 --> 00:40:37.920
[Guest 1]: was talking about along the Sino-Soviet border as well.

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:40.120
[Guest 1]: So that's where they sort of contrast.

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:48.280
[Guest 1]: Nehru was, you know, thinking about self-restraint and vigorous diplomacy, and Mao's focus was

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:53.000
[Guest 1]: on being military, you know, exercising military might.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:41:00.320
[Guest 1]: Going back to like history and ego of people, I think when we talk about Nehru, you have

00:41:00.320 --> 00:41:06.400
[Guest 1]: to, at the end of the day, he wanted to be prime minister, like when he woke up the next

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:07.400
[Guest 1]: day.

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:12.600
[Guest 1]: So the decisions that were made were based on the political capital that he had.

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:20.440
[Guest 1]: And if he could not convince the Indian public of a certain decision that he made, he would

00:41:20.440 --> 00:41:28.600
[Guest 1]: not go ahead with it, which is what happens later when Chuan Lai proposes the compromise.

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:31.720
[Guest 1]: And I forget what your question is.

00:41:31.720 --> 00:41:37.640
[Amit Varma]: How much of these disputes are sort of just a historical artifact, and then the individuals

00:41:37.640 --> 00:41:42.720
[Amit Varma]: concerned, whether it's, you know, Nehru in this case, get trapped by circumstances into

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:47.800
[Amit Varma]: fighting for something which both they don't necessarily care about themselves, and are

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:52.320
[Amit Varma]: also not really of such strategic significance in that sense.

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:56.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, Srinath in his book talks about how Nehru's approach changed from, you

00:41:56.920 --> 00:42:02.000
[Amit Varma]: know, viewing Aksai Chen as a bargaining chip to something that is inherently part of India.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:07.040
[Amit Varma]: And as you correctly said, I will quote Nehru again, using the them and that formulation,

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:12.560
[Amit Varma]: where Nehru at one point said, quote, if I give them that, I shall no longer be prime

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:13.800
[Amit Varma]: minister of India.

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:15.120
[Amit Varma]: I will not do it.

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And by them, he means Chinese and by that he means Aksai Chen.

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:21.840
[Amit Varma]: So if I give the Chinese Aksai Chen, I shall no longer be prime minister, but that's something

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:22.840
[Amit Varma]: we'll come to later.

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:29.120
[Amit Varma]: Well, the larger question I sort of had is that how much of these almost, like to me,

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:35.200
[Amit Varma]: at least from my layman's perspective, a lot of these disputes seems so tragic to me, because

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:39.320
[Amit Varma]: it almost seems like that there is some historical dispute somewhere over reasons that no longer

00:42:39.320 --> 00:42:40.320
[Amit Varma]: apply.

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:43.760
[Amit Varma]: And then you get trapped in a chain of events and eventually millions of people die.

00:42:43.760 --> 00:42:45.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's just a natural way it flows out.

00:42:45.800 --> 00:42:46.800
[Guest 2]: Yeah, Hamsini?

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:50.440
[Guest 2]: Sorry, I just wanted to add to what Shabani was saying.

00:42:50.440 --> 00:42:54.280
[Guest 2]: And I think it's important to remember that the Cold War was taking off.

00:42:54.280 --> 00:43:01.200
[Guest 2]: But it's also important to remember that both Nehru and Mao were at the heads of these new

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:05.920
[Guest 2]: volatile states that were large and that everyone expected to fail, right?

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:11.520
[Guest 2]: So you had these extremely large, poor, populous states that were formed.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:15.640
[Guest 2]: And neither of their borders were what they are today.

00:43:15.640 --> 00:43:19.040
[Guest 2]: At that point in time, your borders were lines in a map.

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:22.920
[Guest 2]: They weren't even fortified with wires or anything.

00:43:22.920 --> 00:43:25.840
[Guest 2]: And I think that's why it was important.

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:31.880
[Guest 2]: India went through the experience of partition, which Nehru, I think, personally also experienced

00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:37.600
[Guest 2]: because of where his home was and so on, and him having sort of the cultural identity of

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:39.200
[Guest 2]: being a Kashmiri Pandit.

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:45.440
[Guest 2]: And I think, therefore, even if he didn't care personally about two kilometers of barren

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest 2]: land, it's about what that symbolized, particularly when you have a belligerent Pakistan on one

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:00.000
[Guest 2]: side, when you have treasures erupting, when you still have the union not officially formed.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:03.160
[Guest 2]: And I think, on the other hand, it's very important to remember that China was going

00:44:03.160 --> 00:44:08.120
[Guest 2]: through the exact same experience of consolidating all of its borders.

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:10.720
[Guest 2]: At that point in time, Tibet was still autonomous.

00:44:10.720 --> 00:44:12.480
[Guest 2]: Hong Kong was under the British.

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:16.600
[Guest 2]: Macau was under the Portuguese.

00:44:16.600 --> 00:44:21.040
[Guest 2]: Inner Mongolia was still officially not a part of the People's Republic.

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:23.160
[Guest 2]: Xinjiang was very disputed.

00:44:23.160 --> 00:44:28.800
[Guest 2]: None of the borders that China had in the 1940s were absolute.

00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:35.760
[Guest 2]: And for China, I think it also felt that it bordered the Soviet Union, which was, I think,

00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:38.800
[Guest 2]: about 4,300 kilometers of land.

00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:43.480
[Guest 2]: And their relationship, though, was heavily influencing the Communist Party, did turn

00:44:43.480 --> 00:44:45.520
[Guest 2]: sour at one point in time.

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:47.280
[Guest 2]: So that threat was present.

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:53.320
[Guest 2]: And the Chinese were also afraid that India was sort of being forced by these imperialists

00:44:53.320 --> 00:44:59.120
[Guest 2]: because India also had an imperialist history to sort of do what the U.S. wanted and to

00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:00.880
[Guest 2]: do what the imperialists wanted.

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:07.640
[Guest 2]: So I don't think it's merely about having these small historical disputes that no one

00:45:07.640 --> 00:45:08.640
[Guest 2]: cared about.

00:45:08.640 --> 00:45:14.400
[Guest 2]: I think if you go back to the 1940s, this is everything, because if you give up on this

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:22.000
[Guest 2]: land, then it's sort of you giving up on your idea of India, which is two years old.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:25.320
[Guest 2]: And you don't have nationalisms like you do now.

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:32.600
[Guest 2]: You have a lot more at stake by giving up these two kilometers of land, is what I think.

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:33.600
[Amit Varma]: That's very insightful.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:37.800
[Amit Varma]: And sort of a couple of thoughts came to my mind while you were going through that.

00:45:37.800 --> 00:45:42.880
[Amit Varma]: And one is that it's interesting that while, you know, both Mao and Nehru were in charge

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:48.120
[Amit Varma]: of relatively sort of new regimes or new nations as they were then, they came to power very

00:45:48.120 --> 00:45:53.280
[Amit Varma]: differently where, you know, Nehru kind of came to power through, you know, classic Congress

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:56.520
[Amit Varma]: moderation, statesmanship, diplomacy, and blah, blah, blah.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:46:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, those values also come into play when he's actually prime minister.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:04.600
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, Mao is the quintessential guerrilla warfare guy.

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:08.400
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, to some extent, that probably influences him.

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:15.440
[Amit Varma]: So just looking at sort of, it's not only that these individuals were impacted by the

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:17.120
[Amit Varma]: way they came to power.

00:46:17.120 --> 00:46:21.960
[Amit Varma]: But given that these were the paths to power, it was almost inevitable that the individuals

00:46:21.960 --> 00:46:28.520
[Amit Varma]: who eventually emerged on top would be individuals like Nehru and Mao, respectively.

00:46:28.520 --> 00:46:34.680
[Amit Varma]: The other thought that strikes me is that despite all the rhetoric about, you know,

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:38.840
[Amit Varma]: non-alignment, and we just want to live peacefully with everybody and all of that, the bottom

00:46:38.840 --> 00:46:44.800
[Amit Varma]: line is that the Indian Union coming together after the British left could also be described

00:46:44.800 --> 00:46:49.640
[Amit Varma]: as a profound act of imperialism, because you have one central government sort of taking

00:46:49.640 --> 00:46:56.640
[Amit Varma]: over these hundreds of princely states, sometimes with, you know, cunningly cajoling them and

00:46:56.640 --> 00:47:02.600
[Amit Varma]: breaking promises later, as we know happened, and sometimes with the threat of force and

00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:05.780
[Amit Varma]: sometimes with force itself.

00:47:05.780 --> 00:47:12.560
[Amit Varma]: So to after that typical scene unseen digression, we shall now get back to Shibani and to take

00:47:12.560 --> 00:47:18.400
[Amit Varma]: us through the 50s, like obviously, the whole takeover of Tibet happens around 1950.

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:24.080
[Amit Varma]: But also take us through what is Nehru's approach to foreign policy, what is Mao's approach

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:25.080
[Amit Varma]: to foreign policy?

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:27.640
[Amit Varma]: How do they look at each other?

00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:31.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, where does Patel differ with Nehru, for example?

00:47:31.040 --> 00:47:34.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, what is Chu and Lai's role in all this?

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sense of that background.

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:43.160
[Guest 1]: So if you look at like, there's a digital archive, which has, you know, a lot of these

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:49.360
[Guest 1]: conversations between the Indian leadership and the Chinese leadership recorded that anyone

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:50.720
[Guest 1]: can access.

00:47:50.720 --> 00:47:57.000
[Guest 1]: And if you look at the minutes of Chairman Mao's first meeting with Nehru, which happens

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:04.520
[Guest 1]: in October 1954, they're talking about Sino-Indian relations, they're talking about the political

00:48:04.520 --> 00:48:11.760
[Guest 1]: situation in Asia, both countries acknowledge that they have suffered from oppression, and

00:48:11.760 --> 00:48:17.400
[Guest 1]: that going forward, both of them need to play an important role in Asia, because they are

00:48:17.400 --> 00:48:22.280
[Guest 1]: the biggest nation states in the region.

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:29.560
[Guest 1]: There is an understanding that they will both pursue rapid development, they're both like

00:48:29.560 --> 00:48:36.320
[Guest 1]: agricultural societies that want to industrialize quickly, and that this, you know, chase for

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:41.640
[Guest 1]: development should not frighten the other so called smaller states in Asia, which is

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:47.840
[Guest 1]: why you have the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, or the Punch Shield, which was

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:52.720
[Guest 1]: actually incidentally signed in the same year earlier that time.

00:48:52.720 --> 00:49:00.520
[Guest 1]: So there is an agreement in terms of what needs to be done in the region between the

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:01.520
[Guest 1]: two.

00:49:01.520 --> 00:49:10.920
[Guest 1]: But there is also mistrust, Mao viewed Nehru as this Western educated leader who could

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:18.520
[Guest 1]: not be fully trusted, because Mao felt that Nehru would lean towards Western ideologies

00:49:18.520 --> 00:49:24.520
[Guest 1]: and you know, would have a soft corner for the institutions that he himself did not believe

00:49:24.520 --> 00:49:27.600
[Guest 1]: in and wanted to challenge.

00:49:27.600 --> 00:49:35.400
[Guest 1]: On the other hand, there are declassified CIA files that say that Nehru was not sure

00:49:35.400 --> 00:49:42.640
[Guest 1]: of Chu Enlai and his sort of intentions, and he's quoted saying that he has cheated me

00:49:42.640 --> 00:49:48.800
[Guest 1]: multiple times, so no matter how many times we have discussions on the border, I'm not

00:49:48.800 --> 00:49:50.600
[Guest 1]: sure I can believe him.

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:58.520
[Guest 1]: So there is that mistrust that we talk about between India and China even today, that exists,

00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:00.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, from the 50s.

00:50:00.640 --> 00:50:05.440
[Amit Varma]: And how does sort of the Chinese takeover of Tibet play into that when it happens in

00:50:05.440 --> 00:50:06.440
[Amit Varma]: 1950?

00:50:06.440 --> 00:50:11.600
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, Nehru is almost inclined, it seems at that time to sort of not take

00:50:11.600 --> 00:50:16.760
[Amit Varma]: an aggressive note and give them the benefit of the doubt, while, you know, Vallabhbhai

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:21.800
[Amit Varma]: Patel, you know, famously in a note to Nehru said that, you know, this throws, quote, into

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:26.960
[Amit Varma]: the melting pot, all frontier and commercial settlement, stop quote, you know, I mean,

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:33.560
[Amit Varma]: he kind of saw it, he described the northeastern frontier as one with, quote, unlimited scope

00:50:33.560 --> 00:50:38.520
[Amit Varma]: for infiltration, stop quote, and also added, and that might be true to the current day

00:50:38.520 --> 00:50:44.280
[Amit Varma]: for good reason, that quote, the people inhabiting those oceans have no established loyalty to

00:50:44.280 --> 00:50:45.840
[Amit Varma]: India, stop quote.

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:50.200
[Amit Varma]: But leaving aside what Patel kind of feels about it, you know, what does the takeover

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:55.220
[Amit Varma]: of Tibet kind of shake the relationships and how do they then, you know, those border disputes

00:50:55.220 --> 00:50:59.440
[Amit Varma]: are still sort of being discussed, how does all of that proceed for the rest of that decade

00:50:59.440 --> 00:51:00.440
[Amit Varma]: up to 1959?

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:02.440
[Amit Varma]: When, of course, it all blows up.

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:07.320
[Guest 1]: So I have a very brief point to make here and then Hamsini can take over.

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:15.800
[Guest 1]: But with respect to Tibet, I think China felt that India was interfering within its sovereign

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:16.800
[Guest 1]: territory.

00:51:16.800 --> 00:51:18.760
[Guest 1]: And that was not acceptable.

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:22.000
[Guest 1]: Whereas India didn't view it that way.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:25.960
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I think what Shivani has pointed out is very important.

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:30.520
[Guest 2]: You know, the way I think about the 1950s often is that, you know, we sort of celebrated

00:51:30.520 --> 00:51:34.240
[Guest 2]: with, you know, the non-alignment movement and Panjshir and everything that Shivani talked

00:51:34.240 --> 00:51:35.240
[Guest 2]: about.

00:51:35.240 --> 00:51:39.240
[Guest 2]: And there was this real sense of feeling that here are these two countries that are very

00:51:39.240 --> 00:51:46.400
[Guest 2]: similar and facing challenges and could possibly lead the third world, right?

00:51:46.400 --> 00:51:52.120
[Guest 2]: And something that I came across in some of my readings recently is statistical exchanges

00:51:52.120 --> 00:51:54.480
[Guest 2]: between India and China, for example.

00:51:54.480 --> 00:52:00.040
[Guest 2]: The Chinese rejected a lot of statistics as a discipline that took place.

00:52:00.040 --> 00:52:05.800
[Guest 2]: And they said that there was a need for socialist statistics to come about and things like that.

00:52:05.800 --> 00:52:07.040
[Guest 2]: It's very, very fascinating.

00:52:07.040 --> 00:52:11.480
[Guest 2]: Arnab Ghosh has a book called Making It Count.

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:14.720
[Guest 2]: And I had a podcast episode with him recently.

00:52:14.720 --> 00:52:21.200
[Guest 2]: And he was talking about how during the 1950s, you even had some Chinese statisticians come

00:52:21.200 --> 00:52:24.320
[Guest 2]: over and train with PC Mahalnobis.

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:29.920
[Guest 2]: And PC Mahalnobis was invited by Zhou Enlai to go to China and deliver lectures.

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:36.480
[Guest 2]: And that was something that you didn't really see particularly at that period of time, these

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:41.800
[Guest 2]: exchanges that are happening very under the radar, that are very technical, but still

00:52:41.800 --> 00:52:46.760
[Guest 2]: count rather than these big picture things that we think of otherwise.

00:52:46.760 --> 00:52:52.120
[Guest 2]: Moving on to Tibet, and I think Shabani raised again a very, very pertinent point, which

00:52:52.120 --> 00:52:57.800
[Guest 2]: is that the Chinese saw it as interference within their internal affairs, whereas the

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:00.320
[Guest 2]: Indians perceived it differently.

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:06.160
[Guest 2]: And the Indians perceived it differently because even the 13th Dalai Lama, the Dalai Lama before

00:53:06.160 --> 00:53:10.720
[Guest 2]: the present one, had served out a period of his exile in India.

00:53:10.720 --> 00:53:17.880
[Guest 2]: And so there was a lot of exchanges that were happening between the Tibetans and the Indians.

00:53:17.880 --> 00:53:24.480
[Guest 2]: And Nehru had met the 14th Dalai Lama in Beijing, and the 14th Dalai Lama, I think, had come

00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:30.080
[Guest 2]: down for Buddha Jayanti celebrations or something like that a year before he fled.

00:53:30.080 --> 00:53:37.520
[Guest 2]: And so the takeover of Tibet was something that was seen as a natural part of Chinese

00:53:37.520 --> 00:53:42.120
[Guest 2]: history and it still continued to be seen in that manner.

00:53:42.120 --> 00:53:50.320
[Guest 2]: But this was definitely sort of a pivotal point in the relationship because China was

00:53:50.320 --> 00:54:01.680
[Guest 2]: convinced of India's role in aiding Tibetan rebels in that there were covert CIA operations

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:08.960
[Guest 2]: that were happening in Sikkim and all of this was part of the giant imperialist plot.

00:54:08.960 --> 00:54:15.600
[Guest 2]: And I think this also may have hardened the Chinese stance on the border.

00:54:15.600 --> 00:54:20.880
[Amit Varma]: So you know, let's kind of get to the subject which Indians like to avoid, unless they are

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:24.240
[Amit Varma]: Indians who don't like Nehru, in which case they keep coming back to it.

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:29.520
[Amit Varma]: But you know, leading up to sort of the 1962 war and before that, you have things kind

00:54:29.520 --> 00:54:37.320
[Amit Varma]: of beginning to fall apart in 1959 and 1959 seems to me in some ways to almost be similar

00:54:37.320 --> 00:54:41.800
[Amit Varma]: to modern times where, you know, there almost seems to be this naive expectation from the

00:54:41.800 --> 00:54:45.720
[Amit Varma]: Indian side that, oh, you know, nothing will really happen at the border and it's cool

00:54:45.720 --> 00:54:47.120
[Amit Varma]: and we're all chill.

00:54:47.120 --> 00:54:50.840
[Amit Varma]: And then suddenly there are these attacks and Indian soldiers die and it's like what's

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:52.120
[Amit Varma]: going on.

00:54:52.120 --> 00:54:55.820
[Amit Varma]: And you know, take me through sort of what are the issues there?

00:54:55.820 --> 00:54:57.720
[Amit Varma]: Why do those skirmishes happen?

00:54:57.720 --> 00:55:00.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, how are the Indians looking at China at that point in time?

00:55:00.760 --> 00:55:05.520
[Amit Varma]: And the Chinese, as you guys mentioned, obviously are suspicious because they are just worried

00:55:05.520 --> 00:55:12.280
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, India will continue the imperialism of their predecessor colonial power, so to

00:55:12.280 --> 00:55:13.280
[Guest 2]: say.

00:55:13.280 --> 00:55:14.280
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:15.280
[Guest 2]: So I can get into what happened.

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:20.240
[Guest 2]: And I think before you dive into 1959, Amit, I think it's important to go to 1957.

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:28.600
[Guest 2]: And what happens in 1957 is that China constructs a highway from Xinjiang to Tibet, all the

00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:29.800
[Guest 2]: way to Lhasa.

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:32.160
[Guest 2]: And this cuts across Aksai Chin.

00:55:32.160 --> 00:55:38.820
[Guest 2]: And this really surprised the Indians because they hadn't imagined that a project like this

00:55:38.820 --> 00:55:39.820
[Guest 2]: could have taken place.

00:55:39.820 --> 00:55:43.520
[Guest 2]: At that point in time, the highway was still sort of cavel stones, right?

00:55:43.520 --> 00:55:48.480
[Guest 2]: It's not a six-way lane in which we imagine highways today.

00:55:48.480 --> 00:55:53.880
[Guest 2]: But this was still a road through a boundary that the Indians considered disputed.

00:55:53.880 --> 00:56:02.000
[Guest 2]: And therefore, this also steered the Indian stance on taking a harsher line to the border.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:08.880
[Guest 2]: And so you have two clashes in 1959, one in what we used to call the Northeast frontier

00:56:08.880 --> 00:56:17.120
[Guest 2]: region, the Arunachal Pradesh, Arnefa, and one in Ladakh, which is still disputed.

00:56:17.120 --> 00:56:25.400
[Guest 2]: And so what happens with the fallout of these two clashes is that China offered that both

00:56:25.400 --> 00:56:32.600
[Guest 2]: countries fall back by 20 kilometers in Ladakh, and they don't violate the Makmohan line in

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:33.600
[Guest 1]: the East.

00:56:33.600 --> 00:56:41.920
[Guest 1]: So, yeah, talking about what Hamsini said, that, you know, the conflict that led to the

00:56:41.920 --> 00:56:48.480
[Guest 1]: 1962 war started in the fifties, and I would go even further back to say that it started

00:56:48.480 --> 00:56:51.320
[Guest 1]: in 1954.

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:56.320
[Guest 1]: This is when India published new maps that included Aksai Chin within the boundaries

00:56:56.320 --> 00:56:58.000
[Guest 1]: of India.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:06.240
[Guest 1]: And when it discovered the highway, Nehru sort of, you know, called up Chou Enlai and

00:57:06.240 --> 00:57:08.640
[Guest 1]: said, what's going on?

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:14.440
[Guest 1]: And Chou sort of reassured him multiple times that, you know, there was an error and that

00:57:14.440 --> 00:57:18.600
[Guest 1]: the maps needed, like, revising.

00:57:18.600 --> 00:57:24.520
[Guest 1]: There wasn't actually any sort of crossing of the line, so to say.

00:57:24.520 --> 00:57:30.760
[Guest 1]: And there were multiple conversations around this, which also led to an increase in suspicion

00:57:30.760 --> 00:57:33.280
[Guest 1]: towards China that Nehru felt.

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:41.160
[Guest 1]: This is also evident in the fact that, in how Nehru sort of tackled China within his

00:57:41.160 --> 00:57:42.160
[Guest 1]: office.

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:50.800
[Guest 1]: So, G. Parthasarathy, who was the Indian envoy to China at the time, was asked to bypass

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:58.160
[Guest 1]: the defense minister, who was Mr. Menon at the time, and bring in all communications

00:57:58.160 --> 00:58:01.800
[Guest 1]: related to China directly to Nehru.

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:09.400
[Guest 1]: Again, Nehru, I would sort of call this, you know, fog in foreign policy.

00:58:09.400 --> 00:58:14.600
[Guest 1]: Fog is actually a strategic studies term where you talk about the uncertainty on the battlefield

00:58:14.600 --> 00:58:21.200
[Guest 1]: in times of war, but you also see it happening in foreign policy, where the leadership is

00:58:21.200 --> 00:58:26.520
[Guest 1]: unsure about what the other side is doing, there's information asymmetry, and you're

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:29.280
[Guest 1]: not sure who you can trust.

00:58:29.280 --> 00:58:34.520
[Guest 1]: The same way Nehru was not sure that the defense minister could be trusted because of his leanings

00:58:34.520 --> 00:58:39.160
[Guest 1]: towards the left, and he felt that he would be sympathetic to the Chinese, so he should

00:58:39.160 --> 00:58:41.200
[Guest 1]: be bypassed.

00:58:41.200 --> 00:58:48.200
[Guest 1]: And that sort of brings us to what Hamsini was saying, where the highway was discovered.

00:58:48.200 --> 00:58:56.160
[Guest 1]: And in 1960, Chou En-lai proposed that India drop the claim to Aksai Chin.

00:58:56.160 --> 00:59:00.840
[Guest 1]: And if India were to do that, China would, you know, withdraw its claim from the Northeast

00:59:00.840 --> 00:59:03.560
[Guest 1]: Frontier Agency.

00:59:03.560 --> 00:59:10.240
[Guest 1]: This was not a subtle move on the part of the Chinese, and, you know, Chou consistently

00:59:10.240 --> 00:59:14.500
[Guest 1]: refused to accept the legitimacy of India's territorial claims.

00:59:14.500 --> 00:59:20.040
[Guest 1]: So it was, I think, a very frustrating round of negotiations between India and China that

00:59:20.040 --> 00:59:27.760
[Guest 1]: I think Chou tried so many times that within 1960, he visited India four times.

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:31.840
[Guest 1]: And the meetings, if you read the transcripts, they go on for hours.

00:59:31.840 --> 00:59:39.560
[Guest 1]: So it was an increasingly frustrating process, and neither side was willing to sort of back

00:59:39.560 --> 00:59:42.400
[Guest 1]: down on its claim.

00:59:42.400 --> 00:59:49.320
[Guest 1]: In hindsight, a lot of people argue that Nehru should have taken the deal, and all future

00:59:49.320 --> 00:59:55.200
[Guest 1]: conflict could have been avoided, 1962 could have definitely been avoided.

00:59:55.200 --> 01:00:02.200
[Guest 1]: But I would say, like, in my understanding of international relations, there are no guarantees.

01:00:02.200 --> 01:00:08.760
[Guest 1]: We cannot say that had India taken that deal or made that compromise at that time, we would

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:15.640
[Guest 1]: not be sitting here recording this podcast discussing the exact same things that we are

01:00:15.640 --> 01:00:16.640
[Guest 1]: today.

01:00:16.640 --> 01:00:22.080
[Guest 1]: So yeah, I mean, you will always be blamed for things that you didn't do.

01:00:22.080 --> 01:00:28.920
[Guest 1]: Nehru did not have the political capital at the time to justify taking on the deal.

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:33.800
[Guest 1]: And like I said before, if you are a leader, you want to wake up and still be the leader

01:00:33.800 --> 01:00:35.160
[Guest 1]: of the country.

01:00:35.160 --> 01:00:39.680
[Guest 1]: So that is a big consideration for any decision that you make.

01:00:39.680 --> 01:00:44.800
[Amit Varma]: No, and I'm very pleased at the implication that the recording of this episode is not

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:48.240
[Amit Varma]: contingent on random historical events.

01:00:48.240 --> 01:00:52.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, you're talking about, I have a quote from Chauhan Lai where he visited India in

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:53.680
[Amit Varma]: April 1960.

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:54.680
[Amit Varma]: This was his April trip.

01:00:54.680 --> 01:00:59.960
[Amit Varma]: As you said, he came a number of times that year, where he says, quote, I have come here

01:00:59.960 --> 01:01:04.440
[Amit Varma]: to seek a solution and not to repeat arguments, stop quote.

01:01:04.440 --> 01:01:06.720
[Amit Varma]: So you get a sense of what is going on through his head.

01:01:06.720 --> 01:01:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And earlier, one of you mentioned that Nehru didn't like him because he was like, this

01:01:10.320 --> 01:01:12.040
[Amit Varma]: guy is always cheating me.

01:01:12.040 --> 01:01:16.320
[Amit Varma]: So this is sort of the mutual distrust that is going on.

01:01:16.320 --> 01:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And also at this time, sort of what the Indians do is they have a strategy which is called,

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:27.080
[Amit Varma]: I think, the forward strategy or the forward policy where, you know, the approach is that

01:01:27.080 --> 01:01:31.560
[Amit Varma]: whatever is disputed territory, you don't cross that.

01:01:31.560 --> 01:01:36.640
[Amit Varma]: But you set up Indian outposts over there aggressively so that the Chinese don't come

01:01:36.640 --> 01:01:37.840
[Amit Varma]: over.

01:01:37.840 --> 01:01:42.080
[Amit Varma]: And India apparently did that in, I think, up to 60, if I remember correctly, 60 outposts

01:01:42.080 --> 01:01:43.080
[Amit Varma]: of this sort.

01:01:43.080 --> 01:01:45.680
[Amit Varma]: And the Chinese viewed it as almost an act of war.

01:01:45.680 --> 01:01:48.280
[Amit Varma]: It's like, you know, they are creeping closer and closer.

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:54.400
[Amit Varma]: And all these areas on either side of whatever those de facto borders are, were sort of unoccupied.

01:01:54.400 --> 01:01:56.240
[Amit Varma]: And why are they setting up so many posts?

01:01:56.240 --> 01:02:01.200
[Amit Varma]: And that was kind of what sparked the whole thing off and what sort of interests me.

01:02:01.200 --> 01:02:06.880
[Amit Varma]: And this is also sort of a subject that is pertinent today and is going to be wherever

01:02:06.880 --> 01:02:07.880
[Amit Varma]: there is politics.

01:02:07.880 --> 01:02:08.880
[Amit Varma]: This will be pertinent.

01:02:08.880 --> 01:02:13.360
[Amit Varma]: These are the incentives of politicians, whereas, you know, we've earlier discussed how Nehru

01:02:13.360 --> 01:02:16.640
[Amit Varma]: said that, look, I want to wake up tomorrow morning as prime minister.

01:02:16.640 --> 01:02:20.680
[Amit Varma]: And it is, you know, not going to be possible if I give away Aksai Chen.

01:02:20.680 --> 01:02:23.520
[Amit Varma]: And there are stories about how, you know, within the Congress, he was under pressure

01:02:23.520 --> 01:02:27.920
[Amit Varma]: to do something and to ramp up the sort of the aggression.

01:02:27.920 --> 01:02:31.760
[Amit Varma]: How much, in your view, does politics drive all of this?

01:02:31.760 --> 01:02:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And to me, it's, you know, when I look at the incentives of politicians, it's very sort

01:02:37.120 --> 01:02:42.280
[Amit Varma]: of much easier to understand what the incentives of politicians in India are like Nehru then

01:02:42.280 --> 01:02:47.320
[Amit Varma]: or Modi today, that you cannot be seen to back down beyond the point, which is possibly,

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:51.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, why Chou Enlai could have understood that and framed the whole thing differently

01:02:51.560 --> 01:02:54.040
[Amit Varma]: so that Nehru could have had a face saving way out.

01:02:54.040 --> 01:02:58.240
[Amit Varma]: And we would still be recording this episode, but he could have had a face saving way out.

01:02:58.240 --> 01:03:02.720
[Amit Varma]: But I'm sort of a little baffled by what are the incentives on the Chinese side, like what

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:08.000
[Amit Varma]: are Chou's incentives, what are Mao's incentives, you know, and today and a question we'll come

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:12.760
[Amit Varma]: to much later also in the episode is what are Xi's incentives today, for example, what

01:03:12.760 --> 01:03:17.800
[Amit Varma]: were Hu's incentives in the early 2000s, where he was, you know, far friendlier.

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:19.800
[Amit Varma]: So can you guys shed some light on that?

01:03:19.800 --> 01:03:23.680
[Amit Varma]: What constituencies are they playing to and what is driving them?

01:03:23.680 --> 01:03:31.040
[Guest 2]: So I think there's, it's very important to look at China in the 1960s, right?

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:37.800
[Guest 2]: This is right after Mao started his great leap forward, steel is being melted around

01:03:37.800 --> 01:03:41.320
[Guest 2]: the country so that it can be poured into industries.

01:03:41.320 --> 01:03:44.720
[Guest 2]: And that's what's happening domestically.

01:03:44.720 --> 01:03:49.960
[Guest 2]: But this is also the time when there's something called the Ita incident that happens in Xinjiang,

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:54.680
[Guest 2]: where about 60,000 Kazakhs suddenly flee from Xinjiang.

01:03:54.680 --> 01:04:01.880
[Guest 2]: And so the Chinese realized that they really need to start putting up definite boundaries.

01:04:01.880 --> 01:04:10.160
[Guest 2]: So the 1960s are a period when China had boundary issues with countries all over, right?

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:18.120
[Guest 2]: But it managed to, at this period of time, 1960 to 1963, 65, settle its boundaries with

01:04:18.120 --> 01:04:21.320
[Guest 2]: Pakistan, settle its boundaries with Myanmar.

01:04:21.320 --> 01:04:28.000
[Guest 2]: And that's very interesting for me, because when you look at why would China resolve its

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:31.440
[Guest 2]: boundaries with Pakistan and Myanmar, but not with India.

01:04:31.440 --> 01:04:36.320
[Guest 2]: And there's this book by M. Taylor Francis called Strong Borders, Secure Nation.

01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:43.960
[Guest 2]: And it's really fascinating, because what it suggests is that rather than simplifying

01:04:43.960 --> 01:04:50.960
[Guest 2]: it as whenever China has been in internal strife, it seeks to be more aggressive on

01:04:50.960 --> 01:04:54.080
[Guest 2]: the outside, is something that we hear even today.

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:58.200
[Guest 2]: You know, China is going through this COVID pandemic, needs to deflect, and therefore

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:00.120
[Guest 2]: it's being more aggressive.

01:05:00.120 --> 01:05:06.160
[Guest 2]: But I think what the book argues, and what I think makes a lot of sense, is that whenever

01:05:06.160 --> 01:05:13.400
[Guest 2]: China has faced internal crises, whether it is Tibet or Taiwan or Xinjiang, it's been

01:05:13.400 --> 01:05:22.640
[Guest 2]: more open to compromise and cooperation, whereas if it's had external threats or crises, it's

01:05:22.640 --> 01:05:25.600
[Guest 2]: been more prone to aggression.

01:05:25.600 --> 01:05:33.600
[Guest 2]: So how this would play out in the India-Pakistan scenario, for example, is that China was going

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:39.680
[Guest 2]: through the crises in Tibet, it was going through a crisis in Xinjiang, and of course

01:05:39.680 --> 01:05:44.880
[Guest 2]: facing off with Taiwan, apart from the Great Leap Forward, which is ongoing.

01:05:44.880 --> 01:05:49.280
[Guest 2]: So this is a period of internal strife.

01:05:49.280 --> 01:05:55.320
[Guest 2]: And therefore, they did not want to have to deal with border wars, with the Pakistan border,

01:05:55.320 --> 01:05:56.320
[Guest 2]: for example.

01:05:56.320 --> 01:05:59.840
[Guest 2]: Pakistan was supposed to have reached out to China during this period of time in the

01:05:59.840 --> 01:06:03.440
[Guest 2]: 1960s, and the Chinese didn't get back to them.

01:06:03.440 --> 01:06:11.440
[Guest 2]: But as soon as the month-long border war happens with India, they immediately resolve their

01:06:11.440 --> 01:06:15.720
[Guest 2]: border differences with Pakistan and with Myanmar.

01:06:15.720 --> 01:06:20.600
[Guest 2]: And that's what's interesting for me, because it's not internal crises that's led them to

01:06:20.600 --> 01:06:25.260
[Guest 2]: resolve those boundaries, it's sort of the aggression with India.

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:30.600
[Guest 2]: So you can ask, hey, then why did we fight the boundary war with China?

01:06:30.600 --> 01:06:32.760
[Guest 2]: Why didn't Pakistan or Myanmar fight it?

01:06:32.760 --> 01:06:37.520
[Guest 2]: And the answer there could be in the forward policy that you'd mentioned, Amit.

01:06:37.520 --> 01:06:45.360
[Guest 2]: It could be that Mao had perceived this policy as external aggression, coupled with whatever

01:06:45.360 --> 01:06:52.360
[Guest 2]: was happening in Tibet, and therefore construing all of this as sort of expansionism that needed

01:06:52.360 --> 01:06:53.880
[Guest 2]: to be taught a lesson.

01:06:53.880 --> 01:06:57.640
[Guest 2]: That's a quote that's often come, right, India needs to be taught a lesson, is something

01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:00.760
[Guest 2]: that Mao supposedly said.

01:07:00.760 --> 01:07:10.360
[Guest 2]: And that's seen very clearly in what happened in terms of politics between Mao and Nehru.

01:07:10.360 --> 01:07:18.880
[Guest 1]: Just to add a bit of trivia for politics between Mao and Nehru, I read that Mao had actually

01:07:18.880 --> 01:07:26.400
[Guest 1]: told Nehru that he would like to discuss with him war as a policy instrument, and what were

01:07:26.400 --> 01:07:34.120
[Guest 1]: Nehru's thoughts on it, if war became the instrument of statecraft.

01:07:34.120 --> 01:07:40.080
[Guest 1]: And this is happening in the backdrop of Tibet and India and China discussing how they need

01:07:40.080 --> 01:07:47.000
[Guest 1]: to be responsible Asian powers.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:51.800
[Guest 1]: So yeah, that is an interesting bit of detail I wanted to add.

01:07:51.800 --> 01:07:56.680
[Guest 2]: I think the other important thing, and this is something that Bertil Lintner says, is

01:07:56.680 --> 01:08:02.880
[Guest 2]: that it could have sort of been a strategy, whereas, you know, for example, Mao had his

01:08:02.880 --> 01:08:10.840
[Guest 2]: disdain for Nehru and this idea of teaching India a lesson, whereas Zhou Enlai was entrusted

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:16.960
[Guest 2]: with keeping India guessing about China's actual intentions, you know.

01:08:16.960 --> 01:08:23.480
[Guest 2]: And I think what scholars have said at various points with Zhou is that he genuinely attempted

01:08:23.480 --> 01:08:28.880
[Guest 2]: to, you know, impress on Nehru that India should meet China halfway.

01:08:28.880 --> 01:08:34.200
[Guest 2]: And what's evident with the other countries is that they sort of signaled a willingness

01:08:34.200 --> 01:08:36.640
[Guest 2]: to meet China halfway.

01:08:36.640 --> 01:08:41.600
[Guest 2]: And with the Pakistan border, if you look at it, China actually granted them some extra

01:08:41.600 --> 01:08:45.720
[Guest 2]: territory and took very little in return.

01:08:45.720 --> 01:08:52.600
[Guest 2]: And so that was sort of taken as an example of China's benevolence, you know, and look

01:08:52.600 --> 01:08:54.840
[Guest 2]: at how we deal with our smaller neighbors.

01:08:54.840 --> 01:09:00.240
[Guest 2]: Most of these deals are made at our own cost, whereas their cost was just that they wanted

01:09:00.240 --> 01:09:04.380
[Guest 2]: these borders to be sealed and to not have any loopholes with them.

01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:09.000
[Guest 2]: So this could have also been sort of another factor that was dealing in the politics between

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:10.000
[Guest 2]: people.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:13.960
[Amit Varma]: No, and I want to get a wise track out of the way before I get on to my observations,

01:09:13.960 --> 01:09:18.920
[Amit Varma]: which is when, you know, when Mao said we want to teach India a lesson, maybe he recognized

01:09:18.920 --> 01:09:22.680
[Amit Varma]: how broken our education system is, and it still is today.

01:09:22.680 --> 01:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: So perhaps Nehru should have let him.

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:29.640
[Amit Varma]: But the irony of all this is that if you look at, you know, how the alignments are happening,

01:09:29.640 --> 01:09:33.320
[Amit Varma]: despite all our claims of being non-aligned and all that, if you look at all the alignments,

01:09:33.320 --> 01:09:37.920
[Amit Varma]: the Chinese in the 50s actually looked at Pakistan with a little bit of suspicion because

01:09:37.920 --> 01:09:44.000
[Amit Varma]: hey, Pakistan is aligning with the US and it made complete sense for the Soviets, China

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.360
[Amit Varma]: and India to kind of form a block.

01:09:46.360 --> 01:09:50.280
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you know, when the 59 skirmishes happen and all that, and the Soviets make

01:09:50.280 --> 01:09:55.120
[Amit Varma]: a statement in favor of India, initially, you know, it's a little bit awkward.

01:09:55.120 --> 01:09:58.840
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, Khrushchev and Mao meet and they have some interesting dialogues.

01:09:58.840 --> 01:10:04.260
[Amit Varma]: And then the moment that Mao really chooses to step up Chinese aggression in 62 is when

01:10:04.260 --> 01:10:09.480
[Amit Varma]: he knows that hey, US and Soviets are going to be busy because a Cuban crisis is happening.

01:10:09.480 --> 01:10:11.960
[Amit Varma]: So he's like, okay, they are busy here.

01:10:11.960 --> 01:10:18.220
[Amit Varma]: Let us bully this kid in our, in sort of our neighborhood.

01:10:18.220 --> 01:10:22.560
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that also strikes me is that something that Mao actually articulated

01:10:22.560 --> 01:10:27.520
[Amit Varma]: and which would not have been a mystery at the time, is that China as far as it came

01:10:27.520 --> 01:10:32.520
[Amit Varma]: to, you know, South Asia was not interested in taking territory, as we see even after

01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:37.880
[Amit Varma]: the 62 war got over and in the offers of you and all, it's not like they wanted to conquer

01:10:37.880 --> 01:10:38.880
[Amit Varma]: anyone.

01:10:38.880 --> 01:10:42.360
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, what you just said in the context of Pakistan, at the moment, Pakistan agreed

01:10:42.360 --> 01:10:47.200
[Amit Varma]: to a deal, they actually gave them a little bit of territory makes sense, even, you know,

01:10:47.200 --> 01:10:51.560
[Amit Varma]: during the 62 war, their strategy was okay, we just drive the Indians out and we get back

01:10:51.560 --> 01:10:56.760
[Amit Varma]: to whatever the de facto line of control was, and then we call a ceasefire and we withdraw.

01:10:56.760 --> 01:10:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And that was the whole game.

01:10:58.200 --> 01:11:03.820
[Amit Varma]: So at some levels, you know, to get into that conflict, sort of end up kind of losing and

01:11:03.820 --> 01:11:10.160
[Amit Varma]: everything that happened, seems to me to, you know, constitute a series of self goals.

01:11:10.160 --> 01:11:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And I am so traumatized by the thought that I need a break.

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And I will share it with both of you and all our listeners.

01:11:18.160 --> 01:11:22.280
[Amit Varma]: Are you one of those people who loves to be surrounded by beauty, let's say you like contemporary

01:11:22.280 --> 01:11:27.240
[Amit Varma]: fine art, you want more of it in your life, but you don't have the time to visit galleries

01:11:27.240 --> 01:11:30.160
[Amit Varma]: and buying art to hang on your walls can be expensive.

01:11:30.160 --> 01:11:34.320
[Amit Varma]: Well, there is a way out, head on over to Indian colors.com.

