[Amit Varma]: Corporate gifting is also available.

01:12:29.320 --> 01:12:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So head on over to indiancolors.com.

01:12:32.200 --> 01:12:38.000
[Amit Varma]: That's colors with an OU and make art a part of your life.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:39.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen.

01:12:39.320 --> 01:12:44.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Hamsini Hariharan and Shibani Mehta on what I realize much to my embarrassment

01:12:44.880 --> 01:12:50.520
[Amit Varma]: is not Indo-China conflicts because that would involve Cambodia, but Sino-Indian conflicts.

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:51.520
[Guest 2]: Is that right Hamsini?

01:12:51.520 --> 01:12:53.520
[Amit Varma]: Yes, that's completely right.

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:12:54.520 --> 01:12:57.680
[Amit Varma]: So we are talking about Sino-Indian conflicts.

01:12:57.680 --> 01:13:03.960
[Amit Varma]: And we just finished chatting before the break about the 1962 war, you know, which we basically

01:13:03.960 --> 01:13:09.440
[Amit Varma]: ended up losing, but the Chinese philosophy was not really to, you know, a colonial one

01:13:09.440 --> 01:13:13.240
[Amit Varma]: of conquer territory and let us march to Delhi and all of that.

01:13:13.240 --> 01:13:18.920
[Amit Varma]: But you know, they kind of proved their point, established sort of the lines of control that

01:13:18.920 --> 01:13:21.240
[Amit Varma]: they wanted, and they headed back.

01:13:21.240 --> 01:13:23.920
[Amit Varma]: Now what's the deal with the aftermath of the war?

01:13:23.920 --> 01:13:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing which in an Indian context, everyone knows is that of course, VK Krishnamen

01:13:28.480 --> 01:13:31.960
[Amit Varma]: and the defense minister was kind of disgraced and he had to quit.

01:13:31.960 --> 01:13:38.560
[Amit Varma]: And all of that happened, which is, I think, what is known in the Indian popular imagination.

01:13:38.560 --> 01:13:43.680
[Amit Varma]: But give me a deeper sense of what is the aftermath between both countries?

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:45.920
[Amit Varma]: What are you mentioned that there was schools of thought on it?

01:13:45.920 --> 01:13:49.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that, because I find that fascinating.

01:13:49.320 --> 01:13:50.320
[Guest 2]: Sure.

01:13:50.320 --> 01:13:55.920
[Guest 2]: So I think whenever you're looking at the 1962 war, I didn't really want to get into

01:13:55.920 --> 01:14:00.400
[Guest 2]: sort of the specific, the war itself, because I'm not someone who served in the military

01:14:00.400 --> 01:14:04.560
[Guest 2]: and therefore, I would not be the best person to speak about it.

01:14:04.560 --> 01:14:11.400
[Guest 2]: But I think whenever you talk about the 1962 war, some clear strands really stick out at

01:14:11.400 --> 01:14:12.400
[Guest 2]: you, right?

01:14:12.400 --> 01:14:17.600
[Guest 2]: And the first is that, why did the Chinese withdraw in a month?

01:14:17.600 --> 01:14:21.960
[Guest 2]: Why didn't they march down to Delhi or why didn't they march down to Assam?

01:14:21.960 --> 01:14:24.720
[Guest 2]: And that is something that really came about.

01:14:24.720 --> 01:14:30.880
[Guest 2]: The second was this question that how could they construct a highway in 1959 that we spoke

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:32.100
[Guest 2]: about earlier?

01:14:32.100 --> 01:14:36.360
[Guest 2]: How could they rise to such commanding heights across this border?

01:14:36.360 --> 01:14:38.400
[Guest 2]: And we didn't even have a clue.

01:14:38.400 --> 01:14:42.160
[Guest 2]: So that intelligence failure was something that was repeatedly brought up.

01:14:42.160 --> 01:14:47.600
[Guest 2]: And the third was something that military historians still talk about, which is, why

01:14:47.600 --> 01:14:50.120
[Guest 2]: was offensive air power not used?

01:14:50.120 --> 01:14:55.300
[Guest 2]: We had the Indian Air Force, which was possibly one of the best air forces at that time.

01:14:55.300 --> 01:14:57.380
[Guest 2]: We had bases, we had aircraft.

01:14:57.380 --> 01:14:59.600
[Guest 2]: So why didn't we use these?

01:14:59.600 --> 01:15:02.680
[Guest 2]: So these were major questions that came about.

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:08.120
[Guest 2]: And I think, to be fair to the Indian establishment, they did take a lot of them into consideration.

01:15:08.120 --> 01:15:13.600
[Guest 2]: There was a clear effort by the Indian government to rehaul intelligence, for example.

01:15:13.600 --> 01:15:19.440
[Guest 2]: So this is when it was after the 1962 war that the R&AW, the Research and Analysis Wing,

01:15:19.440 --> 01:15:20.640
[Guest 2]: was finally formed.

01:15:20.640 --> 01:15:25.600
[Guest 2]: So you had a lot of internal reforms that took place.

01:15:25.600 --> 01:15:29.140
[Guest 2]: Now when you think about the war itself, the first question that I asked, which is, why

01:15:29.140 --> 01:15:31.880
[Guest 2]: did China just withdraw after a month?

01:15:31.880 --> 01:15:36.040
[Guest 2]: This is possibly one of the shortest wars that have taken place.

01:15:36.040 --> 01:15:42.280
[Guest 2]: You can look at the Sino-Indian conflict through two major schools of thought.

01:15:42.280 --> 01:15:48.600
[Guest 2]: And both of them come down to this report called the Henderson-Brooks-Bhagat Report.

01:15:48.600 --> 01:15:54.980
[Guest 2]: And the Henderson-Brooks-Bhagat Report is a report written by two Indian Armed Forces

01:15:54.980 --> 01:15:58.300
[Guest 2]: officers who were both serving at that point in time.

01:15:58.300 --> 01:16:03.560
[Guest 2]: And they'd written this report to point out that the Indian Army had intelligence, that

01:16:03.560 --> 01:16:09.120
[Guest 2]: they believed that the forward policy that we'd spoken about was erroneous in a way.

01:16:09.120 --> 01:16:18.260
[Guest 2]: And they pointed out clear gaps in the political vision of the border and of the tensions.

01:16:18.260 --> 01:16:22.160
[Guest 2]: And so that clear misreading was picked up.

01:16:22.160 --> 01:16:26.720
[Guest 2]: And the reason that the Henderson-Brooks-Bhagat Report is important is because the report

01:16:26.720 --> 01:16:31.960
[Guest 2]: got leaked and it got into the hands of this Australian journalist called Neville Maxwell,

01:16:31.960 --> 01:16:34.000
[Guest 2]: who didn't publish the report then.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:38.880
[Guest 2]: He published parts of the report and then retracted it in 2014 on his website.

01:16:38.880 --> 01:16:43.200
[Guest 2]: So before then, the only thing we could do was sort of take his word for it.

01:16:43.200 --> 01:16:48.800
[Guest 2]: And what Maxwell essentially did was write a book called India's China War, where he

01:16:48.800 --> 01:16:55.400
[Guest 2]: wrote a book along with other voices like Alistair Lamb, who writes his own book.

01:16:55.400 --> 01:16:59.400
[Guest 2]: And what these authors essentially argue is that Nehru was wrong.

01:16:59.400 --> 01:17:04.440
[Guest 2]: There were all of these glaring gaps in India's foreign policy.

01:17:04.440 --> 01:17:06.660
[Guest 2]: Nehru misread the situation.

01:17:06.660 --> 01:17:08.400
[Guest 2]: He was high handed.

01:17:08.400 --> 01:17:13.560
[Guest 2]: And it is clearly India's fault that they went ahead with the forward policy.

01:17:13.560 --> 01:17:16.840
[Guest 2]: And that's why the Chinese sort of struck back.

01:17:16.840 --> 01:17:24.120
[Guest 2]: And there's even a very funny anecdote of Zhou Enlai and Mao having sort of a state

01:17:24.120 --> 01:17:30.200
[Guest 2]: dinner with, I think, the Pakistani head of state, yeah, with Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto.

01:17:30.200 --> 01:17:33.680
[Guest 2]: And Neville Maxwell is there, this is 1971.

01:17:33.680 --> 01:17:39.440
[Guest 2]: And what Zhou does is he stands up and he calls for a toast.

01:17:39.440 --> 01:17:44.360
[Guest 2]: And through his interpreter, he tells Neville Maxwell, he says, Mr. Maxwell, your book

01:17:44.360 --> 01:17:46.360
[Guest 2]: has done a service to truth.

01:17:46.360 --> 01:17:49.320
[Guest 2]: And China has benefited from that, stop quote.

01:17:49.320 --> 01:17:55.760
[Guest 2]: So this is something that was immediately rubbished by a lot of Indian analysts, by

01:17:55.760 --> 01:17:56.760
[Guest 2]: the Indian public.

01:17:56.760 --> 01:18:02.280
[Guest 2]: Neville Maxwell had sort of a notorious reputation for being this China hand, as did Alistair

01:18:02.280 --> 01:18:03.400
[Guest 2]: Lamb.

01:18:03.400 --> 01:18:10.320
[Guest 2]: And to be fair, they raised a lot of pertinent questions that a lot of scholars at that point

01:18:10.320 --> 01:18:14.360
[Guest 2]: in time were possibly not able to justify.

01:18:14.360 --> 01:18:20.080
[Guest 2]: But I think it's also fair that a lot of criticisms have been leveled against them.

01:18:20.080 --> 01:18:24.960
[Guest 2]: In particular, there's a book that Bertil Lintner wrote recently called China's India

01:18:24.960 --> 01:18:27.240
[Guest 2]: War, which is a play on Maxwell's book.

01:18:27.240 --> 01:18:35.440
[Guest 2]: And Indian authors and Lintner, they systematically refute a lot of the claims that Maxwell and

01:18:35.440 --> 01:18:36.440
[Guest 2]: Lamb raised.

01:18:36.440 --> 01:18:41.200
[Guest 2]: For example, if you remember, in the first half of the podcast, we spoke about sort of

01:18:41.200 --> 01:18:44.160
[Guest 2]: this inner Tibet and outer Tibet, right?

01:18:44.160 --> 01:18:51.120
[Guest 2]: And that was sort of the basis for the 1914 McMohan Line.

01:18:51.120 --> 01:18:57.360
[Guest 2]: Lamb also points out that there was an inner line and an outer line in the Nifa region

01:18:57.360 --> 01:18:58.520
[Guest 2]: in the Northeast.

01:18:58.520 --> 01:19:04.840
[Guest 2]: And he says, the inner line was clearly what was put down by the British, which the inner

01:19:04.840 --> 01:19:10.720
[Guest 2]: line still exists in some parts of the Northeast today, which didn't allow mainland Indians

01:19:10.720 --> 01:19:13.300
[Guest 2]: in court to go to these regions.

01:19:13.300 --> 01:19:17.120
[Guest 2]: And so he says, you know, this inner line itself proved that the Indians did not have

01:19:17.120 --> 01:19:21.280
[Guest 2]: control over these regions, that these regions clearly came under South Tibet.

01:19:21.280 --> 01:19:26.240
[Guest 2]: And this inner line is supposed to end where the McMohan Line ends, and so on.

01:19:26.240 --> 01:19:31.420
[Guest 2]: And these claims are, a lot of them are misguided, a lot of them are just false.

01:19:31.420 --> 01:19:36.760
[Guest 2]: So what I would say is that most scholars today, whenever they're talking about the

01:19:36.760 --> 01:19:44.240
[Guest 2]: Sino-Indian War, follow one or two of these schools of thought. One believes that India

01:19:44.240 --> 01:19:51.200
[Guest 2]: was responsible for the war, that it triggered Chinese aggression through the forward policy.

01:19:51.200 --> 01:19:57.400
[Guest 2]: And the second believes that even if the forward policy was put down by Nehru, it was put down

01:19:57.400 --> 01:20:02.720
[Guest 2]: because India was triggered by what China was doing in the regions.

01:20:02.720 --> 01:20:08.040
[Guest 2]: So this is essentially how people categorize their views. The Maxwell Lamb School of Thought

01:20:08.040 --> 01:20:14.040
[Guest 2]: has really influenced the way debate about Sino-Indian relations has been done for a

01:20:14.040 --> 01:20:18.400
[Guest 2]: very long time. It's because their books came out in the 1970s. So they were possibly one

01:20:18.400 --> 01:20:23.960
[Guest 2]: of the first few authoritarian works that was written. But over the last couple of years,

01:20:23.960 --> 01:20:29.640
[Guest 2]: there's been more inquiry into the war. Yeah, so that's basically the two main schools of

01:20:29.640 --> 01:20:30.640
[Amit Varma]: thought.

01:20:30.640 --> 01:20:34.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so let me let me kind of sort of process that and sum that up. And you can tell me

01:20:34.160 --> 01:20:39.040
[Amit Varma]: if I did that accurately. And this kind of raises a very interesting question, like,

01:20:39.040 --> 01:20:44.300
[Amit Varma]: when you spoke of sort of Maxwell and Lamb being called, like China hands, as if they

01:20:44.300 --> 01:20:48.560
[Amit Varma]: are sort of peddling the China narrative, and they obviously have their own incentives.

01:20:48.560 --> 01:20:52.560
[Amit Varma]: And I guess all authors will have incentives of some kind or the other. It doesn't mean

01:20:52.560 --> 01:20:55.920
[Amit Varma]: that a government is necessarily paying them, but in terms of access, or where they are

01:20:55.920 --> 01:21:00.840
[Amit Varma]: based, or what are their intellectual communities like, and all of that, there will be these

01:21:00.840 --> 01:21:05.840
[Amit Varma]: incentives. And you pointed out that there are two schools of thought. One is sort of

01:21:05.840 --> 01:21:11.560
[Amit Varma]: the one which was dominant in the early years, I think Maxwell's book, India's China War

01:21:11.560 --> 01:21:17.920
[Amit Varma]: came out in 1971. And, you know, that's a period you also refer to the fascinating meeting

01:21:17.920 --> 01:21:22.840
[Amit Varma]: with the Pakistani and the Chinese. And the Chinese obviously had reason to be wary of

01:21:22.840 --> 01:21:26.600
[Amit Varma]: the Indian because, you know, they saw the British as an imperialist colonial power.

01:21:26.600 --> 01:21:31.040
[Amit Varma]: And they were worried that India even after independence would continue along those lines

01:21:31.040 --> 01:21:37.800
[Amit Varma]: and Nehru's forward policy, you know, sparked off the conflict in which they behave responsibly.

01:21:37.800 --> 01:21:40.800
[Amit Varma]: And you're pointing out at the other school of thought, which is something that is finding

01:21:40.800 --> 01:21:45.920
[Amit Varma]: more voice now among Indian scholars and people like Berlin Lintner, who couldn't think of

01:21:45.920 --> 01:21:50.160
[Amit Varma]: an entirely different title, he said, Uska book tha India's China War, I will be China's

01:21:50.160 --> 01:21:55.960
[Amit Varma]: India War, but I get it. It's very smart, basically takes the whole approach of pointing

01:21:55.960 --> 01:22:00.480
[Amit Varma]: out that listen, China was doing all of these little things, these border disagreements

01:22:00.480 --> 01:22:05.840
[Amit Varma]: and so on through the 1950s, that they were the aggressors, they were the one who, you

01:22:05.840 --> 01:22:10.360
[Amit Varma]: know, took Tibet to begin with. And Nehru was just trying to respond to that. So it's

01:22:10.360 --> 01:22:14.960
[Amit Varma]: really not India's fault. You know, this seems to me one of the situations where whichever

01:22:14.960 --> 01:22:21.920
[Amit Varma]: case you're making, you know, it's not like there is truth out there. You can essentially

01:22:21.920 --> 01:22:26.640
[Amit Varma]: believe any version of these because we don't know what the main players are thinking. It's

01:22:26.640 --> 01:22:30.120
[Amit Varma]: quite likely that in certain minds of the players involved, both accounts are completely

01:22:30.120 --> 01:22:34.720
[Amit Varma]: true. Like Nehru may have felt he was entirely justified. And, you know, Xu may have felt

01:22:34.720 --> 01:22:41.680
[Amit Varma]: what is this guy doing? And all of that. So, so yeah, I'm just kind of thinking aloud and

01:22:41.680 --> 01:22:48.640
[Amit Varma]: trying to sum up what you said and given that this is the case, how does then policy towards

01:22:48.640 --> 01:22:53.200
[Amit Varma]: each other in both these countries evolve? Like I presume the war is over. And China

01:22:53.200 --> 01:22:57.840
[Amit Varma]: is like, okay, these guys were getting too fresh and we taught them a lesson. And for

01:22:57.840 --> 01:23:03.200
[Amit Varma]: India, it's just a humiliation, but it's okay. Nehru dies a couple of years after and you'd

01:23:03.200 --> 01:23:10.120
[Amit Varma]: imagine there is some kind of reset. And VK Krishnamenon is, you know, consigned to history.

01:23:10.120 --> 01:23:15.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, how do those sort of approaches within both countries domestically evolve

01:23:15.720 --> 01:23:16.720
[Guest 2]: in that period?

01:23:16.720 --> 01:23:21.040
[Guest 2]: When I think about it, I was speaking a little bit about how, you know, structures were overhauled

01:23:21.040 --> 01:23:29.800
[Guest 2]: and stuff like that. And I think in India, since 62, we continue to have this insecurity

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:36.160
[Guest 2]: about China. I think it's just something that we have never gotten over, this sort of national

01:23:36.160 --> 01:23:42.400
[Guest 2]: humiliation, you know, in a month they were able to completely override us. And I think

01:23:42.400 --> 01:23:48.680
[Guest 2]: you continue to have those narratives today when we talk about India and China's relationships,

01:23:48.680 --> 01:23:53.280
[Guest 2]: you know, about how there's a lot that's written about how Nehru died a heartbroken man, and

01:23:53.280 --> 01:23:58.920
[Guest 2]: you could see that this clearly had an effect on his health. And I think, you know, the

01:23:58.920 --> 01:24:05.920
[Guest 2]: war really left a lasting impression on India's narratives and the way it saw itself as a

01:24:05.920 --> 01:24:06.920
[Guest 2]: country.

01:24:06.920 --> 01:24:11.160
[Guest 2]: But I think more tangibly, you know, barely months after China and Pakistan reached their

01:24:11.160 --> 01:24:15.680
[Guest 2]: first border agreements in a year, they completely finalized their border, which was something

01:24:15.680 --> 01:24:21.120
[Guest 2]: that India was very angry about. And then in 1965, India and Pakistan fight another

01:24:21.120 --> 01:24:28.480
[Guest 2]: war. And this is the time where there is a real fear that India would be fighting a two-front

01:24:28.480 --> 01:24:34.720
[Guest 2]: war, right? And this is particularly true of Sikkim. Sikkim was at this point in time

01:24:34.720 --> 01:24:41.600
[Guest 2]: still an independent Himalayan kingdom, right? So there are reports that when the war with

01:24:41.600 --> 01:24:47.960
[Guest 2]: Pakistan was really beginning to heat up, the Chinese government sent a note asking

01:24:47.960 --> 01:24:54.720
[Guest 2]: India to vacate from some of these posts that it had occupied along the border between Sikkim

01:24:54.720 --> 01:25:01.320
[Guest 2]: and China. And the Indians were rather perplexed because they didn't really occupy anything.

01:25:01.320 --> 01:25:04.960
[Guest 2]: So at that point in time, the governor said, you know what, just ignore the note, don't

01:25:04.960 --> 01:25:08.520
[Guest 2]: respond to it. But the note was an ultimatum in that sense. It was saying, you know, if

01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:13.840
[Guest 2]: you don't vacate in three days, then we will attack. And what essentially happened was

01:25:13.840 --> 01:25:18.080
[Guest 2]: that India ignored the note, nothing came of it. And then the Chinese, I think at the

01:25:18.080 --> 01:25:24.320
[Guest 2]: end of three days said, oh, thank you for vacating the land that you occupied, you know.

01:25:24.320 --> 01:25:30.000
[Guest 2]: But that really drove the fear that what would India do if it was faced with a threat both

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:35.400
[Guest 2]: in its Eastern as well as its Western sectors. And this is when India really started looking

01:25:35.400 --> 01:25:41.480
[Guest 2]: at how it was going to deal with threats along the border. Something else that's also happening

01:25:41.480 --> 01:25:48.520
[Guest 2]: internally is you have to remember that the Northeast, as it looks right now, it's still

01:25:48.520 --> 01:25:55.800
[Guest 2]: not very much in sort of the Indian's imagination, but it was even less at that point in time.

01:25:55.800 --> 01:26:01.920
[Guest 2]: What happened was that the Chinese began to aid Naga rebels and, you know, more than about

01:26:01.920 --> 01:26:07.160
[Guest 2]: 700 rebels were actually trained in Yunnan and, you know, provided with guns. And this

01:26:07.160 --> 01:26:12.080
[Guest 2]: also happens with Manipuri revolutionaries, Mizo rebels, a lot of them get training and

01:26:12.080 --> 01:26:16.520
[Guest 2]: support. Before we get into that in detail, I think there are a couple of other things

01:26:16.520 --> 01:26:23.480
[Guest 2]: that I want to touch upon. One is the Communist Party in India. The left took a huge sort

01:26:23.480 --> 01:26:31.800
[Guest 2]: of ideological beating in that sense. And the CPI split after 1962. And that's when,

01:26:31.800 --> 01:26:37.720
[Guest 2]: you know, you have the CPI Marxist being formed. And this is because the CPI largely condemns

01:26:37.720 --> 01:26:44.000
[Guest 2]: the war. Krishnamanand was essentially a part of it. And the CPI continues to condemn the

01:26:44.000 --> 01:26:50.520
[Guest 2]: 1962 war. Whereas the CPI-M essentially saw the war as a fight between, you know, the

01:26:50.520 --> 01:26:55.080
[Guest 2]: socialists and the capitalists. China being the socialists, us being the capitalists.

01:26:55.080 --> 01:26:59.240
[Amit Varma]: So they were on the Chinese side. They were on the Chinese side. And after this, you know,

01:26:59.240 --> 01:27:03.560
[Guest 2]: you have people like Karu Sanyal and others traveling to Nepal and finally going to Beijing,

01:27:03.560 --> 01:27:09.440
[Guest 2]: where they meet Mao and were promised men in arms. So you have that thread that eventually

01:27:09.440 --> 01:27:15.360
[Guest 2]: comes out to play. The other thing that happens is, you mentioned Krishnamanand, you also

01:27:15.360 --> 01:27:22.760
[Guest 2]: have a lot of army officers who go into early retirement, you know, the Chief of Army Staff,

01:27:22.760 --> 01:27:28.280
[Guest 2]: the Chief of General Staff. So a lot of them, even if they weren't directly responsible

01:27:28.280 --> 01:27:32.480
[Guest 2]: for things that happened, still saw a lot of heads rolling.

01:27:32.480 --> 01:27:38.680
[Guest 1]: So just adding to what Hamsini was saying about the humiliation that India faced, particularly

01:27:38.680 --> 01:27:45.640
[Guest 1]: Nehru, after the 1962 war, this was something that Indira Gandhi, when she became Prime

01:27:45.640 --> 01:27:52.760
[Guest 1]: Minister of India, knew she wanted to fix. She wanted to redeem the image of her father

01:27:52.760 --> 01:27:58.240
[Guest 1]: and also redeem the image or the humiliation that the Prime Minister's office itself had

01:27:58.240 --> 01:28:05.840
[Guest 1]: suffered in the country. And it can be argued that she was open to dialogue with China about

01:28:05.840 --> 01:28:13.120
[Guest 1]: the territorial disputes. So while, you know, like Hamsini was saying, there was a lot of

01:28:13.120 --> 01:28:20.280
[Guest 1]: argument about who was right on either side, there was this very small window in 1970,

01:28:20.280 --> 01:28:28.200
[Guest 1]: when both India and China were open to dialogue. But they kind of just missed each other multiple

01:28:28.200 --> 01:28:37.640
[Guest 1]: times. And this starts with on the 30th of April, 1970, the day before China celebrates

01:28:37.640 --> 01:28:44.080
[Guest 1]: May Day, there was a display of fireworks. Now, remember at this point, diplomatic relations

01:28:44.080 --> 01:28:50.040
[Guest 1]: between both countries have completely broken down. Ambassadors have been called back. So

01:28:50.040 --> 01:28:56.400
[Guest 1]: there is no formal sort of representation. But there is an Indian representative in Brijesh

01:28:56.400 --> 01:29:03.200
[Guest 1]: Mishra, who's at this display of fireworks. And during the meet and greet, he's approached

01:29:03.200 --> 01:29:11.480
[Guest 1]: by Mao, who says, we cannot keep quarreling like this. Let us try and be friends. And

01:29:11.480 --> 01:29:17.800
[Guest 1]: this is seen as an enthusiastic sort of move that China is making. Mao tells Brijesh Mishra

01:29:17.800 --> 01:29:23.280
[Guest 1]: to convey this message to the Prime Minister, which he says that, you know, this is the

01:29:23.280 --> 01:29:32.560
[Guest 1]: time we can sort of resume dialogue. And so both sides are open to it. The sort of conditions

01:29:32.560 --> 01:29:38.040
[Guest 1]: in China, which is undergoing the Cultural Revolution, as Hamzani had pointed out, also

01:29:38.040 --> 01:29:44.840
[Guest 1]: would have made negotiations easier because of the domestic conditions in China. And there

01:29:44.840 --> 01:29:51.160
[Guest 1]: was some sort of civil unrest amongst the left in China itself. So the negotiation could

01:29:51.160 --> 01:29:59.240
[Guest 1]: have been favourable for India. But there is a delay in response from the Indian side.

01:29:59.240 --> 01:30:05.920
[Guest 1]: And Sudhendra Kulkarni has a two part series in The Wire about the events that lead up

01:30:05.920 --> 01:30:12.040
[Guest 1]: to the 71 Bangladesh Liberation War and sort of explains the entire dynamic. So I would

01:30:12.040 --> 01:30:18.400
[Guest 1]: recommend people reading that. But the reason there is a delay in replying from the Indian

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:25.600
[Guest 1]: side is because, again, what Hamzani pointed out, there is division between the CPI in

01:30:25.600 --> 01:30:32.600
[Guest 1]: India and one side is seen favouring China, therefore being anti-government and anti-Indira

01:30:32.600 --> 01:30:39.240
[Guest 1]: Gandhi, which did not please the Prime Minister. And second, there was a rising insecurity

01:30:39.240 --> 01:30:46.840
[Guest 1]: towards Pakistan. So we see a distinct shift between Nehru and Indira Gandhi, where Nehru

01:30:46.840 --> 01:30:53.000
[Guest 1]: was trying to be the peacemaker and trying to bring in the aspirations of all Asian powers

01:30:53.000 --> 01:31:01.480
[Guest 1]: and achieve them collectively. But Indira Gandhi becomes more regional. She's driven

01:31:01.480 --> 01:31:07.920
[Guest 1]: by securing regional security. And a lot of her actions and her foreign policy is driven

01:31:07.920 --> 01:31:15.960
[Guest 1]: by that motivation. So there is some sort of a distraction with Pakistan and how that

01:31:15.960 --> 01:31:23.680
[Guest 1]: is going to be handled at the same time. And this one here is really exciting for an international

01:31:23.680 --> 01:31:30.280
[Guest 1]: relations scholar because you have a lot of players getting involved slowly. So this is

01:31:30.280 --> 01:31:37.720
[Guest 1]: a time that the United States realises it has a chance to rebuild its relationship with

01:31:37.720 --> 01:31:46.200
[Guest 1]: China. So you have President Nixon and NSA Kissinger arranging a meeting with China,

01:31:46.200 --> 01:31:55.680
[Guest 1]: which is a sort of secretive meeting and it's aided by Pakistan. So Pakistan is also involved.

01:31:55.680 --> 01:32:03.800
[Guest 1]: And what is argued is that the window that India had is sort of grabbed by the US and

01:32:03.800 --> 01:32:12.920
[Guest 1]: Nixon is able to sort of re-establish relationships with China. Because Pakistan helped the United

01:32:12.920 --> 01:32:21.720
[Guest 1]: States in doing that, India is unhappy and therefore turns to the Soviet Union, signs

01:32:21.720 --> 01:32:29.920
[Guest 1]: the Treaty of Peace and Friendship as a security from Pakistan, which China in turn views as

01:32:29.920 --> 01:32:35.840
[Guest 1]: an anti-China move. So a lot of things happen in that really short period. And of course,

01:32:35.840 --> 01:32:43.280
[Guest 1]: then you have the Pakistan-Bangladesh Liberation War, which again takes a toll on the country

01:32:43.280 --> 01:32:48.400
[Guest 1]: and that window sort of closes in the 70s.

01:32:48.400 --> 01:32:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I had a fascinating episode on that year. I mean, basically the Bangladesh war

01:32:54.880 --> 01:32:59.960
[Amit Varma]: with Srinath Raghavan, but he, you know, we spoke about the events of that year and how,

01:32:59.960 --> 01:33:04.120
[Amit Varma]: if I remember correctly, Kissinger makes a secret trip to China and he pretends he's

01:33:04.120 --> 01:33:08.720
[Amit Varma]: visiting Pakistan, but he, you know, flies down to China. And today they could just,

01:33:08.720 --> 01:33:14.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, chat on WeChat or something and kind of say what they have to say while every

01:33:14.280 --> 01:33:20.720
[Amit Varma]: other country watches on because they've hacked the phones. But let me also then sort of take

01:33:20.720 --> 01:33:25.200
[Amit Varma]: a lateral detour and I'll come back to Indira Gandhi and what her policy was like and those

01:33:25.200 --> 01:33:29.120
[Amit Varma]: very interesting years and what happened in the aftermath of that. And I also briefly

01:33:29.120 --> 01:33:34.480
[Amit Varma]: want to talk about Sikkim, but just to take a lateral detour at the same time, you know,

01:33:34.480 --> 01:33:40.560
[Amit Varma]: India's popular imagination is both shaped by and reflected in Bollywood to a certain

01:33:40.560 --> 01:33:45.880
[Amit Varma]: extent, right. Or, you know, other regional cinema and all that. And I found that, you

01:33:45.880 --> 01:33:52.640
[Amit Varma]: know, popular culture often acts as a barometer of what people think and feel in the culture.

01:33:52.640 --> 01:33:57.520
[Amit Varma]: So Shibani, tell me a little bit about, you know, how was China looked at in the Indian

01:33:57.520 --> 01:34:02.440
[Amit Varma]: popular imagination? Like even today, you know, Indians are very xenophobic towards

01:34:02.440 --> 01:34:07.400
[Amit Varma]: the Chinese. So what was sort of attitudes like, how were they evolving? You know, there

01:34:07.400 --> 01:34:12.560
[Amit Varma]: was also this Hindi-Chini bhai bhai stuff that had kind of happened. Give me some rope

01:34:12.560 --> 01:34:13.560
[Guest 1]: on that.

01:34:13.560 --> 01:34:20.880
[Guest 1]: So Bollywood presents a very interesting case to understand national sentiment. I should

01:34:20.880 --> 01:34:27.040
[Guest 1]: say that I haven't been exposed to regional cinema, so I can't speak for what's happening

01:34:27.040 --> 01:34:32.240
[Guest 1]: there. If anyone has recommendations on what I would watch, please let me know. I'd love

01:34:32.240 --> 01:34:40.400
[Guest 1]: to do that. But speaking about Bollywood, so in the 50s, cinema felt, or Hindi cinema,

01:34:40.400 --> 01:34:45.480
[Guest 1]: there was a lot of social responsibility in the film. You had Guru Dutt's Pyaasa, which

01:34:45.480 --> 01:34:52.280
[Guest 1]: was a critique of a materialistic society. The same year, you had Mother India, which

01:34:52.280 --> 01:34:59.760
[Guest 1]: was, you know, the Indian nation state as it existed in the villages. And then you also

01:34:59.760 --> 01:35:06.960
[Guest 1]: had B. R. Chopra's Naya Daur, which was, you know, a salutation to Nehruvian socialism.

01:35:06.960 --> 01:35:12.480
[Guest 1]: So there's a lot of celebration of the birth of India, the growth of India, and, you know,

01:35:12.480 --> 01:35:19.920
[Guest 1]: what the aspirations that India has. With the 62nd war, you see a departure from social

01:35:19.920 --> 01:35:28.840
[Guest 1]: responsibility and move towards escapist entertainment. So you have films like Theesri Manzil, A Jewel

01:35:28.840 --> 01:35:34.720
[Guest 1]: Thief, Guide, and Vakht that come in the 60s, which are just purely for entertainment. They're

01:35:34.720 --> 01:35:41.040
[Guest 1]: not thrillers, they're dramas, there's romance. Films are being shot in foreign locations.

01:35:41.040 --> 01:35:50.040
[Guest 1]: And it's just pure entertainment value. The only movie about the 1962 war, which you quoted,

01:35:50.040 --> 01:36:01.800
[Guest 1]: is Hakikatt that came out two years after the war in 1964. And this movie is also been,

01:36:01.800 --> 01:36:08.880
[Guest 1]: it oversympathizes with the Indian side. It tries to, you know, sort of bring down the

01:36:08.880 --> 01:36:15.320
[Guest 1]: humiliation that India felt and, you know, play up the loss of life of soldiers and things

01:36:15.320 --> 01:36:22.920
[Guest 1]: like that. But I should point out that it does not villainize the Chinese. So it is

01:36:22.920 --> 01:36:28.040
[Guest 1]: only looking at the Indian point of view, what happened with the soldiers, goes into

01:36:28.040 --> 01:36:33.400
[Guest 1]: the personal lives of some of the characters, but there is no villainization of the Chinese

01:36:33.400 --> 01:36:43.440
[Guest 1]: side. It was just a war that went wrong. And yeah, after that, the few films about India,

01:36:43.440 --> 01:36:51.840
[Guest 1]: so I think you had Shaheed, which was based on the life of Bhagat Singh that came in 1965.

01:36:51.840 --> 01:36:57.360
[Guest 1]: But that's again, pre-independence. So again, going back to that freedom, notion of freedom

01:36:57.360 --> 01:37:07.240
[Guest 1]: struggle and stuff, but nothing really touches upon Indian society till you have the angry

01:37:07.240 --> 01:37:12.400
[Guest 1]: young man making an appearance almost a decade later.

01:37:12.400 --> 01:37:16.160
[Amit Varma]: So it's almost like, you know, it was just a dark moment, and we chose to blot it out

01:37:16.160 --> 01:37:19.720
[Amit Varma]: of the collective imagination and pretend it never happened. Because, you know, it's

01:37:19.720 --> 01:37:24.080
[Amit Varma]: much easier to sort of, like the constant sort of nationalistic trope that has happened

01:37:24.080 --> 01:37:28.320
[Amit Varma]: in the decades since is, you know, where you show Pakistanis as a villain and you're fighting

01:37:28.320 --> 01:37:36.240
[Amit Varma]: the ISI and Sunny Deol is going to the border with a big gun and saving all of us. But China

01:37:36.240 --> 01:37:42.200
[Amit Varma]: is just something that we choose to sort of not think about because, hey, look what happened.

01:37:42.200 --> 01:37:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's get back to the politics. I mean, as you guys would know, I am no fan of Indira

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi for all the things she did in the domestic sphere. But at the same time, as far as her

01:37:52.880 --> 01:37:57.720
[Amit Varma]: geopolitical sort of acumen was concerned, she seems to have kind of done a much better

01:37:57.720 --> 01:38:03.760
[Amit Varma]: job, one in the way she handled the Bangladesh war. And if I'm not mistaken, and Hamsa maybe

01:38:03.760 --> 01:38:10.760
[Amit Varma]: you can sort of elaborate on this, she also seems to have moved away from Nehru's mistaken

01:38:10.760 --> 01:38:17.400
[Amit Varma]: idealism and actually taken a much more hard-nosed, realistic view of what one, a realist view

01:38:17.400 --> 01:38:23.640
[Amit Varma]: rather of what one needed to do in the, in the neighborhood. So tell me a little bit

01:38:23.640 --> 01:38:27.760
[Amit Varma]: about that. I mean, and also, you know, one thing that kind of intrigues me is today,

01:38:27.760 --> 01:38:32.600
[Amit Varma]: of course, there is a lot of talk and I've had episodes in this as well about how sort

01:38:32.600 --> 01:38:37.960
[Amit Varma]: of China and, you know, the worry of between China and Pakistan kind of getting close together

01:38:37.960 --> 01:38:42.320
[Amit Varma]: and how that's going to impact us. And there was recent talk that, you know, when Nepal

01:38:42.320 --> 01:38:47.400
[Amit Varma]: caught the snow catastrophes, because, you know, they've been emboldened by China kind

01:38:47.400 --> 01:38:53.360
[Amit Varma]: of getting there. Were these worries back then, you know, in the 70s and 80s? So sort

01:38:53.360 --> 01:38:55.560
[Amit Varma]: of take me through a bit of that period.

01:38:55.560 --> 01:39:01.760
[Guest 2]: Sure. Amit, just something that I wanted to just briefly go up on before we get into the

01:39:01.760 --> 01:39:10.000
[Guest 2]: 1970s, is that in the 1960s, one important thing happens, which is an other sort of clash

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:17.160
[Guest 2]: between India and China. And this happens in 67, a little before the 70s and the Bangladesh

01:39:17.160 --> 01:39:22.640
[Guest 2]: war and all of that. And the reason why it's important is because accepting the current

01:39:22.640 --> 01:39:28.520
[Guest 2]: crisis at Kalwa, that was the last crisis where India lost men across the line of actual

01:39:28.520 --> 01:39:36.440
[Guest 2]: control. So what actually happens in 1967 is, there's still not a lot of scholarship

01:39:36.440 --> 01:39:42.520
[Guest 2]: that's done on it. There's a new book by Prabal Das Gupta called Watershed 1967. So what essentially

01:39:42.520 --> 01:39:49.120
[Guest 2]: happens in 1967 is that you have the two passes in Sikkim, Chola and Nathula, where we were

01:39:49.120 --> 01:39:56.680
[Guest 2]: afraid that the Chinese would also fight against in 65. The Indians decided to fence that border.

01:39:56.680 --> 01:40:01.880
[Guest 2]: And while they were fencing the border, often there were Chinese troops that came about

01:40:01.880 --> 01:40:06.120
[Guest 2]: saying that you can't fence this border because you're in our territory. And in one of those

01:40:06.120 --> 01:40:12.480
[Guest 2]: scuffles, there were both Indian and Chinese lives lost. As a scholar, I will say that

01:40:12.480 --> 01:40:18.200
[Guest 2]: objectively we don't have a number, an exact number of the number of lives that were lost

01:40:18.200 --> 01:40:23.880
[Guest 2]: during that point in time. The lowest numbers put it at 30 on the Chinese side and 60 on

01:40:23.880 --> 01:40:29.000
[Guest 2]: the Indian side and the highest numbers put it on 350 on the Chinese side. So that is

01:40:29.000 --> 01:40:34.280
[Guest 2]: something that we need to keep an open mind towards. But these clashes did happen. And

01:40:34.280 --> 01:40:38.320
[Guest 2]: the other thing that sort of came out of it, which Shivani referred to when she was talking

01:40:38.320 --> 01:40:44.400
[Guest 2]: about Indira Gandhi, the reason we didn't have any ambassadors present in China is because

01:40:44.400 --> 01:40:52.200
[Guest 2]: in 67, in the same year, two Indian embassy officials were accused by the Chinese of spying.

01:40:52.200 --> 01:40:57.320
[Guest 2]: And so they were beaten by the Red Guards. They were publicly humiliated. And they were

01:40:57.320 --> 01:41:03.680
[Guest 2]: eventually, you know, the Indian embassy was supposedly under siege for days with people

01:41:03.680 --> 01:41:09.320
[Guest 2]: standing outside, you know, clamoring to get in. And other embassies tried to send in,

01:41:09.320 --> 01:41:14.080
[Guest 2]: you know, supplies, but they couldn't get through. And then when the Indians heard of

01:41:14.080 --> 01:41:20.120
[Guest 2]: it, the exact same thing happened here. The Chinese ambassadors were beaten up. They were,

01:41:20.120 --> 01:41:25.440
[Guest 2]: and essentially all of them were deported and became sort of like persona non grata.

01:41:25.440 --> 01:41:31.040
[Guest 2]: And that is one of the reasons why relations sired even more. And when Indira Gandhi comes

01:41:31.040 --> 01:41:36.280
[Guest 2]: into office, that's sort of, you know, the last exchange that India and China have had

01:41:36.280 --> 01:41:42.520
[Guest 2]: on an ambassadorial level. I think I agree with you. I am not a big fan of what Indira

01:41:42.520 --> 01:41:50.320
[Guest 2]: Gandhi's policies were domestically, but on a foreign policy landscape, she dealt with

01:41:50.320 --> 01:41:55.840
[Guest 2]: a lot of challenges that India was facing very, very well. The Bangladesh war, which

01:41:55.840 --> 01:42:01.920
[Guest 2]: you have spoken about in detail for one. I think the other, it was from then on this

01:42:01.920 --> 01:42:09.800
[Guest 2]: prevailing worry that India would lose its neighborhood, right? And why the Indira Gandhi

01:42:09.800 --> 01:42:14.000
[Guest 2]: government onwards were afraid of this is because, as I'd mentioned, the Chinese were

01:42:14.000 --> 01:42:19.880
[Guest 2]: providing resources to rebel groups. At one point in time, there was this idea that a

01:42:19.880 --> 01:42:24.840
[Guest 2]: red corridor would be formed, right? Like the Naxalite movement was coming to the fore,

01:42:24.840 --> 01:42:29.320
[Guest 2]: that it would go through India, go through Nepal, and finally go to China. And this was

01:42:29.320 --> 01:42:36.200
[Guest 2]: sort of the revolution spreading to all across the world. But I think Indira Gandhi was,

01:42:36.200 --> 01:42:40.860
[Guest 2]: and this is sort of one of the great things about studying the foreign policy about that

01:42:40.860 --> 01:42:48.640
[Guest 2]: period, is that, you know, in 1976, both countries exchanged ambassadors for the first time.

01:42:48.640 --> 01:42:53.520
[Guest 2]: And you know what happens immediately, the emergency, so nothing else happened. And so

01:42:53.520 --> 01:42:59.640
[Guest 2]: Indira Gandhi didn't really have any other contact with the Chinese while she was in

01:42:59.640 --> 01:43:05.360
[Guest 2]: power. When the Janaka government comes in, for a very brief period, what happens is that

01:43:05.360 --> 01:43:10.280
[Guest 2]: Vajpayee visits Beijing, but he had to cut his trip short, because he was protesting

01:43:10.280 --> 01:43:14.920
[Guest 2]: the Chinese invasion of Vietnam. And then you move forward, Indira Gandhi comes back

01:43:14.920 --> 01:43:19.880
[Guest 2]: to power. And the main issue then doesn't turn out to be the border, it doesn't turn

01:43:19.880 --> 01:43:25.960
[Guest 2]: out to be relations in the neighborhood. It's very odd, but from what I can read, the main

01:43:25.960 --> 01:43:35.920
[Guest 2]: issues at that point in time was that in Indochina, there was the war between Vietnam and Cambodia.

01:43:35.920 --> 01:43:40.160
[Guest 2]: And in Cambodia, you had the Khmer Rouge, who the Chinese were backing, and you had

01:43:40.160 --> 01:43:45.360
[Guest 2]: the People's Republic of Kampuchea, which was Vietnamese backed. And the main issue

01:43:45.360 --> 01:43:50.840
[Guest 2]: between India and China was supposedly the Indian government's recognition of the People's

01:43:50.840 --> 01:43:56.520
[Guest 2]: Republic of Kampuchea. And that became a huge issue for some reason. And that was the sort

01:43:56.520 --> 01:43:59.280
[Guest 2]: of roadblock between relations.

01:43:59.280 --> 01:44:04.600
[Guest 1]: So adding to what Hamsini was saying about Indira Gandhi's foreign policy, it's the

01:44:04.600 --> 01:44:11.440
[Guest 1]: first time we see a departure from non-alignment, because Indira Gandhi, like you said, was

01:44:11.440 --> 01:44:16.120
[Guest 1]: more of a realist than her father was. And there was an inclination towards balance of

01:44:16.120 --> 01:44:24.600
[Guest 1]: power politics. And she also displayed a greater willingness to use coercive tactics and force.

01:44:24.600 --> 01:44:31.840
[Guest 1]: But the challenge that, you know, the Indian government faced during the 70s is that there

01:44:31.840 --> 01:44:36.720
[Guest 1]: was no stability. Governments were coming and going very quickly. And there was a lot

01:44:36.720 --> 01:44:44.800
[Guest 1]: of domestic disturbance that it had to cope with, because of which, as Hamsini was saying,

01:44:44.800 --> 01:44:51.360
[Guest 1]: you would establish contact with the Chinese, but you wouldn't be able to engage with China,

01:44:51.360 --> 01:44:52.360
[Guest 1]: because something else would happen.

01:44:52.360 --> 01:44:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Right. And Hamsini, I also want you to sort of briefly mention on, you know, was what

01:44:56.560 --> 01:45:01.520
[Amit Varma]: happened in Sikkim significant there? Just bring me up to speed on that. And also, just

01:45:01.520 --> 01:45:06.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of another point I'd like you to clarify, which is, you know, when we use the term,

01:45:06.640 --> 01:45:11.140
[Amit Varma]: the line of actual control, and there is sort of in the popular imagination of border is

01:45:11.140 --> 01:45:15.280
[Amit Varma]: one line, right? So it's a line and on one side, you have the Indians and on the other

01:45:15.280 --> 01:45:20.000
[Amit Varma]: side, you have the Chinese. But actually, there is no line in the sense that, you know,

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:24.760
[Amit Varma]: both countries are quite clear about what territory definitely belongs to them. But

01:45:24.760 --> 01:45:31.000
[Amit Varma]: there is also a sort of no man's land in between where there is, you know, much ambiguity and

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:36.200
[Amit Varma]: uncertainty. And a lot of action happens on that no man's land, like allegedly in 67,

01:45:36.200 --> 01:45:41.400
[Amit Varma]: or recently, what happened in Galwan, which is why you know, you could actually have a

01:45:41.400 --> 01:45:47.080
[Amit Varma]: conflict on territory that was not Chinese territory. But at the same time, the Prime

01:45:47.080 --> 01:45:52.280
[Amit Varma]: Minister wasn't entirely wrong when he said they haven't come into our territory. It was

01:45:52.280 --> 01:45:56.960
[Amit Varma]: sort of like a kind of a buffer zone. Is that understanding broadly correct?

01:45:56.960 --> 01:46:02.160
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, I'm not again, as I said, like a military specialist, but I think that is

01:46:02.160 --> 01:46:07.120
[Guest 2]: a good way to sum up the line of actual control. You know, as much as we like to imagine, you

01:46:07.120 --> 01:46:13.400
[Guest 2]: know, maps in our heads, and you have this specific thing that separates India from China.

01:46:13.400 --> 01:46:19.800
[Guest 2]: That's not exactly true. You know, in 1962, the Chinese, you know, swept into India, and

01:46:19.800 --> 01:46:25.720
[Guest 2]: then they drew back to what they believed was the line that was supposed to be the border

01:46:25.720 --> 01:46:30.280
[Guest 2]: between India and China. And we there have been a lot of border talks and stuff that

01:46:30.280 --> 01:46:35.360
[Guest 2]: I can get into, which were exchanged. And there is this sort of agreement that these

01:46:35.360 --> 01:46:40.520
[Guest 2]: are the Indian and Chinese positions and you keep a couple of sometimes less than a couple

01:46:40.520 --> 01:46:45.880
[Guest 2]: of kilometers in between that neither side shall pass through. And this is essentially

01:46:45.880 --> 01:46:52.600
[Guest 2]: the problem even with the clashes that happened this year. Therefore, this fundamental misunderstanding

01:46:52.600 --> 01:46:58.440
[Guest 2]: about knowing what the border actually is. I remember reading some reports about this

01:46:58.440 --> 01:47:06.160
[Guest 2]: crisis talking about, oh, does China refer to the border as what it had captured in 1962?

01:47:06.160 --> 01:47:10.760
[Guest 2]: Because if that's the definition of the border that it's going by, then it's going to be

01:47:10.760 --> 01:47:16.360
[Guest 2]: a real problem, right? So that's one of the main problems, the line of actual control,

01:47:16.360 --> 01:47:21.880
[Guest 2]: unlike the LOC, the border with Pakistan, which is fenced, which for the most part,

01:47:21.880 --> 01:47:30.320
[Guest 2]: is clearly demarcated. The LAC is very ambiguous. About Sikkim, right? So during the 1970s,

01:47:30.320 --> 01:47:37.120
[Guest 2]: as Shivani had spoken about, there was a lot of worry about neighborhood stability. There

01:47:37.120 --> 01:47:44.440
[Guest 2]: was also, you know, personal anxiety about from Indira Gandhi's end about instability

01:47:44.440 --> 01:47:50.440
[Guest 2]: within the country, right? And this is where Sikkim becomes really interesting, because

01:47:50.440 --> 01:47:57.800
[Guest 2]: Sikkim was this independent kingdom, and it was independent the same way Bhutan was independent.

01:47:57.800 --> 01:48:01.760
[Guest 2]: So Sikkim and Bhutan both had treaties with India, where India said, you know, it would

01:48:01.760 --> 01:48:06.600
[Guest 2]: advise these governments on external affairs and so on, which India continues to do for

01:48:06.600 --> 01:48:11.440
[Guest 2]: Bhutan. Whereas what happened with Sikkim is that the Chokyal or the leader of the Sikkim

01:48:11.440 --> 01:48:17.320
[Guest 2]: kingdom married an American, and there was a lot of vitriol directed towards her, particularly

01:48:17.320 --> 01:48:22.400
[Guest 2]: by the Indians. A lot of people said, you know, she was a CIA spy. And she was, you

01:48:22.400 --> 01:48:28.800
[Guest 2]: know, influencing the kingdom to go against India. And, you know, we won't know if that's

01:48:28.800 --> 01:48:35.320
[Guest 2]: true, just because, you know, she's a woman and in a powerful position, or if she was

01:48:35.320 --> 01:48:40.480
[Guest 2]: actually a CIA spy. But that's not really the point, right? The point is that you were

01:48:40.480 --> 01:48:46.240
[Guest 2]: suddenly dealing with another problem on this front. And this is a front where you've already

01:48:46.240 --> 01:48:53.040
[Guest 2]: had a clash with Justin 67. So I did an episode on states of anarchy with a scholar called

01:48:53.040 --> 01:48:57.560
[Guest 2]: Deep Pal recently. And we were talking about this. And what I was essentially asking him

01:48:57.560 --> 01:49:03.520
[Guest 2]: was, you know, why did Sikkim get annexed by the Indian kingdom? And why didn't Bhutan,

01:49:03.520 --> 01:49:08.000
[Guest 2]: you know, why was there sort of a disparity between Indian foreign policy towards the

01:49:08.000 --> 01:49:14.560
[Guest 2]: two? And what he says, which I think makes a lot of sense, is that this fits into the

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:23.360
[Guest 2]: Sikkimese imagination of India's perception towards itself, towards India, as well as

01:49:23.360 --> 01:49:27.560
[Guest 2]: of Sikkim. So I'm going to break that down a little bit. Essentially, what that means

01:49:27.560 --> 01:49:34.320
[Guest 2]: is that India had a perception of itself as a country. And it perceived Bhutan and Sikkim

01:49:34.320 --> 01:49:40.960
[Guest 2]: into fitting into that imagination in a particular way. And Bhutan did. Bhutanese army officers,

01:49:40.960 --> 01:49:45.920
[Guest 2]: for example, were trained in India. Bhutan fell in line with a lot of things that India

01:49:45.920 --> 01:49:51.320
[Guest 2]: wanted. India in return gave it military aid and continues to give it military aid. Sikkim,

01:49:51.320 --> 01:49:58.480
[Guest 2]: on the other hand, was starting to show a lot of signs of wanting more. And India was

01:49:58.480 --> 01:50:04.120
[Guest 2]: afraid that this was going to have to be yet another border that they would have to contend

01:50:04.120 --> 01:50:08.760
[Guest 2]: with. And that was not really something that they could deal with. There are a lot of books

01:50:08.760 --> 01:50:15.920
[Guest 2]: that are written about the annexation of Sikkim alone. But I think one of the reasons why

01:50:15.920 --> 01:50:22.400
[Guest 2]: Sikkim was incorporated into the Indian Union was definitely its place on the border between

01:50:22.400 --> 01:50:23.400
[Guest 2]: India and China.

01:50:23.400 --> 01:50:25.760
[Amit Varma]: And how did China react to that?

01:50:25.760 --> 01:50:32.840
[Guest 2]: China did protest because it saw this as sort of a unilateral move by India. And for years,

01:50:32.840 --> 01:50:39.360
[Guest 2]: China didn't really recognize that Sikkim was a part of India. So that was something

01:50:39.360 --> 01:50:46.160
[Guest 2]: that was part of relations. Imagine that it reacted the same way that it would if Ladakh

01:50:46.160 --> 01:50:52.080
[Guest 2]: was made a union territory. So that's sort of the same pitch of the reaction that India

01:50:52.080 --> 01:50:58.520
[Guest 2]: is unilaterally changing borders and unilaterally changing the status quo. So that's something

01:50:58.520 --> 01:51:05.720
[Guest 2]: that's very important that happens in the 1970s. As you sort of move towards the 80s,

01:51:05.720 --> 01:51:10.200
[Guest 2]: even under Indira Gandhi, you have sort of the first visit of the Chinese foreign minister

01:51:10.200 --> 01:51:16.240
[Guest 2]: in 1981. And then you have five rounds of border talks. And these are important because

01:51:16.240 --> 01:51:25.440
[Guest 2]: 20 years after the original crisis is when both countries begin to agree that they actually

01:51:25.440 --> 01:51:32.200
[Guest 2]: have a problem on their hands. And they both took very different views to it. China wanted

01:51:32.200 --> 01:51:37.280
[Guest 2]: to shelve the border issue and it wanted to focus on other things like trade. And India

01:51:37.280 --> 01:51:40.080
[Guest 2]: wanted to resolve the border issue first.

01:51:40.080 --> 01:51:45.880
[Guest 2]: So the other thing that was important to note in these border talks is that India wanted

01:51:45.880 --> 01:51:50.320
[Guest 2]: a sector by sector approach, which China really didn't want. What a sector by sector approach

01:51:50.320 --> 01:51:55.760
[Guest 2]: essentially is, is that the Indian border, the LAC in the Indian imagination is divided

01:51:55.760 --> 01:52:00.560
[Guest 2]: into three bits, right? You have the eastern sector, which is Arunachal Pradesh and Sikkim.

01:52:00.560 --> 01:52:06.680
[Guest 2]: You have the central sector, which is sort of near the border of Nepal, all the way to

01:52:06.680 --> 01:52:11.240
[Guest 2]: where the Skiti Valley of Himachal Pradesh is. And then you have the western sector,

01:52:11.240 --> 01:52:17.200
[Guest 2]: which is Ladakh. So what India wanted was to say, hey, let's talk about where you think

01:52:17.200 --> 01:52:21.560
[Guest 2]: the border is on the eastern sector and where we think the border is in the eastern sector.

01:52:21.560 --> 01:52:26.200
[Guest 2]: And we can look at it from that point of view. The Chinese, on the other hand, wanted a quid

01:52:26.200 --> 01:52:32.080
[Guest 2]: pro quo. They said, no, Aksai Chinnazar's, Tawang Nifa is yours. And we will agree to

01:52:32.080 --> 01:52:35.980
[Guest 2]: that. We will not agree to a sector by sector approach. And this is something that really

01:52:35.980 --> 01:52:38.760
[Guest 2]: held up border talks for a couple of years.

01:52:38.760 --> 01:52:46.040
[Guest 2]: So just moving ahead to what happens with Rajiv Gandhi essentially is that I think you

01:52:46.040 --> 01:52:52.320
[Guest 2]: have to remember that the 1980s in both India and China are very, very important, right?

01:52:52.320 --> 01:52:57.600
[Guest 2]: China for the first time liberalizes its economy. You have Deng Xiaoping who comes up and says,

01:52:57.600 --> 01:53:02.920
[Guest 2]: you know, it doesn't matter if a cat is black or white, as long as it chases the mice. And

01:53:02.920 --> 01:53:10.240
[Guest 2]: China really wants to set aside its ideological biases that it had been carrying forward for

01:53:10.240 --> 01:53:16.520
[Guest 2]: the first 20 years in its foreign policy. And you see this reflected in all of Chinese

01:53:16.520 --> 01:53:22.520
[Guest 2]: foreign policy, actually. The 1980s is a really interesting time to study in China. And India

01:53:22.520 --> 01:53:27.320
[Guest 2]: is also sort of the stirrings of liberalization, if I might call it that. But I think a couple

01:53:27.320 --> 01:53:32.440
[Guest 2]: of important things also happened during this time. And the first is in 1986, Arunachal

01:53:32.440 --> 01:53:36.880
[Guest 2]: Pradesh was granted full statehood. And this was something that really pissed the Chinese

01:53:36.880 --> 01:53:44.520
[Guest 2]: off, because it was India unilaterally changing status quo. In 1986, you have clashes along

01:53:44.520 --> 01:53:52.760
[Guest 2]: the Sundaram Chu, which is basically military exercises of India in Arunachal Pradesh, which

01:53:52.760 --> 01:53:57.960
[Guest 2]: finally lead to escalation. People don't really lose lives, both sides manage to de-escalate

01:53:57.960 --> 01:54:04.080
[Guest 2]: the issue, and then go back to their respective sides of the border. But this crisis essentially

01:54:04.080 --> 01:54:11.400
[Guest 2]: turns the tide in India-China relations, because after this is when N.D. Tiwari suggests that

01:54:11.400 --> 01:54:16.680
[Guest 2]: India and China expand cooperation in other fields, like it's a completely new idea. And

01:54:16.680 --> 01:54:22.640
[Guest 2]: this is when the Chinese finally, supposedly understood for the first time since 62, that

01:54:22.640 --> 01:54:27.960
[Guest 2]: the Indians didn't go to war. So until this time, the Chinese claim that they didn't really

01:54:27.960 --> 01:54:32.880
[Guest 2]: get a sense that the Indians wanted peace along the border. They only understood that

01:54:32.880 --> 01:54:38.440
[Guest 2]: Indians were being extremely aggressive along the border. So finally, a year later, Rajiv

01:54:38.440 --> 01:54:45.080
[Guest 2]: Gandhi goes to China. And this trip is the first time in 30-odd years that an Indian

01:54:45.080 --> 01:54:52.240
[Guest 2]: head of state has visited China. So this is an important moment in India-China relations.

01:54:52.240 --> 01:54:58.640
[Guest 2]: But Rajiv Gandhi faces a lot of criticism for it within India. And this is because a

01:54:58.640 --> 01:55:06.040
[Guest 2]: lot of people point out that he was the one who recognized that Tibet was a part of China.

01:55:06.040 --> 01:55:11.200
[Guest 2]: But he did this unilaterally. The Chinese didn't really offer anything in return. They

01:55:11.200 --> 01:55:15.480
[Guest 2]: didn't recognize Sikkim, they didn't recognize Arunachal Pradesh. And so Rajiv Gandhi was

01:55:15.480 --> 01:55:22.200
[Guest 2]: really criticized at that point in time by the opposition that he was giving away a lot

01:55:22.200 --> 01:55:25.400
[Guest 2]: of the Indian standing on the issue.

01:55:25.400 --> 01:55:29.880
[Amit Varma]: So a sort of a couple of thoughts. One is I'll actually object to your characterization

01:55:29.880 --> 01:55:37.520
[Amit Varma]: of those years as the early years of liberalization. Yeah, I do. I think that's a post-factual

01:55:37.520 --> 01:55:42.240
[Amit Varma]: narrative that you know, people are trying to give the family some credit for the good

01:55:42.240 --> 01:55:46.880
[Amit Varma]: that came out of liberalization. And I am not sure how much truth there is to that.

01:55:46.880 --> 01:55:52.040
[Amit Varma]: But quite apart from that, what I sort of, you know, kind of see happening is that one

01:55:52.040 --> 01:55:59.160
[Amit Varma]: obviously deng moving towards more of a market economy within China, also signals a fundamental

01:55:59.160 --> 01:56:04.320
[Amit Varma]: mindset shift, which impacts everything, not just, you know, economics locally, but also

01:56:04.320 --> 01:56:09.780
[Amit Varma]: foreign policy, because a mindset shift is one of, you know, positive, some growth where

01:56:09.780 --> 01:56:14.360
[Amit Varma]: you trade and everybody benefits and blah, blah, blah. And it seems to me that, you know,

01:56:14.360 --> 01:56:19.640
[Amit Varma]: that approach starts showing off in other domains as well, possibly one, would you agree

01:56:19.640 --> 01:56:25.040
[Amit Varma]: with that? Is that true? And true with India, there is an increase of assertiveness in the

01:56:25.040 --> 01:56:31.680
[Amit Varma]: region, for example, the nonsense that Rajiv Gandhi gets up to in Sri Lanka, for example.

01:56:31.680 --> 01:56:37.320
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, does that sort of play a part where they are trying to balance China's influence?

01:56:37.320 --> 01:56:42.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, how is the thinking developing on the respective roles of the two countries

01:56:42.160 --> 01:56:50.960
[Guest 2]: within South Asia at this point in time? Amit, I would sort of object to your saying that

01:56:50.960 --> 01:56:56.720
[Guest 2]: moving towards market economy is a fundamental shift for the same reason why you object that

01:56:56.720 --> 01:57:01.600
[Guest 2]: I call it stirrings of liberalization, right? Because China also, you know, now when we

01:57:01.600 --> 01:57:08.160
[Guest 2]: look back, we look at it as this one long continuous history. But at that point in time,

01:57:08.160 --> 01:57:13.440
[Guest 2]: it was just the end of the Cultural Revolution. It was the fall of, you know, the fall. And

01:57:13.440 --> 01:57:20.760
[Guest 2]: therefore, people were also really scared to experiment. No one knew if anything that

01:57:20.760 --> 01:57:26.920
[Guest 2]: was going to happen in China was going to continue for, forget a long period of time,

01:57:26.920 --> 01:57:32.280
[Guest 2]: for even a short period of time, right? So there is this shift that occurs, but I would

01:57:32.280 --> 01:57:38.640
[Guest 2]: say it occurs in the latter half of the 1980s rather than the first half. Because the Chinese

01:57:38.640 --> 01:57:43.360
[Guest 2]: government at that point in time also starts only with policy experimentation. It doesn't

01:57:43.360 --> 01:57:49.320
[Guest 2]: do these big sweeping reforms that it now claims that it's done, you know. And we can

01:57:49.320 --> 01:57:53.200
[Guest 2]: argue about this till the cows come home. There are different views about this. But

01:57:53.200 --> 01:57:59.960
[Guest 2]: at least my take on this is that the shifts in foreign policy, the shifts in the economy

01:57:59.960 --> 01:58:07.160
[Guest 2]: are still small. There is a marked difference in what happened earlier, which is, you know,

01:58:07.160 --> 01:58:14.720
[Guest 2]: a personality cult driven, ideologically minded foreign policy, which essentially looked at

01:58:14.720 --> 01:58:22.840
[Guest 2]: expanding, you know, the revolution across the world. I think what China wanted by this

01:58:22.840 --> 01:58:30.480
[Guest 2]: point in time was to not open up. Those are, at the end of the day, not the words that

01:58:30.480 --> 01:58:37.440
[Guest 2]: they use, but they wanted to focus on improving the quality of life. They wanted to focus

01:58:37.440 --> 01:58:44.240
[Guest 2]: on just becoming richer. And the only way that they could see this happening was to

01:58:44.240 --> 01:58:50.960
[Guest 2]: have some semblance of stability in the economy. And you can't have any semblance of stability

01:58:50.960 --> 01:58:56.520
[Guest 2]: in the economy if your foreign policy is constantly denouncing other countries or getting into

01:58:56.520 --> 01:59:02.040
[Guest 2]: tips with them. The other thing I think we need to remember with respect to your second

01:59:02.040 --> 01:59:07.080
[Guest 2]: question, you know, about whether there's an increase in assertiveness in the region.

01:59:07.080 --> 01:59:13.800
[Guest 2]: I think it's important to remember that during this time, particularly in the late 1980s,

01:59:13.800 --> 01:59:20.760
[Guest 2]: there's a lot of worry about the Soviet Union, because Gorbachev had made some speeches about

01:59:20.760 --> 01:59:26.560
[Guest 2]: Glasnost and Perestroika, but it was still difficult to read those signals. No one knew

01:59:26.560 --> 01:59:31.080
[Guest 2]: that the Soviet Union was going to fall at this point in time. But I think, at least

01:59:31.080 --> 01:59:40.160
[Guest 2]: from what I've read, is that Rajiv Gandhi wanted to also diversify his foreign policy.

01:59:40.160 --> 01:59:44.360
[Guest 2]: And when I mean him, I don't mean him as a person, but rather the foreign policy administration

01:59:44.360 --> 01:59:50.520
[Guest 2]: that he was commanding, is that the establishment at that point in time wanted to go ahead with

01:59:50.520 --> 01:59:56.240
[Guest 2]: non-alignment and realize that if they would lose the Soviet Union, then they needed to

01:59:56.240 --> 02:00:00.680
[Guest 2]: be on better terms with the Chinese, because that balance that Shivani had mentioned a

02:00:00.680 --> 02:00:04.960
[Guest 2]: couple of years ago would be lost otherwise. What do you think, Shivani?

02:00:04.960 --> 02:00:11.600
[Guest 1]: You're absolutely right. I think India was aware of the association that it had with

02:00:11.600 --> 02:00:18.560
[Guest 1]: the Soviet Union, had a negative impact on India's image because of the Soviet Union's

02:00:18.560 --> 02:00:27.800
[Guest 1]: involvement in Afghanistan. And it wanted to keep the Soviet Union at a distance. And

02:00:27.800 --> 02:00:35.720
[Guest 1]: that's why in the 80s, you see there's a push to build relationships with the US and China.

02:00:35.720 --> 02:00:42.520
[Guest 1]: But most of the energies went towards the Indian subcontinent. So you have Pakistan,

02:00:42.520 --> 02:00:49.080
[Guest 1]: Sri Lanka, like Amit pointed out, as well as Nepal. And that's what's occupying most

02:00:49.080 --> 02:00:52.480
[Guest 1]: of the time for the Ministry of External Affairs.

02:00:52.480 --> 02:00:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And Shivani, I'll turn to you now as we kind of take the narrative forward. But before

02:00:55.960 --> 02:01:01.040
[Amit Varma]: that, we'll take the narrative back briefly. My sense of the sort of when the economics

02:01:01.040 --> 02:01:05.520
[Amit Varma]: of China kind of started shifting is also, you know, the late 70s was an important time

02:01:05.520 --> 02:01:10.040
[Amit Varma]: where they made a move away from collectivist farming and a slightly deeper recognition

02:01:10.040 --> 02:01:14.920
[Amit Varma]: of property rights at that level. But I mean, leave that aside is obviously a process which

02:01:14.920 --> 02:01:20.880
[Amit Varma]: takes many years. So Shivani kind of like moving forward and coming all the way to sort

02:01:20.880 --> 02:01:27.000
[Amit Varma]: of eventually to the 2000s and Hu Jintao and China's really changing through this period

02:01:27.000 --> 02:01:32.600
[Amit Varma]: and equally, their foreign policy is really changing. And these shifts are really interesting

02:01:32.600 --> 02:01:39.800
[Amit Varma]: the shift to sort of whose approach to towards foreign policy and the world in general and,

02:01:39.800 --> 02:01:46.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, how he internally looks at China, and then later, the much more aggressive authoritarian

02:01:46.160 --> 02:01:51.120
[Amit Varma]: tone that she has taken since so you know, so take me through this sort of historical

02:01:51.120 --> 02:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: shift and what's happening here.

02:01:53.440 --> 02:02:03.920
[Guest 1]: So in the last 20 years, a lot has changed. But if we go back to the 2000s, at this time,

02:02:03.920 --> 02:02:11.000
[Guest 1]: Deng's philosophy of hide your capabilities and bide your time is still very important

02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:18.560
[Guest 1]: for Chinese foreign policy. Beijing has made a pragmatic accommodations and is learning

02:02:18.560 --> 02:02:25.400
[Guest 1]: to live with the hegemon, which is the United States. And so policy adjustments are made

02:02:25.400 --> 02:02:36.680
[Guest 1]: according to this reality. What happens in 2001 is 9-11, US is now concentrating all

02:02:36.680 --> 02:02:44.640
[Guest 1]: of its efforts to against international terrorism and becomes obsessed with Iraq. And this gives

02:02:44.640 --> 02:02:50.720
[Guest 1]: China somewhat of a window to start being assertive, and to be a little more vocal about

02:02:50.720 --> 02:02:56.400
[Guest 1]: its interests, which it hadn't been doing so far, at least internationally. And, you

02:02:56.400 --> 02:03:03.920
[Guest 1]: know, China uses the 2000s to signal its intent as a rising power and what are these aspirations,

02:03:03.920 --> 02:03:11.640
[Guest 1]: the Chinese leadership slowly includes more and more controversial issues and expands

02:03:11.640 --> 02:03:18.920
[Guest 1]: this list of China's core interests. So the pursuit of foreign policy becomes this, we

02:03:18.920 --> 02:03:24.600
[Guest 1]: are just China is just pursuing its core interests, and it becomes a little more assertive. So

02:03:24.600 --> 02:03:31.960
[Guest 1]: you have the South China Sea being mentioned, territorial disputes with Japan coming up

02:03:31.960 --> 02:03:38.800
[Guest 1]: being mentioned. There are certain things being talked about with the Southeast Asian

02:03:38.800 --> 02:03:48.760
[Guest 1]: countries, etc. And so China is growing increasingly confident. And unfortunately, for China, there's

02:03:48.760 --> 02:03:56.800
[Guest 1]: a moment of frustration with the 2008 economic meltdown. So after the 2008 economic meltdown,

02:03:56.800 --> 02:04:02.000
[Guest 1]: China has to calibrate all of its efforts and ensure the socioeconomic makeup of China

02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:10.880
[Guest 1]: is not damaged significantly. And suddenly, it has to sort of balance wanting to be a

02:04:10.880 --> 02:04:18.800
[Guest 1]: great power, but also, you know, being responsible for towards its domestic audience. So it's

02:04:18.800 --> 02:04:25.480
[Guest 1]: in this, under Hu Jintao, China is in this middle state where it wants to, you know,

02:04:25.480 --> 02:04:29.760
[Guest 1]: eat at the table with the big kids, it's ready to do that. But also, there's a lot of stuff

02:04:29.760 --> 02:04:35.080
[Guest 1]: happening back home that it needs to pay attention to. And there are questions about whether

02:04:35.080 --> 02:04:42.120
[Guest 1]: China is ready to be, to take on the responsibilities of being a world power.

02:04:42.120 --> 02:04:45.920
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you know, you refer to those years as a middle state, you know,

02:04:45.920 --> 02:04:50.000
[Amit Varma]: the middle state of the Middle Kingdom, that could be the title of your first book. And

02:04:50.000 --> 02:04:54.600
[Amit Varma]: that also then seems to indicate that there is a transition happening here, that you have

02:04:54.600 --> 02:05:00.480
[Amit Varma]: a China, which is kind of, it's a rising power, it's asserting itself, it's looking at, you

02:05:00.480 --> 02:05:05.480
[Amit Varma]: know, itself vis-a-vis the US. And then gradually, what happens is you have the 2008 shift and

02:05:05.480 --> 02:05:09.400
[Amit Varma]: China's, you know, you know, telling the US that, you know, what the hell we were following

02:05:09.400 --> 02:05:13.880
[Amit Varma]: you and, you know, what is this that you've done? And, and then under Xi, you have this

02:05:13.880 --> 02:05:18.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of a much greater assertiveness where like, would it be fair to say then that this

02:05:18.800 --> 02:05:23.000
[Amit Varma]: is no longer a middle state? Now, China said that, okay, we have arrived and we are going

02:05:23.000 --> 02:05:28.560
[Amit Varma]: to compete with everybody. And we are going to cock a snooker to you. And, you know, we

02:05:28.560 --> 02:05:32.880
[Amit Varma]: are taking our place. Is it fair to say that that's the change in approach that has happened?

02:05:32.880 --> 02:05:41.640
[Guest 1]: So one of the things that changed with Xi coming to power is earlier, while China was

02:05:41.640 --> 02:05:47.600
[Guest 1]: being assertive, there was not a very strong link between its global power aspirations

02:05:47.600 --> 02:05:56.360
[Guest 1]: and what it was doing towards achieving them. That's what Xi has been able to do very successfully.

02:05:56.360 --> 02:06:03.160
[Guest 1]: And there's a very decisive leadership style that he follows. And also, like when you think

02:06:03.160 --> 02:06:08.320
[Guest 1]: of Xi coming to power, the first few things that come to your mind are the anti-corruption

02:06:08.320 --> 02:06:16.680
[Guest 1]: campaign that he ran, President for Life. But there has been a very calculated and gradual

02:06:16.680 --> 02:06:24.120
[Guest 1]: move that has been facilitated by events that took place in the 2000s, which are allowing

02:06:24.120 --> 02:06:33.760
[Guest 1]: Xi to sort of reap the benefits of an assertive China in the international stage. Robert Blackwell

02:06:33.760 --> 02:06:40.240
[Guest 1]: and Kurt Campbell, when they write about Xi's foreign policy, say that one of the things

02:06:40.240 --> 02:06:45.760
[Guest 1]: that make him different or this foreign policy different is, this phase of foreign policy

02:06:45.760 --> 02:06:52.320
[Guest 1]: different is Xi's willingness to use every instrument of statecraft, from military assets

02:06:52.320 --> 02:06:59.240
[Guest 1]: to geo-economic intimidation, as well as economic rewards, which we see in the form of the Belt

02:06:59.240 --> 02:07:07.160
[Guest 1]: and Road Initiative, to pursue the geopolitical objectives that China has. And I would also

02:07:07.160 --> 02:07:13.920
[Guest 1]: like to point out that Xi's policies exhibit a continuity. So a lot of scholars argue that

02:07:13.920 --> 02:07:22.200
[Guest 1]: this is new and it's different, yes, but it's not new. It's not unexpected. There is a continuity.

02:07:22.200 --> 02:07:28.920
[Guest 1]: It's just an increase in assertiveness on, say, territorial matters and in the East China

02:07:28.920 --> 02:07:35.680
[Guest 1]: Sea and South China Sea. But Deng's high-deal capabilities and by-deal time have naturally

02:07:35.680 --> 02:07:43.960
[Guest 1]: expired now. This is the right moment. Xi happens to be in the moment. If there was

02:07:43.960 --> 02:07:48.160
[Guest 1]: anyone else, the results would probably have been the same.

02:07:48.160 --> 02:07:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so that kind of repudiating the great man theory of history and saying that this

02:07:52.880 --> 02:07:57.960
[Amit Varma]: is how foreign policy and geopolitics was evolving anyway. And what's also interesting

02:07:57.960 --> 02:08:04.760
[Amit Varma]: in the last few years is that just in terms of coherence of geopolitical policy, America

02:08:04.760 --> 02:08:09.240
[Amit Varma]: has completely fallen apart with Trump at the helm and you have all these insane trade

02:08:09.240 --> 02:08:14.760
[Amit Varma]: wars, which would have been unforeseeable, I think, years ago, because they just make

02:08:14.760 --> 02:08:19.320
[Amit Varma]: absolutely no sense. It's a negative-sum game against the world. And at the same time, it

02:08:19.320 --> 02:08:25.280
[Amit Varma]: seems to me that what China has done is, you know, very focused, very cogent in terms of,

02:08:25.280 --> 02:08:28.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, the Belt and Road, which in fact, I'll ask you to kind of expand on because

02:08:28.880 --> 02:08:35.960
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me to be a very good sort of illustration of how they are using their economic power

02:08:35.960 --> 02:08:41.240
[Amit Varma]: to enhance their standing in the world and their influence over other countries.

02:08:41.240 --> 02:08:45.200
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know, Belt and Road and what's happening there. And it

02:08:45.200 --> 02:08:49.760
[Amit Varma]: also seems to me, and tell me if you guys agree with it, that, you know, Indian foreign

02:08:49.760 --> 02:08:53.920
[Amit Varma]: policy towards China doesn't, or towards the region, doesn't seem to have any of the same

02:08:53.920 --> 02:09:00.240
[Amit Varma]: cogency, where we, you know, we are following the reflexive patterns of the past, in a sense,

02:09:00.240 --> 02:09:05.200
[Amit Varma]: and doing the same old, same old, while China actually has, like, a focused vision on how

02:09:05.200 --> 02:09:09.760
[Amit Varma]: to deal with the region and how to deal with India. Hamsri, would you say that that's...

02:09:09.760 --> 02:09:15.400
[Guest 2]: Okay, this is a couple of different things at play, right? What I wanted to point out

02:09:15.400 --> 02:09:19.760
[Guest 2]: earlier to you, Amit, is that you talked about how US foreign policy with Trump at the helm

02:09:19.760 --> 02:09:23.960
[Guest 2]: seems to be falling apart. And I think one important thing in what Shivani was talking

02:09:23.960 --> 02:09:31.080
[Guest 2]: about is also other countries' reactions to China, right? And Hu Jintao, and like much

02:09:31.080 --> 02:09:37.040
[Guest 2]: of Chinese foreign policy in the 2000s, is devoted in telling people that China is going

02:09:37.040 --> 02:09:42.840
[Guest 2]: to rise peacefully, that China is not a hegemonic power, like the United States or any other

02:09:42.840 --> 02:09:48.080
[Guest 2]: imperialist country, because China has gone through, you know, the century of humiliation

02:09:48.080 --> 02:09:52.320
[Guest 2]: and has emerged to the other side. So their rise is not going to be the rise of any other

02:09:52.320 --> 02:10:02.160
[Guest 2]: country. But what happens with the 2008 crisis? And 2008 is also important, at least in Beijing's

02:10:02.160 --> 02:10:08.040
[Guest 2]: history, it sees it as important because 2008 is the year that Beijing hosts the Olympics,

02:10:08.040 --> 02:10:13.920
[Guest 2]: right? And this is supposed to really mark the year that China arrives. And I think what

02:10:13.920 --> 02:10:20.040
[Guest 2]: happens around this time, 2010-11, when Obama comes to power, you have Hillary Clinton talking

02:10:20.040 --> 02:10:26.720
[Guest 2]: about the Asian century, you have a lot of people across Australia and Singapore starting

02:10:26.720 --> 02:10:34.320
[Guest 2]: to talk about the Indo-Pacific century. And the reason why the Asia-Pacific, the Indo-Pacific

02:10:34.320 --> 02:10:40.320
[Guest 2]: really come into parlance and really come into the spotlight is because India, and to

02:10:40.320 --> 02:10:49.880
[Guest 2]: a greater extent China, at that time faced fewer effects of the 2008 crisis. And this

02:10:49.880 --> 02:10:56.840
[Guest 2]: is the point where you have a lot of reform that is being called for, right? This is when

02:10:56.840 --> 02:11:03.880
[Guest 2]: BRICS and the AIIB and all of these ideas really come to the fore, or the G20, because

02:11:03.880 --> 02:11:10.520
[Guest 2]: now it's being seen as, oh, the world is no longer just the US and perhaps Russia. It's

02:11:10.520 --> 02:11:16.400
[Guest 2]: all of these smaller countries in Asia that are going to take over. And I guess over the

02:11:16.400 --> 02:11:21.720
[Guest 2]: last decade, we've seen that change as well with Xi. And I think what Shivani's pointed

02:11:21.720 --> 02:11:27.640
[Guest 2]: out is very, very important with respect to how assertive that Xi is being. But I would

02:11:27.640 --> 02:11:34.280
[Guest 2]: say that there's often a fallacy, Amit, that when you're outside China, what China is doing

02:11:34.280 --> 02:11:41.440
[Guest 2]: seems to be like a concerted effort, that they have a vision, that they know what they're

02:11:41.440 --> 02:11:47.480
[Guest 2]: doing. And I think, for the most part, they don't. I'm not going to discount what China

02:11:47.480 --> 02:11:53.920
[Guest 2]: is doing. But I think that this is part of Chinese strategy, that they want to convince

02:11:53.920 --> 02:11:59.600
[Guest 2]: the world that they do have a vision for it, that all of this is going towards the great

02:11:59.600 --> 02:12:06.480
[Guest 2]: socialist society, whatever that might be, right? And I would really, you know, question

02:12:06.480 --> 02:12:14.240
[Guest 2]: our biases in thinking about all of China's foreign policy as following a single file

02:12:14.240 --> 02:12:20.240
[Guest 2]: narrative in that sense. But that does not mean that India is not middling through its

02:12:20.240 --> 02:12:24.800
[Guest 2]: foreign policy in the neighborhood. Shivani would be a better person to talk about that.

02:12:24.800 --> 02:12:32.360
[Guest 2]: But I do believe that perhaps Indian foreign policy with China is still reckoning how to

02:12:32.360 --> 02:12:39.600
[Guest 2]: deal with this country that a decade ago we were being compared to, but not really anymore,

02:12:39.600 --> 02:12:46.200
[Guest 2]: right? So it's clear that the gap that India and China had at one particular time has now

02:12:46.200 --> 02:12:52.960
[Guest 2]: widened to the point that China is definitely a player who you can't ignore on the world

02:12:52.960 --> 02:12:59.560
[Guest 2]: stage. Whereas India, perhaps you can still ignore it on the global stage. Shivani, what

02:12:59.560 --> 02:13:07.520
[Guest 1]: do you think about the neighborhood? So to your point about how India is dealing with

02:13:07.520 --> 02:13:13.120
[Guest 1]: China, I think I completely agree. Both sides are trying to figure out how to cope with

02:13:13.120 --> 02:13:20.880
[Guest 1]: the other. There is a significant power asymmetry between the two. I think there is an acknowledgement

02:13:20.880 --> 02:13:27.720
[Guest 1]: of that existing. Unless India is able to catch up with the economic development and

02:13:27.720 --> 02:13:37.440
[Guest 1]: growth that China is seeing, that power asymmetry is going to exist. That said, how India is

02:13:37.440 --> 02:13:44.160
[Guest 1]: approaching China is trying to see what are the issues where India and China can cooperate,

02:13:44.160 --> 02:13:52.560
[Guest 1]: what are issues that they will always have competition or conflict in, and what are some

02:13:52.560 --> 02:13:58.320
[Guest 1]: of the areas where they will just coexist. That seems to be my understanding. Shivani,

02:13:58.320 --> 02:14:04.000
[Guest 2]: I was just thinking while you were talking about this. I'm not sure India will ever be

02:14:04.000 --> 02:14:12.080
[Guest 2]: able to catch up with China in that sense. The Chinese style of growth is simply not

02:14:12.080 --> 02:14:18.720
[Guest 2]: possible here. And one of the reasons why I say that is because China doesn't have to

02:14:18.720 --> 02:14:23.680
[Guest 2]: ever worry about things like land acquisition, because there is no concept of property rights.

02:14:23.680 --> 02:14:29.360
[Guest 2]: So if your land gets taken over by the government, oh, too bad. Here is a payout that the government

02:14:29.360 --> 02:14:35.240
[Guest 2]: might or might not award you. And that's it. Whereas in India, if you look at development

02:14:35.240 --> 02:14:39.880
[Guest 2]: projects or something like that, which often gets talked about, with the one belt, one

02:14:39.880 --> 02:14:45.640
[Guest 2]: road, particularly in South Asia, there's often a lot that's talked about about, oh,

02:14:45.640 --> 02:14:51.760
[Guest 2]: India doesn't do these projects really quickly. And if you look at a lot of these projects,

02:14:51.760 --> 02:14:55.600
[Guest 2]: particularly in the neighborhood and even developmental projects within India, land

02:14:55.600 --> 02:15:02.280
[Guest 2]: acquisition is a huge problem in any society which is not centralized or which the government

02:15:02.280 --> 02:15:06.920
[Amit Varma]: does not play a huge hand in. But you know, Hamsini, I'll just say that that's just one

02:15:06.920 --> 02:15:10.960
[Amit Varma]: aspect of I agree with you, we'll never catch up with them. The reason for that, that not

02:15:10.960 --> 02:15:17.280
[Amit Varma]: just is that China is too authoritarian, but also that India is too authoritarian in another

02:15:17.280 --> 02:15:22.560
[Amit Varma]: direction. China is too authoritarian in the direction of sort of, you know, all of the

02:15:22.560 --> 02:15:26.400
[Amit Varma]: things that you pointed out that there is no friction between getting things done, so

02:15:26.400 --> 02:15:31.920
[Amit Varma]: to say, India is too authoritarian in the way of, in the sense of standing in the way

02:15:31.920 --> 02:15:38.320
[Amit Varma]: of free markets, you know, starting from Nehru soft socialism to Indira Gandhi and to Modi

02:15:38.320 --> 02:15:44.800
[Amit Varma]: today, where, you know, given the fact that, given our population, which was a great strength,

02:15:44.800 --> 02:15:50.360
[Amit Varma]: we, you know, we could have dominated labor intensive manufacturing from the 70s onwards,

02:15:50.360 --> 02:15:55.400
[Amit Varma]: before China got into the game, and got serious about it. And we missed all of those opportunities.

02:15:55.400 --> 02:16:00.560
[Amit Varma]: So while I agree with you that we won't catch up with them, it's not just because they are

02:16:00.560 --> 02:16:05.400
[Amit Varma]: doing something wrong, and we can't do that wrong thing, we are also messing up really

02:16:05.400 --> 02:16:09.360
[Amit Varma]: massively in terms of the economy. The other sort of, you know, when you were talking earlier

02:16:09.360 --> 02:16:13.680
[Amit Varma]: about how we can often, you know, commit the narrative fallacy, I think, though you're

02:16:13.680 --> 02:16:18.800
[Amit Varma]: in use those words, and assume that hey, China has a cogent vision, and they don't necessarily

02:16:18.800 --> 02:16:23.000
[Amit Varma]: do and it was sort of interesting that, you know, to my mind, firstly, if you have a vision

02:16:23.000 --> 02:16:27.240
[Amit Varma]: for communicating what your vision should be, then you could argue that you actually

02:16:27.240 --> 02:16:33.880
[Amit Varma]: do have a vision. And, and secondly, the thing is that even if you, regardless of what your

02:16:33.880 --> 02:16:39.440
[Amit Varma]: intent or vision might be, if your actions are cogent and moving in a certain direction,

02:16:39.440 --> 02:16:44.240
[Amit Varma]: and it seems to the outsider that you do have a vision, then in a de facto sense, it doesn't

02:16:44.240 --> 02:16:49.040
[Amit Varma]: really make a difference of what your original intent was. So I'll go back to the question

02:16:49.040 --> 02:16:53.400
[Amit Varma]: that I kind of asked earlier about now, you know, for those of my listeners were kind

02:16:53.400 --> 02:16:58.520
[Amit Varma]: of not aware of the belt and road initiative, and what a big deal it is in geopolitical

02:16:58.520 --> 02:17:03.560
[Amit Varma]: terms. And, you know, how it is both changing the game and a reflection of how much the

02:17:03.560 --> 02:17:08.520
[Amit Varma]: game has changed. You know, Shibani, would you like to chat a little bit about that?

02:17:08.520 --> 02:17:17.640
[Guest 1]: The Belt and Road Initiative, if you break it down to simple terms is a trade network

02:17:17.640 --> 02:17:26.760
[Guest 1]: that spreads across the entire world, allowing China access to a lot of markets, but also

02:17:26.760 --> 02:17:33.800
[Guest 1]: giving it opportunities in terms of the BRI thing. So it's a trade network giving China

02:17:33.800 --> 02:17:40.200
[Guest 1]: access to new markets across the world. It is a very important foreign policy initiative

02:17:40.200 --> 02:17:49.320
[Guest 1]: of the Chinese government. And what you see, India is not on board with the BRI. And that's

02:17:49.320 --> 02:17:55.160
[Guest 1]: because it feels that it's a little imprudent. It doesn't want to give China the kind of

02:17:55.160 --> 02:18:03.880
[Guest 1]: control that BRI agreements sort of allow for. And we see that increasingly in the Indian

02:18:03.880 --> 02:18:11.000
[Guest 1]: subcontinent, a lot of states, including Pakistan, are a part of the BRI. And that is adding

02:18:11.000 --> 02:18:15.000
[Guest 1]: to the insecurity that India feels towards China.

02:18:15.000 --> 02:18:19.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And there is also, you know, a dual sense of BRI where one is that, look, it's

02:18:19.800 --> 02:18:24.200
[Amit Varma]: a trade network and it's positive some, but there is also the fear that they are sort

02:18:24.200 --> 02:18:29.160
[Amit Varma]: of building these dependencies so that all of these nations, including Pakistan and nations

02:18:29.160 --> 02:18:35.080
[Amit Varma]: in the region sort of become more and more dependent on China and kind of have to listen

02:18:35.080 --> 02:18:38.920
[Amit Varma]: to them. And what is India's approach to this? And what should be India's approach to this?

02:18:39.560 --> 02:18:43.480
[Guest 2]: Just a couple of things. So the one belt, one road by Shivani is right in saying that,

02:18:43.480 --> 02:18:47.800
[Guest 2]: you know, it's exploring new markets. And this is why I was saying that a lot of this

02:18:47.800 --> 02:18:53.640
[Guest 2]: is the narrative fallacy or even a confirmation bias, Amit, is because the Belt and Road now

02:18:53.640 --> 02:18:58.840
[Guest 2]: includes projects that were started in the nineties, you know, and it just subsumes a

02:18:58.840 --> 02:19:05.400
[Guest 2]: lot of these projects under what was launched three, four years ago. And, you know, repackages

02:19:05.400 --> 02:19:08.120
[Guest 2]: all of this under nice new branding.

02:19:08.120 --> 02:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: You're making she sound like Modi ji now. Modi she.

02:19:13.720 --> 02:19:18.920
[Guest 2]: No, but it is what it is in the sense that a lot of the projects that are now claimed

02:19:18.920 --> 02:19:23.240
[Guest 2]: by the Belt and Road didn't start out as Belt and Road projects. They just started out as

02:19:23.240 --> 02:19:29.720
[Guest 2]: development projects and then became part of the Belt and Road. And I agree with Shivani

02:19:29.720 --> 02:19:34.360
[Guest 2]: that earlier we were talking about Xi's assertiveness and the Belt and Road really

02:19:34.360 --> 02:19:41.800
[Guest 2]: fits into sort of China's giant strategy, perhaps. But a lot of things really don't

02:19:41.800 --> 02:19:47.240
[Guest 2]: add up for it. And you can see it just in the way that the Belt and Road unfolds. Right.

02:19:47.240 --> 02:19:55.320
[Guest 2]: I was at an overland port in Chengdu, near Chengdu, which is supposed to be where a train

02:19:55.320 --> 02:20:01.960
[Guest 2]: starts from Chengdu and goes all the way up to Poland. Right. And it was very interesting

02:20:01.960 --> 02:20:07.080
[Guest 2]: to be there also because when I was there, we noticed that Nepal was not part of the

02:20:07.080 --> 02:20:12.840
[Guest 2]: world map. Only it was indicated as part of China. Borders were wrong. And a lot of people

02:20:12.840 --> 02:20:17.400
[Guest 2]: raised objections to what was happening. And to my mind, I would just think that, you know,

02:20:17.400 --> 02:20:21.480
[Guest 2]: if you're starting an international project that's communicating your vision to the world,

02:20:22.280 --> 02:20:29.320
[Guest 2]: you wouldn't want to offend a small country that is already very easily offended. So anyway,

02:20:29.320 --> 02:20:35.400
[Guest 2]: that was sort of just my tangential experience into what the BRI could sometimes look like

02:20:35.400 --> 02:20:43.640
[Guest 2]: on the ground. But I think one of India's reasons for staying away from the BRI is a very real

02:20:43.640 --> 02:20:49.880
[Guest 2]: issue of sovereignty. Now, the biggest project off the Belt and Road is the China-Pakistan

02:20:49.880 --> 02:20:55.480
[Guest 2]: Economic Corridor. And this is a corridor that passes from China through Xinjiang,

02:20:55.480 --> 02:21:00.920
[Guest 2]: through the Pakistan-occupied Kashmir border, all the way down to Gwadar. So this is not just

02:21:00.920 --> 02:21:06.600
[Guest 2]: a highway. This is also a port. These are pipelines, electricity grids, internet,

02:21:06.600 --> 02:21:12.920
[Guest 2]: fiber optic cables, anything and everything that you can think of has come under this project.

02:21:14.040 --> 02:21:20.520
[Guest 2]: And why India objects to it is because at the end of the day, India does not accept that the

02:21:20.520 --> 02:21:25.960
[Guest 2]: China-Pakistan border is valid because India still believes that this goes against India's

02:21:25.960 --> 02:21:31.240
[Guest 2]: sovereignty. And that is the main reason why India cites, at least that's the main reason

02:21:31.240 --> 02:21:37.000
[Guest 2]: that India cites for not being part of the Belt and Road Initiative. China has tried to get India

02:21:37.000 --> 02:21:44.200
[Guest 2]: to be part of the Belt and Road Initiative for many years. And I honestly, particularly now,

02:21:44.200 --> 02:21:50.440
[Guest 2]: don't see that happening because the Indian government has recently been announcing that

02:21:50.440 --> 02:21:54.680
[Guest 2]: all Chinese investments are going to come under additional scrutiny. About a month ago,

02:21:54.680 --> 02:22:00.440
[Guest 2]: the Ministry of Corporate Affairs actually passed a new law which said that some sort of Chinese

02:22:00.440 --> 02:22:04.840
[Guest 2]: investments were going to come under additional scrutiny. And we know that bureaucracy is a pain.

02:22:04.840 --> 02:22:11.080
[Guest 2]: So a lot of things are happening, at least to indicate that China, that India does not

02:22:11.800 --> 02:22:17.560
[Guest 2]: definitely want to be part of the Belt and Road Initiative. And I think that is something that

02:22:17.560 --> 02:22:20.760
[Guest 2]: is set to continue. This is at least my reading of the Belt and Road.

02:22:20.760 --> 02:22:25.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, coming back to the present time, and listeners have kind of stuck with this episode

02:22:25.160 --> 02:22:31.160
[Amit Varma]: for so long, wondering that, but what about the Galwan Valley? Why did they attack us now?

02:22:31.160 --> 02:22:35.960
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, give me give me a sense of what is China thinking now? Like, of course, they do

02:22:35.960 --> 02:22:40.040
[Amit Varma]: things when the rest of the world is distracted, as we know, from the 62 war itself, because the

02:22:40.040 --> 02:22:45.960
[Amit Varma]: Cuban Missile Crisis is going on. And yeah, okay, the big boys are busy. And let's, you know,

02:22:45.960 --> 02:22:50.840
[Amit Varma]: the dip tower mamla with India in the meantime. But now you would imagine, you know, the whole

02:22:50.840 --> 02:22:56.840
[Amit Varma]: world is kind of struggling with the pandemic, including India. So what is China's game here?

02:22:56.840 --> 02:23:02.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, it would seem to me that whatever little gains that you want to make in terms of

02:23:02.120 --> 02:23:07.960
[Amit Varma]: borders, you know, minute gains in territory at best, they don't have imperialistic ambitions.

02:23:07.960 --> 02:23:10.760
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so what's going on? What's what's happening?

02:23:10.760 --> 02:23:17.800
[Guest 2]: So my reading of the current crisis and what's happening is that, you know,

02:23:17.800 --> 02:23:22.040
[Guest 2]: through this whole podcast, I also spoke about this when we were discussing the 1980s,

02:23:22.040 --> 02:23:29.240
[Guest 2]: that China wanted to separate the issue of border and other things that we could have in common.

02:23:29.240 --> 02:23:33.240
[Guest 2]: And that's sort of the pattern that our cooperation over the last 20 years has formed,

02:23:33.240 --> 02:23:37.160
[Guest 2]: right? Particularly in the last couple of years, you have informal summits that are happening,

02:23:37.160 --> 02:23:44.920
[Guest 2]: you have more trade and so on. But with the current crisis, India is the one that's keen

02:23:44.920 --> 02:23:50.600
[Guest 2]: for the border to be resolved. Because this, at the end of the day, is something that

02:23:50.600 --> 02:23:56.280
[Guest 2]: occupies Indian imagination a lot. And this is India's largest border. So it's no wonder that

02:23:56.280 --> 02:24:01.160
[Guest 2]: India, that it's India's largest occupation, right? For the Chinese, on the other hand,

02:24:01.160 --> 02:24:06.040
[Guest 2]: this is something that they've shown in the past in the South China Sea as well,

02:24:06.040 --> 02:24:12.440
[Guest 2]: is that they're very content to play the long game in this, you know, to construct a couple

02:24:12.440 --> 02:24:15.960
[Guest 2]: of small islands, someone will protest, they will retreat, and then they will construct a

02:24:15.960 --> 02:24:21.400
[Guest 2]: couple of more islands, someone will protest until the status quo is changed. So I think,

02:24:21.400 --> 02:24:26.680
[Guest 2]: at least my reading of what is happening currently is that we spoke about M. Taylor

02:24:26.680 --> 02:24:32.920
[Guest 2]: Francis in the first half of the episode, and his thesis that China is more willing

02:24:32.920 --> 02:24:39.800
[Guest 2]: to compromise when there is an internal crisis, and more willing to go head to head on over a

02:24:39.800 --> 02:24:45.480
[Guest 2]: confrontation whenever there's an external crisis. And I think that is particularly telling now.

02:24:46.600 --> 02:24:51.880
[Guest 2]: I think China feels that the world is distracted enough, which is why you have a national security

02:24:51.880 --> 02:24:57.640
[Guest 2]: law that is being passed in Hong Kong. It is why you have some tensions with Vietnam in the South

02:24:57.640 --> 02:25:06.120
[Guest 2]: China Sea. The other thing that I think is quite important to remember is that when India made

02:25:06.120 --> 02:25:12.280
[Guest 2]: Ladakh a Union Territory last year, China again registered protests, like we'd spoken about

02:25:12.280 --> 02:25:21.320
[Guest 2]: multiple times. And this really seems to have pushed China's buttons somewhere. And so this

02:25:21.320 --> 02:25:28.200
[Guest 2]: aggression could also be a reaction of what happened with Kashmir, and the abrogation of

02:25:28.200 --> 02:25:34.760
[Guest 1]: treason. Hamsini made some really important point about China playing the long game. And I

02:25:34.760 --> 02:25:43.160
[Guest 1]: completely agree with that. The sort of scuffles and minor conflicts along the LAC are not something

02:25:43.160 --> 02:25:51.240
[Guest 1]: new. Even if we look back just the last decade, this is sort of status quo for both India and

02:25:51.240 --> 02:25:59.240
[Guest 1]: China. There'll be like an occasional crossfire and stuff like that. The public claim over Galwan

02:25:59.240 --> 02:26:07.480
[Guest 1]: Valley is new, but the territorial dispute as we have discussed isn't. And I would also agree with

02:26:07.480 --> 02:26:15.000
[Guest 1]: Hamsini that it's not just China taking an assertive position against India. There are other

02:26:15.000 --> 02:26:20.440
[Guest 1]: conflicts that it's bringing up. Taiwan, Hong Kong, all of these are in the news again. It's

02:26:20.440 --> 02:26:25.320
[Guest 1]: all happening simultaneously. What Hamsini spoke about is one school of thought that

02:26:25.880 --> 02:26:32.440
[Guest 1]: this is opportunism. The world is distracted by the coronavirus. So China is just looking at this

02:26:32.440 --> 02:26:37.960
[Guest 1]: as a chance to create some trouble because governments are distracted with a public health emergency.

02:26:37.960 --> 02:26:44.920
[Guest 1]: The other argument is that it's again acting out of deep insecurity, and that it's just a

02:26:44.920 --> 02:26:52.200
[Guest 1]: continuation of the strategic objectives that China has. It just seems like the timing of it

02:26:52.200 --> 02:27:01.320
[Guest 1]: is extraordinary because we have a pandemic. But for China, regardless of that, it's continuing on

02:27:01.320 --> 02:27:08.280
[Guest 1]: its sort of... So those are the two broad positions that people are taking about this.

02:27:09.000 --> 02:27:17.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah. So two points that Hamsini mentioned about the BRI that I wanted to add to. First is that

02:27:18.600 --> 02:27:24.600
[Guest 1]: not everything is going well with the Belt and Road Initiative. Last month, the Chinese foreign

02:27:24.600 --> 02:27:32.760
[Guest 1]: ministry said that projects under the BRI had suffered significantly during the pandemic

02:27:33.480 --> 02:27:41.400
[Guest 1]: because a lot of the infrastructure development had to be shut down, and it was incurring a

02:27:41.400 --> 02:27:48.680
[Guest 1]: big financial cost. So while they have accepted that this is a huge economic cost for China,

02:27:48.680 --> 02:27:55.160
[Guest 1]: I'd also like to point out a lot of the infrastructure projects that China is investing

02:27:55.160 --> 02:28:01.080
[Guest 1]: in, it is not sure whether it will get the return on the investment that it's making.

02:28:01.640 --> 02:28:08.360
[Guest 1]: There is no guarantee that these projects will bring back all the money, at least all the money

02:28:08.360 --> 02:28:16.680
[Guest 1]: that's going into them. You have the question of Afghanistan. China really wants the BRI to

02:28:16.680 --> 02:28:23.080
[Guest 1]: sort of take off there, but there are concerns about terrorism and the safety of the Chinese

02:28:23.080 --> 02:28:31.400
[Guest 1]: people living, staying in Afghanistan. So it's trying to get Pakistan to sort of mediate that

02:28:31.400 --> 02:28:39.240
[Guest 1]: discussion. And the other point I wanted to make about India's opposition to the BRI based on

02:28:39.240 --> 02:28:45.000
[Guest 1]: sovereignty, of the BRI going against the sovereignty of the country. This is the same

02:28:45.000 --> 02:28:55.000
[Guest 1]: argument that India uses to convince other nations in the Indian subcontinent to be careful of China.

02:28:55.000 --> 02:29:00.040
[Guest 1]: There's constant reminders to both, you know, you keep going back to the Sri Lankan example,

02:29:00.600 --> 02:29:07.400
[Guest 1]: remember the debt trap, remember Hambantota, be careful about what your engagement is like with

02:29:07.400 --> 02:29:15.080
[Guest 1]: China when it comes to the BRI. And we see that sort of Bangladesh is listening. We know that

02:29:15.080 --> 02:29:21.640
[Guest 1]: there was some renegotiation of the loan terms with China. Maldives has also asked for, you know,

02:29:21.640 --> 02:29:27.480
[Guest 1]: renegotiating those terms again. So yeah, those are the two things I had to say.

02:29:27.480 --> 02:29:33.320
[Guest 2]: I think Shibani, one thing that you've raised a very pertinent point is that these countries are

02:29:33.320 --> 02:29:38.760
[Guest 2]: revising terms. And I think, you know, the sort of the good thing about China being in the

02:29:38.760 --> 02:29:43.560
[Guest 2]: neighborhood, and I don't know if we can characterize it as a good thing, but is that

02:29:43.560 --> 02:29:50.120
[Guest 2]: for the first time in a very long time, countries in the Indian subcontinent have an alternative,

02:29:50.120 --> 02:29:56.440
[Guest 2]: right? And what happens with smaller powers is that they generally hedge bigger powers against

02:29:56.440 --> 02:30:02.600
[Guest 2]: each other and then sort of scramble for what's left. And it's perfectly understandable. And I

02:30:02.600 --> 02:30:08.600
[Guest 2]: think a lot of countries are renegotiating the terms of the BRI because they don't want to be

02:30:08.600 --> 02:30:14.600
[Guest 2]: stuck in debt traps. And I think they're very aware of the threats that could come with it.

02:30:14.600 --> 02:30:23.480
[Guest 2]: The other thing I think is that it really betrays the failure that India has in terms of delivering

02:30:23.480 --> 02:30:31.480
[Guest 2]: on some of these projects in the region. And this is also forcing them to revise deals with India.

02:30:31.480 --> 02:30:37.800
[Guest 2]: And I guess this would now then be up to India to provide better projects. And that is something

02:30:37.800 --> 02:30:42.760
[Amit Varma]: that we ought to be able to do. I sort of like you're phrasing here if it's a good thing that

02:30:42.760 --> 02:30:47.320
[Amit Varma]: China is in the neighborhood as if we have an option that a China moved away one day,

02:30:47.320 --> 02:30:51.800
[Amit Varma]: the China is now between us and Canada and let them deal with, you know, the big guy.

02:30:51.800 --> 02:30:56.280
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of a great point that you raised that, you know, it's really a good deal for all

02:30:56.280 --> 02:31:02.120
[Amit Varma]: the smaller nations that both China and India are trying to bangle influence and spend their money

02:31:02.120 --> 02:31:06.840
[Amit Varma]: and kind of doing all of that. And they can play this competition off and they can play India China

02:31:06.840 --> 02:31:11.560
[Amit Varma]: off against each other and some good can come out of it. And because all trade is a positive

02:31:11.560 --> 02:31:17.560
[Amit Varma]: something, it could be good for China and India as well. But is India as focused towards all of

02:31:17.560 --> 02:31:22.600
[Amit Varma]: these like the one of course, you would argue that this is an important lever that we have

02:31:22.600 --> 02:31:29.720
[Amit Varma]: that if we engage more deeply and try to increase our influence among all of these nations,

02:31:29.720 --> 02:31:36.200
[Amit Varma]: where China also wants to play a big role, then that's a sort of a lever we have to keep China

02:31:36.200 --> 02:31:41.560
[Amit Varma]: at bay and to sort of balance that. But my question there is one, are we doing enough of

02:31:41.560 --> 02:31:46.440
[Amit Varma]: that? And two, do we really have like what are the levers that we really have? Because one of

02:31:46.440 --> 02:31:51.480
[Amit Varma]: the things that became obvious in this whole Galwan Valley thing is that regardless of how

02:31:51.480 --> 02:31:57.880
[Amit Varma]: China looks at it, we can't afford for this thing to escalate. Because any kind of war nuclear or

02:31:57.880 --> 02:32:03.240
[Amit Varma]: otherwise, it's just going to be bad for us beyond the point we can't let it escalate. So then the

02:32:03.240 --> 02:32:09.720
[Amit Varma]: question comes up, what are the levers that we have by which we can influence China's behavior?

02:32:11.080 --> 02:32:18.760
[Guest 1]: I would say that India is not doing enough in the neighborhood. And to a certain extent, it just

02:32:18.760 --> 02:32:26.760
[Guest 1]: underestimates the allies that it has right around it. And I say this because the efforts

02:32:26.760 --> 02:32:34.360
[Guest 1]: to build relationships with the neighbors has not been consistent. It's episodic. And I would say

02:32:34.360 --> 02:32:41.320
[Guest 1]: that the states in the neighborhood see India as only if it moves too close to China will India

02:32:41.320 --> 02:32:47.640
[Guest 1]: get involved. Otherwise, India doesn't have a stake in the country, which is very unfortunate.

02:32:47.640 --> 02:32:56.920
[Guest 1]: I think India as a country needs to make consistent efforts to ensure the neighbors that it is a

02:32:56.920 --> 02:33:03.080
[Guest 1]: presence, it is there for support, it is going to balance out the Chinese influence, because

02:33:03.080 --> 02:33:09.320
[Guest 1]: the Chinese influence is also not something that all neighbors are very happy about. Both India

02:33:09.320 --> 02:33:15.800
[Guest 1]: and China seem to sort of interfere with the internal politics of the smaller states. And that

02:33:15.800 --> 02:33:21.560
[Guest 1]: is not appreciated by these countries. But talking about the Indian side, it seems like sometimes

02:33:21.560 --> 02:33:29.400
[Guest 1]: India doesn't care. I can't recall the name, but there was an Indian publication that got

02:33:29.400 --> 02:33:37.160
[Guest 1]: the name of the king of Bhutan wrong. So they used a picture of the current king, but used the name

02:33:37.160 --> 02:33:44.120
[Guest 1]: of his predecessor. And these are small things. I mean, they appear to be small things for India,

02:33:44.120 --> 02:33:51.560
[Guest 1]: but it is a big deal for Bhutan, it is going to impact your relationship. That said, the neighbors

02:33:51.560 --> 02:33:58.680
[Guest 1]: also are very aware of the leverage that they hold, both against India and China. And they're

02:33:58.680 --> 02:34:05.160
[Amit Varma]: not afraid to use it to balance the two. The other part of my question was, what can India do now?

02:34:05.160 --> 02:34:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Like if you put yourself in the Prime Minister's shoes, what are the options he had on the day that

02:34:10.360 --> 02:34:16.120
[Amit Varma]: the news about the Galwan Valley broke? Like, okay, so many of our soldiers have been killed

02:34:16.120 --> 02:34:21.560
[Amit Varma]: by the Chinese. But what can we do? And I guess it's a two part question. One is what can we do

02:34:21.560 --> 02:34:27.720
[Amit Varma]: in terms of controlling sort of the domestic fallout of this, which they are trying to

02:34:27.720 --> 02:34:32.760
[Amit Varma]: sort of manipulate through, where they're trying to sort of build this narrative of Oh, nothing

02:34:33.400 --> 02:34:38.360
[Amit Varma]: but we taught them a lesson at the same time by banning TikTok. But apart from that, what are the

02:34:38.360 --> 02:34:43.080
[Amit Varma]: realistic options that are on the table? What could Modi have done? What can Modi do?

02:34:43.960 --> 02:34:49.640
[Guest 1]: The way I see it is that there is no one right answer to this. There have to be multiple

02:34:49.640 --> 02:34:57.880
[Guest 1]: approaches that have to be used simultaneously as India engages with China. The first is external

02:34:57.880 --> 02:35:06.040
[Guest 1]: balancing, which I think India does well with the bigger powers, but fails to do with the

02:35:06.040 --> 02:35:14.200
[Guest 1]: allies within the neighborhood. So I would say building institutional relationships in the Indian

02:35:14.200 --> 02:35:20.600
[Guest 1]: subcontinent that are not driven just by personalities or, you know, the heads of state,

02:35:21.560 --> 02:35:28.360
[Guest 1]: because that is temporary. But if you are able to establish institutional relationships that

02:35:28.360 --> 02:35:35.560
[Guest 1]: go beyond personalities and administrations, I think that would be more fruitful. And the second

02:35:35.560 --> 02:35:44.680
[Guest 1]: approach, I think, is again, continuous engagement with China. We can't just frown and say,

02:35:45.480 --> 02:35:53.480
[Guest 1]: I'm not going to talk to you. Dialogue has to go on, engagement in areas where you can cooperate

02:35:53.480 --> 02:36:01.960
[Guest 1]: with one another is necessary, because there is an economic dependency that India has with China.

02:36:01.960 --> 02:36:09.480
[Guest 1]: And any move that will harm India economically is, I don't think it makes sense, because

02:36:10.120 --> 02:36:15.720
[Guest 1]: you're trying to prove a point, but you're also harming your own economy. So yeah, I don't think

02:36:15.720 --> 02:36:19.480
[Guest 1]: there has to be engagement, it has to be done in a wise manner.

02:36:19.480 --> 02:36:23.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I think that's what when you know, people use the term economic warfare, they,

02:36:23.080 --> 02:36:27.480
[Amit Varma]: they don't get it that the point is that anything you do against the economy of the other country

02:36:27.480 --> 02:36:31.640
[Amit Varma]: also harms the people of your own country, like, you know, banning Chinese products, for example,

02:36:31.640 --> 02:36:37.080
[Amit Varma]: would actually be hurting your own people more than anything else. So I'm not sure people who

02:36:37.080 --> 02:36:40.920
[Amit Varma]: don't use TikTok much would kind of agree with that.

02:36:42.040 --> 02:36:47.560
[Guest 1]: I'm just going to borrow an analogy from Manoj Kevalramani who wrote this in the Hindustan

02:36:47.560 --> 02:36:53.480
[Guest 1]: Times, he said, if you are going to spit on someone else, make sure you don't cut your own

02:36:53.480 --> 02:36:54.360
[Guest 1]: nose while doing it.

02:36:54.360 --> 02:36:57.960
[Amit Varma]: That's mixing metaphors, actually, Manoj needs to attend my writing class,

02:36:57.960 --> 02:37:03.640
[Amit Varma]: so our final China scholar, but I'm not sure if this particular sentence, I thought it'll

02:37:03.640 --> 02:37:07.800
[Amit Varma]: be something like this, just make sure you aren't so close to him that it bounces back on you,

02:37:07.800 --> 02:37:12.360
[Amit Varma]: which would have been Yeah, but oh my god, why have you put that picture in my head?

02:37:13.960 --> 02:37:18.200
[Guest 2]: You know, in Tamil, we have a saying that says if you throw a stone into the gutter,

02:37:18.200 --> 02:37:19.720
[Guest 2]: it will splash back at you.

02:37:20.600 --> 02:37:21.160
[Amit Varma]: That's better.

02:37:21.160 --> 02:37:26.680
[Guest 2]: Sorry, Manoj. No, so a couple of thoughts on what you were saying on what we could do,

02:37:26.680 --> 02:37:32.360
[Guest 2]: right. And I think this, apart from the policy options that are on the table that I will leave

02:37:32.360 --> 02:37:37.960
[Guest 2]: to our extremely qualified bureaucrats to get to, I think there are some fundamental

02:37:37.960 --> 02:37:42.680
[Guest 2]: institutional problems within the Indian government that we need to address, Amit.

02:37:42.680 --> 02:37:48.840
[Guest 2]: And I think the first is that the economic moves that we're talking about, right,

02:37:48.840 --> 02:37:53.880
[Guest 2]: is I've argued against this app ban for various reasons. And the smallest ones being that,

02:37:53.880 --> 02:37:57.800
[Guest 2]: you know, consumer choice will be limited. And this is going to backfire on India's tech scene,

02:37:57.800 --> 02:38:05.000
[Guest 2]: which desperately needs investments. But the other thing is that India needs to realize that

02:38:06.440 --> 02:38:14.280
[Guest 2]: its whole bargaining power on the world stage comes from its economy. No one wants to deal with

02:38:14.280 --> 02:38:20.200
[Guest 2]: a large poor country, Amit. Those exist. We want to have nothing to do with them. And we cannot

02:38:20.200 --> 02:38:26.600
[Guest 2]: afford to be them. So your economic policy is not fungible as your foreign policy. Your strong

02:38:26.600 --> 02:38:33.400
[Guest 2]: economy needs to be the basis for you to have a strong foreign policy. You know, even with the

02:38:33.400 --> 02:38:38.120
[Guest 2]: coronavirus, there's been so much talk about how global supply chains are going to shift at the

02:38:38.120 --> 02:38:44.840
[Guest 2]: end of this. What has India done to actually take advantage of this shifting of the global supply

02:38:44.840 --> 02:38:50.200
[Guest 2]: chains? We talk about ease of doing business and so on, but I really don't see a lot of that

02:38:50.200 --> 02:38:54.440
[Guest 2]: extending beyond Mumbai and Delhi. And we can see that, you know, countries like Vietnam,

02:38:54.440 --> 02:39:00.200
[Guest 2]: countries like Bangladesh are getting a lot of industries that are now moving out of China.

02:39:00.200 --> 02:39:05.800
[Guest 2]: China, because it is developing, is shifting some of its more labor-intensive industries.

02:39:05.800 --> 02:39:10.600
[Guest 2]: To its poorer regions and to other countries in Southeast Asia. So this is something that at the

02:39:10.600 --> 02:39:15.880
[Guest 2]: end of the day, we should have considered. The other thing that I would say is that, you know,

02:39:15.880 --> 02:39:21.240
[Guest 2]: we talk about India's soft power in terms of Bollywood and yoga. But I remember Brookings

02:39:21.240 --> 02:39:27.880
[Guest 2]: recently having a report out that talks about how South Asian students, not Indian, South Asian,

02:39:27.880 --> 02:39:33.640
[Guest 2]: are now flocking to China. And earlier, a lot of these students would come to India, but we no

02:39:33.640 --> 02:39:41.960
[Guest 2]: longer have globally competitive educational institutions. And even when we do, our society

02:39:41.960 --> 02:39:47.960
[Guest 2]: is xenophobic to students from all around the world. And therefore, India is not an attractive

02:39:47.960 --> 02:39:54.760
[Guest 2]: place to come and stay. I think the other thing is that, you know, we have a lot of

02:39:54.760 --> 02:40:01.720
[Guest 2]: students from all over the world who want to come and stay. I think the other thing is that,

02:40:01.720 --> 02:40:08.120
[Guest 2]: you know, Indians fundamentally want to take a strong line against China. And I understand this.

02:40:08.120 --> 02:40:13.160
[Guest 2]: We should be ready to stand up to a bully at any point in time. We should be prepared

02:40:13.160 --> 02:40:20.920
[Guest 2]: to escalate crises. However, I think we need to fundamentally assess if that is the only line

02:40:20.920 --> 02:40:25.000
[Guest 2]: something with China happens. This is something that I hear that we need to take a strong line

02:40:25.000 --> 02:40:30.840
[Guest 2]: against China. I was actually hearing some intellectuals who were saying we shouldn't

02:40:30.840 --> 02:40:35.800
[Guest 2]: have Indian students who go study in China. And I'm opposed to this for personal reasons as well.

02:40:35.800 --> 02:40:40.760
[Guest 2]: But I think, you know, they were saying if Indian students will study in China, they will not take

02:40:40.760 --> 02:40:47.640
[Guest 2]: a strong line for India. And I think a lot of this goes back to Indian scholarship about China. And

02:40:47.640 --> 02:40:53.800
[Guest 2]: this is something that I'm very passionate about because bread and butter. But we have a fundamental

02:40:53.800 --> 02:41:00.440
[Guest 2]: lack of Indian scholars who are working very deeply with Chinese issues. We have very few

02:41:00.440 --> 02:41:05.960
[Guest 2]: scholars in the country who can speak the language fluently. We have very few scholars who've lived

02:41:05.960 --> 02:41:11.320
[Guest 2]: in China who understand China. Now, I've had a lot of people say, you know, this is foreign policy.

02:41:11.320 --> 02:41:16.520
[Guest 2]: All states are the same. Why do you need to have exposure to China? Why do you need to have to live

02:41:16.520 --> 02:41:21.560
[Guest 2]: there? You know, your foreign policy against China should be the same as your foreign policy towards

02:41:21.560 --> 02:41:28.280
[Guest 2]: South Korea, if that's who you're bordering. I can understand that argument. But I think

02:41:28.280 --> 02:41:37.480
[Guest 2]: that we still have a fundamental lack of primary knowledge about Chinese systemic thinking

02:41:37.480 --> 02:41:45.400
[Guest 2]: and Chinese foreign policy. Everything that our policymakers depend on seem to come from

02:41:45.400 --> 02:41:50.600
[Guest 2]: American scholarship or Western scholarship. And therefore, I would actually argue that this is

02:41:50.600 --> 02:41:57.880
[Guest 2]: where we should be nationalist. We should be more nationalist about having knowledge systems

02:41:57.880 --> 02:42:04.760
[Guest 2]: that would inform our policymakers. So I think when you say what can we do whenever we have a

02:42:04.760 --> 02:42:11.800
[Guest 2]: crisis, we can present our policymakers with better options. And the way we do that is to build

02:42:11.800 --> 02:42:18.120
[Guest 2]: domestic structures and systems of knowledge that provide the best policy solutions.

02:42:18.120 --> 02:42:21.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I'm taking three thoughts away from that. One is, of course, as you said, and I

02:42:21.800 --> 02:42:27.240
[Amit Varma]: completely agree, the importance of economic growth for foreign policy. You know, your ex-colleague

02:42:27.240 --> 02:42:33.240
[Amit Varma]: Nitin Pai once wrote a piece which had the headline, India's best foreign policy is 8%

02:42:33.240 --> 02:42:38.040
[Amit Varma]: economic growth. And I couldn't agree more. And you said it very well when you said that,

02:42:38.040 --> 02:42:43.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, economic policy is not fungible, foreign policy may, but in terms of economics, we just have

02:42:43.480 --> 02:42:49.880
[Amit Varma]: to aim for that kind of growth. And I completely agree with you that homegrown scholarship with

02:42:49.880 --> 02:42:56.040
[Amit Varma]: experience within China is important. Yes, you can look at all states as rational actors and

02:42:56.040 --> 02:43:01.800
[Amit Varma]: therefore draw whatever conclusions you draw from that. But the granularity of your understanding of

02:43:01.800 --> 02:43:07.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, the nuances of how a particular people might think about a particular problem or about

02:43:07.960 --> 02:43:12.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, what the popular imagination within the country is, which will also shape what its

02:43:12.840 --> 02:43:19.560
[Amit Varma]: leaders think and, you know, create the incentives that they respond to, that is also incredibly

02:43:19.560 --> 02:43:25.960
[Amit Varma]: important. And, you know, the third point on which you expressed yourself so strongly, and I agree

02:43:25.960 --> 02:43:32.120
[Amit Varma]: with you is that we need to build intellectual capacity on these matters. I think in a lot of

02:43:32.120 --> 02:43:37.880
[Amit Varma]: matters in our policy, not just foreign policy, but other policy, there is my sense from the outside

02:43:37.880 --> 02:43:43.400
[Amit Varma]: that we are ruled by inertia, that there are these practices of the past, some bad practices, some

02:43:43.400 --> 02:43:48.280
[Amit Varma]: perhaps not so bad, but they just continue out of inertia, because that's the way things have

02:43:48.280 --> 02:43:54.520
[Amit Varma]: always been. And we need to build intellectual capacity on the outside of these institutions.

02:43:54.520 --> 02:43:59.720
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, within our country and engaging deeply with China in this context, so that we

02:43:59.720 --> 02:44:05.560
[Amit Varma]: can take those learnings kind of in a crisis like this. And if we had that intellectual capacity,

02:44:05.560 --> 02:44:11.080
[Amit Varma]: and we see the stirrings of it, among the two fine scholars who are with me on the show right now,

02:44:11.080 --> 02:44:15.640
[Amit Varma]: thought experiment I would post to them, and therefore I will post for you is this, that,

02:44:15.640 --> 02:44:20.360
[Amit Varma]: okay, we are sort of assuming that these are sort of the things that we should do in the long term,

02:44:20.360 --> 02:44:25.720
[Amit Varma]: we should have 8% economic growth, we should have greater engagement with all our countries in the

02:44:25.720 --> 02:44:30.280
[Amit Varma]: region, we should, you know, as Nitin keeps saying, maybe also show some involvement in the

02:44:30.280 --> 02:44:35.400
[Amit Varma]: South China Sea so that that also becomes a lever where, which we can use against China. But the

02:44:35.400 --> 02:44:41.480
[Amit Varma]: thought experiment is that supposing they are far more belligerent, and they want everything now,

02:44:41.480 --> 02:44:45.720
[Amit Varma]: and they want every dispute settled in their favor now, and they are acting with men coming

02:44:45.720 --> 02:44:50.760
[Amit Varma]: across the border and tanks and whatever, supposing you know, that is their approach,

02:44:50.760 --> 02:44:56.440
[Amit Varma]: how are we to handle it? Supposing you know, Mr. Modi does get that communique that they have

02:44:56.440 --> 02:45:02.840
[Amit Varma]: crossed the line of control, and they have said that x area is ours. How are we to, are there

02:45:02.840 --> 02:45:09.960
[Amit Varma]: realistic ways of tackling it? Do we sort of get into a conflict where enormous damage could be

02:45:09.960 --> 02:45:16.120
[Amit Varma]: caused? Do we just roll over and sort of give them what they want? How would you think about that?

02:45:16.120 --> 02:45:21.320
[Guest 2]: So suppose China is more belligerent, suppose they cross the border tomorrow.

02:45:22.760 --> 02:45:27.720
[Guest 2]: I think something that we haven't really discussed a little is the role of nuclear

02:45:27.720 --> 02:45:32.280
[Guest 2]: weapons, right? At the end of the day, India and China are both nuclear weapon states.

02:45:32.280 --> 02:45:40.120
[Guest 2]: And therefore, if there is a war like scenario, there would be a threshold of escalation,

02:45:40.120 --> 02:45:46.440
[Guest 2]: after which one of the countries would choose to go nuclear. Now, theoretically, before this

02:45:46.440 --> 02:45:52.200
[Guest 2]: threshold is reached, a lot more international actors will be concerned that this could lead

02:45:52.200 --> 02:45:58.520
[Guest 2]: to mutual annihilation. And therefore, there will be de-escalation. But I think if there is

02:45:59.080 --> 02:46:07.000
[Guest 2]: aggression from the Chinese in blatantly, you know, marching through India's territory and claiming

02:46:07.000 --> 02:46:14.200
[Guest 2]: large chunks of land, India is not the India of 1962. We can sort of compare militaries and

02:46:14.200 --> 02:46:21.720
[Guest 2]: things like that. But I think India would be in a position where at that point in time, they could

02:46:22.360 --> 02:46:30.520
[Guest 2]: provide a reaction that leads to escalation. What I'm saying is that I think India would be willing

02:46:30.520 --> 02:46:35.720
[Guest 2]: to escalate. And that's a little bit of what was seen in the government crisis as well. And I think

02:46:35.720 --> 02:46:43.400
[Guest 2]: it's important to note that a lot of our military structures do exist and are prepared for

02:46:43.400 --> 02:46:51.880
[Guest 2]: escalation in this manner. But I would, at the end of the day, discount a huge war happening

02:46:51.880 --> 02:46:57.400
[Amit Varma]: because we are nuclear power states. Yeah, I mean, that's assuming both people are rational

02:46:57.400 --> 02:47:02.120
[Amit Varma]: actors and treat each other as rational actors. Because if we sort of go back to game theory in

02:47:02.120 --> 02:47:07.240
[Amit Varma]: the game of chicken, for example, about who is more irrational or who can sort of show themselves

02:47:07.240 --> 02:47:12.360
[Amit Varma]: to be more irrational. And it's clear to all concerned that at some point, Modi has to back

02:47:12.360 --> 02:47:17.960
[Amit Varma]: down. That, you know, if things start escalating, she knows that Modi has to back down at some

02:47:17.960 --> 02:47:24.120
[Amit Varma]: point. There will be more international pressure on India than on China, you know, given the levers

02:47:24.120 --> 02:47:30.120
[Amit Varma]: that other nations have and we are far weaker. And there is sort of this fog of uncertainty about

02:47:30.120 --> 02:47:36.360
[Amit Varma]: how China's actors think and what they will do, at least relative to India. But anyway, maybe I'm

02:47:36.360 --> 02:47:41.320
[Amit Varma]: just analysing a thought experiment too much. But I'm just doing that because it just seems to me

02:47:41.320 --> 02:47:49.000
[Amit Varma]: that anybody in on Modi's seat just has really difficult choices before him. My view is that

02:47:49.000 --> 02:47:58.280
[Guest 1]: should sort of China be aggressive, India will act in a manner that displays its military capability

02:47:58.280 --> 02:48:07.400
[Guest 1]: to take China on, but be careful enough not to escalate. And that's a very fine balance. But I

02:48:07.400 --> 02:48:12.040
[Guest 1]: think that is that is going to be the objective of the Indian side.

02:48:12.840 --> 02:48:14.440
[Amit Varma]: Wasn't that Nehru's forward policy?

02:48:15.400 --> 02:48:22.840
[Guest 1]: Yes, but I don't think India would, the cost of going to war is something that that the Indian

02:48:22.840 --> 02:48:30.280
[Guest 1]: that the Indian side realises, the financial, the social, the political cost of going to war,

02:48:30.280 --> 02:48:37.720
[Guest 1]: which is why it would sort of restrain from escalating. From the Chinese side, I mean,

02:48:37.720 --> 02:48:43.400
[Guest 1]: you were saying that, you know, India would face a lot more international pressure than China would.

02:48:43.400 --> 02:48:51.400
[Guest 1]: But my understanding is that China is not ready to face the isolation that would come from,

02:48:51.400 --> 02:48:58.920
[Guest 1]: you know, such an escalation. And maybe that is one of the considerations that the Chinese side

02:48:58.920 --> 02:48:59.800
[Amit Varma]: will have.

02:48:59.800 --> 02:49:03.400
[Amit Varma]: Realistically, do you think anybody would isolate them? You can't afford to isolate

02:49:03.400 --> 02:49:08.360
[Amit Varma]: yourself from China. I mean, even we haven't done it despite banning a few apps, but we can't really

02:49:08.360 --> 02:49:13.320
[Amit Varma]: do it because otherwise, you know, a lot of our electricity comes from machines made in China.

02:49:13.320 --> 02:49:19.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, Vivek Kaul and I did an episode of Econ Central on this. If Indians want to really

02:49:19.640 --> 02:49:23.320
[Amit Varma]: boycott China, they'll have to stop drinking milk in many places because your dairy production

02:49:23.320 --> 02:49:24.280
[Amit Varma]: equipment comes from there.

02:49:25.000 --> 02:49:28.600
[Guest 2]: Amit, I was actually thinking about this and just because it's a thought experiment, right?

02:49:29.160 --> 02:49:36.200
[Guest 2]: If you look fundamentally at the history of wars across the world, you will see the weaker power

02:49:36.200 --> 02:49:41.480
[Guest 2]: as acting more irrational, right? Like if there was going to be a fight between North and South

02:49:41.480 --> 02:49:46.760
[Guest 2]: Korea, you would expect more pressure on South Korea than on the North, right? And therefore,

02:49:46.760 --> 02:49:52.920
[Guest 2]: I would actually argue that if there is a showdown between India and China, then India can afford to

02:49:52.920 --> 02:49:59.960
[Guest 2]: act more irrational than China. I know that then I'm in a sense arguing for being more irrational

02:49:59.960 --> 02:50:03.720
[Guest 2]: than the Chinese is, you know, essentially going to leave the whole world blind.

02:50:03.720 --> 02:50:08.600
[Amit Varma]: But you can say that with a veil of ignorance, but we know that Modi is in charge. And I don't

02:50:08.600 --> 02:50:13.560
[Amit Varma]: mean this as a knock on Modi, but whoever the Indian Prime Minister is, we know that, you know,

02:50:13.560 --> 02:50:17.720
[Amit Varma]: what Shabani said very wisely is that we have to show our military strength, but not actually

02:50:17.720 --> 02:50:22.760
[Amit Varma]: escalate. Now, the thing is, they know this. They know that no matter what happens, there won't be

02:50:22.760 --> 02:50:28.680
[Amit Varma]: a war, because we have to back down. They know this. It is simply no way. Now, it's a different

02:50:28.680 --> 02:50:34.200
[Amit Varma]: matter that fortunately, China is outside of the thought experiment. They are not quite as

02:50:34.200 --> 02:50:41.400
[Amit Varma]: belligerent. But thinking aloud from my possibly naive view, it would seem to me that they can

02:50:41.400 --> 02:50:46.520
[Guest 2]: basically get away with anything. You know, Amit, in the international system, the strong

02:50:47.080 --> 02:50:58.360
[Guest 2]: will eat and the weak is meat. But again, I'm going to say that just because now during this

02:50:58.360 --> 02:51:04.920
[Guest 2]: thought experiment, we can't come up with definite reasons for what we can do apart from backing

02:51:04.920 --> 02:51:12.600
[Guest 2]: down. Maybe what we need is an extremely crazy Prime Minister who's willing to signal absolute

02:51:12.600 --> 02:51:16.600
[Guest 2]: irrationality. Maybe that is something that our policymakers should consider.

02:51:17.400 --> 02:51:21.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's a thought that struck me the other day that if Yogi Adityanath was PM,

02:51:21.960 --> 02:51:26.600
[Amit Varma]: then the Chinese would have to be more wary. But then the problem is that solves your geopolitical

02:51:26.600 --> 02:51:31.960
[Amit Varma]: problem. But what about your internal domestic governance problem? You know, you'll have

02:51:31.960 --> 02:51:38.360
[Amit Varma]: encounter Raj all over India and not just in UP. But leaving that aside, that was an amusing

02:51:38.360 --> 02:51:44.120
[Amit Varma]: thought experiment. And you have you both of you have given me this fascinating trip through

02:51:44.120 --> 02:51:50.120
[Amit Varma]: history and perspective. And I'll also link all my other episodes on China in the show notes.

02:51:51.000 --> 02:51:55.800
[Amit Varma]: So thank you so much for coming on the show and giving me so much of your time. And before I sort

02:51:55.800 --> 02:52:03.080
[Amit Varma]: of before we wrap it up, you know what I'm going to ask, isn't it, which is the sort of the staple

02:52:03.080 --> 02:52:10.360
[Amit Varma]: question of all my sort of episodes and whatever subjects I do. And I'll turn to Shibani first and

02:52:10.360 --> 02:52:17.320
[Amit Varma]: then Hamsini, which is that if you are to sort of if I ask you to look at the year 2030, as far as

02:52:17.320 --> 02:52:21.960
[Amit Varma]: India China relations are concerned, what's the best case scenario and what's the worst case

02:52:21.960 --> 02:52:35.000
[Guest 1]: scenario? 2030 best case scenario is that both sides that the memory of war is strong on either

02:52:35.000 --> 02:52:45.480
[Guest 1]: side. And that is why they don't enter into war with each other to avoid the cost that war carries

02:52:45.480 --> 02:52:50.360
[Amit Varma]: with it. If the memory of war is strong on both sides, that means there's been a war between now

02:52:50.360 --> 02:52:56.360
[Guest 1]: and then. No, I'm saying from, you know, the history of India and China. Oh, okay. Yeah,

02:52:56.360 --> 02:53:02.520
[Guest 1]: fair enough. That memory from the history of India and China carries forward to that time. And it's

02:53:02.520 --> 02:53:10.360
[Guest 1]: not a new generation that thinks bombing the hell out of the other is the way to go. And what's the

02:53:10.360 --> 02:53:16.120
[Guest 1]: worst case scenario? Worst case scenario is that there's a generation that forgets the cost of

02:53:16.120 --> 02:53:23.000
[Guest 1]: going to war. And I would also think, see, one of the things that I wanted to point out earlier

02:53:23.000 --> 02:53:30.920
[Guest 1]: about nuclear weapons in the India China equation is, while both sides have nuclear weapons, the

02:53:31.640 --> 02:53:38.600
[Guest 1]: relationship in that domain has been stable. The use of nuclear weapons in any conflict between

02:53:38.600 --> 02:53:43.640
[Guest 1]: India and China has not been mentioned. When you compare that with India and Pakistan, where

02:53:43.640 --> 02:53:48.440
[Guest 1]: as soon as there is some sort of conflict, immediately someone somewhere will mention,

02:53:49.000 --> 02:53:58.440
[Guest 1]: we'll use nukes. In 2019, there was talks from the Indian Ministry of Defense that,

02:53:58.440 --> 02:54:05.160
[Guest 1]: you know, India is willing to review its position of no first use of nuclear weapons,

02:54:05.720 --> 02:54:10.840
[Guest 1]: if that is required. And that was in context of what was happening between India and Pakistan

02:54:10.840 --> 02:54:17.080
[Guest 1]: at the time. But with India and China, that's never been the case. India saw China's acquiring

02:54:17.080 --> 02:54:23.880
[Guest 1]: of nuclear weapons as its claim to, you know, being a global power never felt threatened by it.

02:54:24.440 --> 02:54:33.560
[Guest 1]: And China has understood India's, you know, growing nuclear arsenal as security against

02:54:33.560 --> 02:54:39.560
[Guest 1]: Pakistan and that, you know, the insecurity within the Indian subcontinent is what is driving that.

02:54:39.560 --> 02:54:45.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think your worst case scenario is that we end up in a conflict which is brutal for both

02:54:45.320 --> 02:54:50.200
[Amit Varma]: sides, because of a generation that forgot the memories of war, right? That's your...

02:54:51.480 --> 02:54:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Hamsini, you are part of a generation which grew up well after the last war.

02:54:55.960 --> 02:55:00.280
[Amit Varma]: What do you remember? Even I am, in fact.

02:55:01.160 --> 02:55:07.160
[Guest 2]: That's true. I mean, actually, yeah, I would... What are your memories of the narrative around

02:55:07.160 --> 02:55:10.920
[Guest 2]: China when you were growing up, Amit, before I answer my question?

02:55:10.920 --> 02:55:15.480
[Amit Varma]: I have no memories. Yeah, there were narratives around Pakistan all the time,

02:55:15.480 --> 02:55:19.960
[Amit Varma]: and they are still pretty much the same. And thankfully, the narrative around capitalists

02:55:19.960 --> 02:55:25.880
[Amit Varma]: has changed a little bit. They're not all evil. But apart from that, you know, I don't remember

02:55:25.880 --> 02:55:32.920
[Amit Varma]: narratives around the Chinese, but we Indians as a people have always been so xenophobic and racist,

02:55:32.920 --> 02:55:35.240
[Amit Varma]: frankly, but leaving that aside.

02:55:35.240 --> 02:55:42.360
[Guest 2]: Okay. I think, Amit, best case scenario is that the border between India and China

02:55:43.080 --> 02:55:50.680
[Guest 2]: is like the border between Russia and China. And what this essentially means is that the border

02:55:50.680 --> 02:55:55.720
[Guest 2]: is settled. It's resolved amicably, whatever amicably could mean. I'm not going to get into

02:55:55.720 --> 02:56:02.840
[Guest 2]: the nitty gritties of who gave what to whom, but you have a border with border ports. You

02:56:02.840 --> 02:56:10.120
[Guest 2]: can have tourism. You can cross into from one side of the Himalayas to the other and

02:56:10.120 --> 02:56:17.160
[Guest 2]: walk into Yunnan from Arunachal Pradesh. That would be best case scenario for me.

02:56:18.280 --> 02:56:23.880
[Guest 2]: And because I think if you resolve this, then a lot of other things may possibly

02:56:23.880 --> 02:56:29.160
[Guest 2]: take off and take off well. Worst case scenario would obviously be

02:56:29.160 --> 02:56:34.280
[Guest 2]: conflict, but conflict could also lead to the resolution of these borders in some way or the

02:56:34.280 --> 02:56:43.240
[Guest 2]: other, right? I think what I would be very afraid of is an India that wants to catch up with China

02:56:43.240 --> 02:56:50.760
[Guest 2]: that wants to posture aggressively, indulges in, you know, building up its arms and

02:56:50.760 --> 02:56:58.440
[Guest 2]: overdrawing the Indian economy to sort of signal strength. I'm afraid that India would sort of

02:56:58.440 --> 02:57:07.000
[Guest 2]: repeat the mistakes of the Soviet Union in that sense, the Soviet Union of the 80s,

02:57:07.000 --> 02:57:13.640
[Guest 2]: essentially. And that is what I would be even more scared of, because it's very easy for us

02:57:13.640 --> 02:57:19.720
[Guest 2]: to think in terms of foreign policy and what India should do. But I think it's the work at

02:57:19.720 --> 02:57:25.320
[Guest 2]: the background, particularly what's happening with the economy that fundamentally worries me

02:57:25.320 --> 02:57:30.440
[Guest 2]: in a short term 10 year scenario. Yeah. And, you know, unsurprisingly, you have packed in a

02:57:30.440 --> 02:57:37.000
[Amit Varma]: profound thought, which I'll unpack in my own words, which is basically, you know, people often

02:57:37.000 --> 02:57:41.480
[Amit Varma]: look at narrative and reality as a binary, and they will look at a government as a government

02:57:41.480 --> 02:57:46.760
[Amit Varma]: that can construct a narrative that has nothing to do with reality as if it is a harmless thing.

02:57:46.760 --> 02:57:52.680
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, narratives can shape reality. And if we build this narrative where we are this

02:57:52.680 --> 02:57:58.760
[Amit Varma]: macho, aggressive nation state that takes no shit from others, then that narrative could shape our

02:57:58.760 --> 02:58:05.960
[Amit Varma]: reality in ways that might lead to your worst case scenario. Hamsini and Shibani, you've both

02:58:05.960 --> 02:58:11.720
[Amit Varma]: been extremely patient. So thank you for coming on the show and for your time and your insights.

02:58:12.360 --> 02:58:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit. This was a lot of fun.

